<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: 'feminization' means 'humanization' of politics  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton on
Tuesday made one of her strongest pitches to date for putting her
in the Senate because she supports what have become known as
traditional ''women's issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also lashed out at her Republican rival Rick Lazio's
plan to repeal a portion of the federal gas tax as ''a bad deal for
New York and a potential bonanza for the oil companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to about 180 members of a Buffalo-area women's
political club, the first lady said the fate of legalized abortion
could hang in the balance with this year's election. She noted that
the next president could wind up appointing at least two and
possibly four new members of the U.S. Supreme Court, who would be
subject to confirmation by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said she would not vote to confirm any nominee for
the Supreme Court who did not support the Roe v. Wade decision
legalizing abortion in America. Lazio, a Long Island congressman,
has declined to make such a pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we don't understand that Roe v. Wade hangs in the balance,
then we could wake up the day after this election in 2000 and
basically see that right slip away,'' Clinton told a luncheon of
the Taking Action in Politics group.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had an appearance scheduled later in the day at a
Buffalo-area shopping mall and was to receive an award Tuesday
night at a Syracuse synagogue
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Tuesday, Lazio campaigned at service stations in the
Hudson Valley, complaining about the high cost of gasoline and the
Clinton administration's inability to bring petroleum prices down.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Senate, Clinton told the women in Buffalo,
she would work for issues ''that will directly affect the quality
of life for our daughters and girls throughout New York and
America.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton told the audience, which included a few men, that
what had become known as women's issues ''is often a misnomer.''
She said issues that concern women, such as Social Security,
education and abortion rights, are also issues that men are
concerned about.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that when her husband was first elected president,
one commentator suggested the new administration's agenda
represented ''the feminization of politics.'' She said, ''I know he
meant it as an insult ... (but) I think it's leading to the
humanization of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she has also heard people complain that she
''has an agenda'' in running for the Senate. She said those critics
are correct.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have an agenda about education ... and when it comes to
health care, I have an agenda,'' Clinton said. ''And when it comes
to the economy, I do have an agenda, I want to see it keep growing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have an agenda when it comes to women's issues,'' Clinton
added, saying that it was important to ''support candidates who
will not blink, who will not flinch.''
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen anti-abortion demonstrators were on hand Tuesday
outside the Butler House, a mansion once owned by a publisher of
the Buffalo News, during Clinton's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she has a chance and I'm very concerned about that,''
said protester Mike Mombrea, a retired television news cameraman.
''I think Lazio is the better of the two candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, during a visit to a shopping mall in the Buffalo suburbs,
the first lady attacked Lazio's plan to repeal 4.3 cents of the
federal gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said ''the gas tax is one of the few exceptions where we
actually get more money back than we send to Washington.'' While
New York sends $300 million a year to Washington in gas taxes,
Clinton said it gets back $477 million in highway funding annually.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said Lazio's plan would have a ''damaging
impact'' on the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems to me, as usual, you've got my opponent siding with
the Republican leadership instead of the needs and interests of the
people of New York,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady called for the Federal Trade Commission to expand
its inquiry into rising gasoline prices to take in the entire
nation. The FTC is investigating rising prices in the Midwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
