<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House To Vote on Disclosure Bill  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a victory for campaign finance reform, the
House easily approved legislation requiring newly popular but often
secretive organizations to say who is paying for TV commercials and
other political activity.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, much like one passed in the Senate, included
only groups that organize under section 527 of the tax code after
GOP efforts to broaden the bill failed.
</P>
<P>
   The 385-39 vote shortly after midnight Tuesday was well above
the two-thirds needed under the special procedure employed by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are moving forward with what is an important but obviously
a small step to open up the secret organizations to sunshine,''
said Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, who has led the effort to force
these groups to disclose their donations and spending. ''This
represents one small triumph for democracy over secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   The final bill was much like one that Democrats originally
proposed. Republican leaders blocked their efforts -- some arguing
that no bill was needed at all; others saying the legislation
should be broadened to include other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, efforts to broaden the bill to include other
nonprofit organizations that get involved in campaigns met with
resistance from Democrats who argued that the GOP bill was unfair
and probably unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ''You shoot as high as you possibly can and end up with
something the majority feels is the best practical solution,'' said
Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., who led the Republican effort.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, was less enthusiastic: ''The House had
a real chance at reform. We blew it.''
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure requirement will not take effect until President
Clinton signs the bill, meaning that even if the legislation makes
it to his desk before the November election, groups will not have
to disclose money they raise between now and then.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope the Senate will now pass this bill and send it to
President Clinton for immediate signature so we will know this
election cycle who and what these organizations are,'' said Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., who pushed similar legislation through the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Section 527 is reserved for political groups, giving them
certain tax advantages. It was created for political parties and
political action committees, which report their spending to the
Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But a new brand of 527 is reporting to no one. As far as the FEC
is concerned, these groups claim to be involved in issues, not
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Other nonprofits also avoid disclosure with the FEC by claiming
to be involved in issues, although they, too, spend large sums on
TV ads that obviously are attempting to influence elections. Still,
unlike 527s, these other groups do face some limit on how much
political activity they can conduct without losing their nonprofit
tax status.
</P>
<P>
   Section 527 allows groups to be entirely focused on politics.
</P>
<P>
   One group, called Republicans for Clean Air, ran $2.5 million in
ads praising Texas Gov. George W. Bush and attacking McCain in the
days before a crucial GOP primary election. Another 527, with ties
to House Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, is campaigning for a variety of
Republicans running for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay attacked the House bill as an unconstitutional
infringement on Americans' right to participate in the political
process.
</P>
<P>
   ''This lack of privacy and free speech is chilling,'' he said in
a statement Tuesday. ''This so-called 'reform' bill is in reality
nothing more than a last-ditch effort by the Democrats to protect
their vulnerable incumbent members from valid attacks on their
positions and beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is intended to shed light on who is paying for
these advertisements, requiring groups to disclose their names to
the Internal Revenue Service, which would make them public.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing back Democratic attempts to pass the bill early this
month, GOP leaders in the House said the legislation should also
include spending by other nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans crafted a bill that included unions, trade
associations and a host of traditional nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats complained that corporations were left out, and
sought to include them as well. Republicans balked.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also complained that such a broad bill was probably
unconstitutional and doomed for repeal. The GOP version included
year-round nonprofit activity, whereas Democrats wanted to limit it
to activity within a month or two of an election.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise arranged Tuesday allowed Democrats to drop their
objections and return to the original legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The final legislation covers any group that raises at least
$25,000 per year, requiring those that do not already report to the
FEC to report to the IRS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 0019 </TRAILER>
