<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> King sentenced to 57 months for defrauding Marine Toys for Tots  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Jerry Lee King, who defrauded the Marine
Corps Toys for Tots Foundation of $1.8 million, was sentenced to
the maximum 57 months in prison and ordered to repay the nonprofit
charity for its losses.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban Buffalo native, a one-time president of the
national Toys for Tots program and the founder of the separate
Amherst Toys for Tots foundation, also faces three years parole
after he was sentenced Tuesday in U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Originally indicted on 22 counts, including money laundering and
insurance fraud, King pleaded guilty last March to one count of
wire fraud and one count of making false statements on a tax
return.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it ''a remarkable case for a number of reasons,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Gretchen Wylegala was pleased that U.S.
Judge Richard J. Arcara chose the maximum sentence of just under
five years. Under sentencing guidelines, Arcara was limited to
choose a term between 46 and 57 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a lot of money for a fraud and, of course, a fraud
against a charity. And I think that that makes this a special type
of a case,'' Wylegala said. ''I think the foundation was the group
that lost the most because they lost, for at least a period of
time, a good part of their reputation and good name.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's since been restored by them, and I think that this now
brings kind of a sad period in that foundation's existence to a
nice closure.''
</P>
<P>
   After delivering his sentence, Judge Arcara said: ''It is clear
from the facts of this case that there was an elaborate scheme to
divert substantial amounts of money.''
</P>
<P>
   King, 57, was released on bond, and has 72 hours before
beginning his sentence, which will be served in McKean, Pa. Had he
been convicted in a trial, King would have faced a maximum sentence
of more than 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   An intensive investigation, which included the FBI and IRS,
found that King used his position as chairman and founder of the
foundation to divert money through at least five bank accounts he
held secretly in Hong Kong. King managed to transfer the money into
those accounts under the impression that it was to buy toys from
Hong Kong-based manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, King used the money for himself, diverting some of it
to fund his own businesses, while also buying a car and using a
portion to pay for one of his two sons' college education.
</P>
<P>
   The fraud took place from 1991 to 1993. King was forced to
resign as foundation president and chairman in 1992 when federal
authorities began their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   King established his reputation in the toy industry in the
1970s, working his way up at Fisher-Price and eventually founding
his own company, Kingsbury Mini-Motors which, prior to going
bankrupt, had become the nation's largest manufacturer of
pedal-powered toys.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jerry King victimized a lot of people,'' said Bill Grein,
retired major and current foundation vice president. ''He
victimized the Toys for Tots Foundation staff, the United States
Marine Corps and a lot of children that could have benefitted from
the money that he took. So we're pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Grein was one of the people who worked alongside King, and
helped uncover the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jerry King was looked upon as the savior, the guy who was
going to take the Toys for Tots Foundation to the next dimension. I
was really proud to be part of that,'' he said. ''Then the longer I
worked with the man, the more I realized that this was a person I
did not want to be associated with.''
</P>
<P>
   Grein said it was especially devastating considering that King
was a former marine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll never forgive Jerry King for that. You just don't let the
Marine Corps down like that, not after 20 years in the corps,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It took almost two years for the foundation to recover,
including moving its headquarters from Buffalo to Virginia. Last
Christmas, the foundation gave out toys to a record 5.9 million
children, Grein said.
</P>
<P>
   ''People seem to have forgiven us for what Jerry King did,'' he
said. ''So one bad man has left the foundation, but the foundation
is in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 2 1-2 hour sentencing hearing, Judge Arcara raised
numerous questions about King's motives and conduct.
</P>
<P>
   When King's defense attorney Patrick Brown noted there was
another side to his client, and he was not ''an evil person,''
Judge Arcara responded: ''You're saying he's not an evil person? I
don't know how you define evil, but $1.8 million ... it almost
sounds like a preconceived plan.''
</P>
<P>
   King refused to comment outside of court. Inside the courtroom,
when asked by the judge whether he had anything to say, King told
the judge his defense attorney ''said everything I can possibly
say. I don't have anything to add to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
