<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State commission imposes $133,600 in fines on lobbyists  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The New York Yankees, struggling on the
field of late, suffered a setback in another arena Tuesday when the
club was fined by the state Lobbying Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were one of 36 groups or companies who lobby New
York state government officials and state legislators to be fined
by the commission for failing to file their 1999 financial
statements by the Jan. 15, 2000, deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the lobby clients, including the Yankees, received
the largest fine handed down by the commission Tuesday, $5,000. The
commission, which discusses its penalties in executive session, did
not disclose why the Yankees were among those getting the largest
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   When lobby clients fail to file the required financial
disclosure statements on time ''it is pretty much cut and dried''
that a fine will be levied, commission Executive Director David
Grandeau said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Grandeau said the club did file the required disclosure forms
prior to June 21, when the commission held a hearing for lobbyists
to explain why they missed the filing deadline.
</P>
<P>
   A grace period for tardy filers disappeared in 2000 thanks to a
new lobbying law created by Gov. George Pataki and the state
Legislature in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first year that lobbyists did not get written
warning and a 15-day grace period to get their financial filings in
to the lobbying commission.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rubenstein of Rubenstein Associates, the New York City
public relations firm which is the Yankees' registered lobbyist in
Albany, said the fine occurred due to an oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a complicated law, passed in December of 1999, that
has different interpretations,'' he said Tuesday. ''The Yankees did
no lobbying (in 1999) and they failed to file a piece of paper.
They had no intent to violate the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees retain a lobbyist to be heard in Albany on various
issues that relate to the club, including the regulation of cable
television and the periodic talk of a new ballpark to replace
Yankee Stadium. Some state money would likely be sought for such a
project.
</P>
<P>
   Grandeau said that from the commission's standpoint, the new law
worked to hasten the filing of financial disclosure statements.
</P>
<P>
   ''Late filers were running at about 20 percent,'' Grandeau said.
''Now we are well below two-three percent. I think people are also
being much more accurate in their reporting because there are
significant fines that can be imposed for inaccurate filing.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission can fine lobbyists or lobby clients up to $25,000
for violations of lobbying rules. The commission requires lobbyists
and lobby clients to disclose all spending on activities meant to
influence state government in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 36 lobby clients, one individual lobbyist -
Vernon Benjamin of Saugerties, who was a registered lobbyist last
year for Citizens for Licensing of Physicists in Medicine - also
failed to file a disclosure form on time. He was fined $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are 1,340 groups, companies, associations, schools and
government entities which employ 2,123 people registered to lobby
in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Grandeau said the commission turns over cases in which penalized
lobbyists do not pay their fines to the state attorney general's
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
