<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Mulls Changing School Board  </HEADLINE>
By CANDACE SMITH
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- District of Columbia Mayor Anthony Williams
headed toward a narrow victory in a referendum Tuesday on his
proposal to appoint some members of the city's school board.
</P>
<P>
   Results released by the D.C. Board of Elections and Ethics
showed 19,643 votes in favor of the proposal and 18,795 against.
That was 51.1 percent in favor and 48.9 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   However, 2,000 absentee and special ballots remained to be
counted, according to elections spokesman Bill O'Field, who said
those votes would be counted Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At present the school board consists of 11 members, all of them
elected. Under the proposal on the referendum, which Williams has
made a major issue, the mayor would appoint four members of a
nine-member board, while the remaining five would be elected.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has said he could not be held responsible for the
quality of education if he had no input on the school board, which
has come under fire for infighting, low test scores and court
mandates requiring improvements to facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the proposal said it deprived district citizens of
one more measure of self-government.
</P>
<P>
   A federally appointed panel took over the troubled system and
stripped the current school board of most of its power more than
three years ago. In May, school superintendent Arlene Ackerman
quit.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the right thing to do right now,'' Williams said of
the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   But city leaders weren't all on Williams' side.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no data to show where a non-elected board improves
the education of our children,'' Councilwoman Carol Schwartz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 0039 </TRAILER>
