<HEADLINE> Red Army Hijacking Suspect in Japan  </HEADLINE>
By KOZO MIZOGUCHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- An ex-member of a radical Japanese leftist group
allegedly involved in the 1970 hijacking of an airliner to North
Korea arrived here Wednesday after being extradited from Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshimi Tanaka, 51, who once belonged to the Red Army terrorist
group, arrived at Tokyo's main international airport on a flight
from Bangkok, police said. Police planned to question him later
about the hijacking of the Japanese jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   The nine hijackers sought exile in North Korea, where four
former Red Army members reportedly remain. Three others have died
from illnesses, while one member secretly returned to Japan in 1988
and was convicted on hijacking charges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Tanaka was arrested in Cambodia with more than $120,000
worth of fake $100 bills. He was trying to flee to Vietnam in a
North Korean Embassy car accompanied by North Korean diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Tanaka was found innocent in Thailand on charges of possessing
fake currency as part of a counterfeit ring, but was kept in jail
until the extradition request was honored. He was also wanted in
Japan on charges of inciting a riot and an attack on a police
station.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Army was responsible for bombings and attacks on
embassies and airports in Japan and abroad. Its most notorious
attack came in 1972 when 24 people were killed at Israel's Lod
airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
