<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Backs Heating Oil Reserve  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Propelled by rising fuel prices, the House
renewed its backing for creation of a special heating oil reserve
for the Northeast and approved a bigger budget for research into
renewable energy sources.
</P>
<P>
   House lawmakers, by a 393-33 vote Tuesday night, approved an
amendment to a $21.7 billion spending bill for energy and water
programs that would set up a 2 million barrel reserve that the
energy secretary could tap into when price spikes cause financial
hardships in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast was hit hard last winter by tight supplies and
sharp jumps in heating oil prices. ''We should not force families
to choose between heating their homes and buying food in the winter
months,'' said Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, sponsored by Rep. Don Sherwood, R-Pa., also
reauthorizes the president's power to withdraw oil from the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve, a 600 million barrel stockpile in
Texas and Louisiana set up during the oil crisis of 1975 to help
meet emergencies. It has been used only once, by President Bush
during the 1991 Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   It also gives the energy secretary the right to purchase oil at
$15 a barrel from small-scale ''stripper'' wells when world oil
prices drop below that level. Oil in the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve must now be purchased from foreign sources.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the same measure in April, but the Senate has
not acted on it and the focus on energy policy brought about by
high gasoline prices drove backers to attach it to the must-pass
fiscal 2001 spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is no secret to anybody that this country is facing an
energy crisis from one end of the nation to another,'' said Rep.
Bernie Sanders, an independent from Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Debate on the energy spending bill, which passed by 407-19, was
dominated by partisan exchanges on who was to blame for high gas
prices and what could be done to make the country more energy
self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused Republicans of cutting funds for alternative
energy and failing to reauthorize the Strategic Petroleum Reserve
law after it expired on March 31, while Republicans said the
administration was to blame for not reducing U.S. dependence on
foreign oil. ''The bottom line,'' said Sherwood, ''is that we lack
a coherent national energy policy to insulate us from the
volatility of these markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The House approved by voice an amendment by Reps. Matt Salmon,
R-Ariz., and Mark Udall, D-Colo., to increase funding for renewable
energy sources -- solar, biomass, wind and geothermal power -- by $40
million to about $390 million. The House bill as it came out of
committee provided $106 million less than President Clinton wanted
for renewable energy.
</P>
<P>
   Another amendment, proposed by Rep. Jack Kingston, R-Ga.,
requires the energy secretary to submit a report within 30 days of
the bill becoming law on national energy policy and plans to
address the escalating prices of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, which has yet to take up the energy and water
spending bill, Energy Committee Chairman Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska,
and Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., were pushing an energy
package that, like the House-passed measure, would reauthorize the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve, create a home heating oil reserve and
encourage stripper well production.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 4733.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Appropriations Committee summary:
http://www.house.gov/appropriations/pr01ewfu.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 0050 </TRAILER>
