<DOCNO> APW20000628.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fugitive pleads case Wednesday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A fugitive who fled prison after being
convicted of selling $20 worth of drugs three decades ago is
expected to surrender Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Harvie Richardson, now 50, will make a last-ditch plea for
leniency by offering letters of support from 100 friends in
Vancouver, British Columbia. Richardson hopes that Monroe County
Court Judge John J. Connell will set aside a 1971 sentence of up to
four years in prison. He sold LSD to an undercover police officer
at the Rochester Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Connell has refused twice to dismiss or reduce Richardson's
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson will argue that he deserves mercy because he became
an exemplary citizen, his lawyer told the Rochester Democrat and
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ''The man who is coming to court is a very different man from
the young, impetuous and reckless student of 30 years ago,'' said
Michael Bolton, who is Richardson's lawyer in Vancouver, where
Richardson has lived since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also will argue that his incarceration could have a
dire effect on his wife, Amalia, who suffers from breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Connell rejects the arguments, the letters of support
could be reviewed by a parole board to help determine when he would
be released.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting Richardson's similar arguments previously and
ordering his surrender to finish his sentence, Connell said
Richardson needs to take responsibility for his actions and
shouldn't be rewarded for escaping.
</P>
<P>
   Although District Attorney Howard R. Relin opposed setting aside
the sentence, he said he expects Richardson to be paroled within
six months.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson couldn't be reached for comment. Bolton said he and
his wife are traveling to Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Because Richardson is a prison escapee, he could be taken into
custody when he enters the United States. Bolton, however, said he
hopes U.S. immigration authorities and police allow him to
surrender on his own.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City native and Vietnam War protester served six
weeks in Attica Correctional Facility, a maximum-security prison.
He then was transferred to Camp Georgetown, a minimum-security work
camp in Madison County.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was at the work camp for six weeks when the riot and
retaking of Attica killed 43 inmates and correctional officers. He
said he walked away from the camp and fled to Canada when a guard
told him that he would return to Attica.
</P>
<P>
   The past of the research technologist who lives in a $700,000
home was revealed in 1998 when New York authorities tracked him to
Vancouver. Because Richardson had not changed his citizenship,
Canadian immigration authorities ordered him to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
