<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, June 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Newcomer Smith Upsets Cook in Utah
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Political rookie Derek Smith upset embattled Rep.
Merrill Cook in Utah's Republican primary Tuesday, handily beating the two-term
incumbent. With nearly half of the precincts reporting, Smith led Cook 58
percent to 42 percent. Cook's seat was considered one of the most vulnerable,
and GOP leaders in Congress had jumped to his defense. But fellow Republicans in
Utah were less supportive, sending Cook into the primary against the millionaire
computer company founder Smith. Cook becomes only the second incumbent to lose
in a primary this year, and the first Republican. The incumbent had been stung
by news reports over the last two years regarding his combustible temper,
erratic behavior and staff mismanagement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Supporters Await Court Ruling
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Supporters of Elian Gonzalez's father were making plans
for the family's possible return to Cuba on Wednesday, as they awaited word from
the Supreme Court on whether the 6-year-old shipwreck survivor would be allowed
to leave the United States. Unless the justices act, Elian could leave for Cuba
as early as 4 p.m. EDT Wednesday. But the departure plans would have to be put
on hold if the Supreme Court agrees to hear an appeal by Elian's Miami relatives
seeking a political asylum hearing for the boy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fed Agency to Fund AIDS Vaccine
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Four new partnerships were announced by a federal health
agency Tuesday to provide funding to groups attempting to bring an AIDS vaccine
to market. These partnerships, called HIV vaccine design and development teams,
were prompted by a presidential directive to increase public-private cooperation
in developing vaccines to major diseases, according to the National Institute of
Allergy and Infectious Diseases, the section of the National Institutes of
Health that set up the deals.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kosovo OK Colombia Emergency Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leading lawmakers agreed Tuesday to the outlines of an
emergency bill financing Colombia's battle against drug traffickers, U.S.
peacekeepers in Kosovo and recovery from storms, fires and other domestic
disasters, one participant said. Rep. Bill Young, R-Fla., chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, declined to provide an exact figure but said it would
be between $9 billion and the $12 billion limit that House and Senate leaders
set for the measure last week. That would make the package double the $5.2
billion President Clinton requested at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
135 Vieques Protesters Are Detained
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Protesters hurled iron bars at U.S. sailors at
sea and crept under ''no trespassing'' fences on land, the U.S. Navy said, as
more than 130 demonstrators intensified their fight to oust the Navy from the
Vieques island training range where it practices bombing and shelling. The
protesters insisted that the Navy bombed and shelled the range while activists
were still at large, and said they had had no news of Independence Party vice
president Fernando Martin and five others.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Rebel Accord Deadline Passes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Defying Fiji hostage-takers, the country's military rulers
said Wednesday they would appoint a civilian government without consulting
further with the gunmen. The rebels holding Fiji's government hostage have
demanded a presence on the interim government before releasing their prisoners,
who include deposed Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry. The announcement came a
day after a rebel leader, once an officer in an elite British anti-terrorism
unit, warned that the captives will die if the army tries to rescue them.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks advanced moderately early Wednesday on momentum
from the previous day's sharp rise. The dollar was lower against the yen. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 79.03 points, or 0.46 percent,
to 17,358.09 in the first hour of trading. On Tuesday, the average closed up
353.66 points, or 2.09 percent. The Dow fell 38.53 to close at 10,504.46, and
the Nasdaq was down 53.16 at 3,858.96. Advancing issues on the New York Stock
Exchange led decliners 1,645-1,282.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Giants Beat Rockies 12-7
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Shawn Estes pitched seven strong innings, and Rich Aurilia had
three hits and four RBIs as the San Francisco Giants beat the Colorado Rockies
12-7 Tuesday night. Bobby Estalella and Jeff Kent homered for the Giants, whose
first nine runs -- and 11 of their 12 -- came with two outs. Estes (7-3) went 7
1-3 innings, allowing just six hits and leaving with a 12-3 lead. Reliever Felix
Rodriguez inherited two runners and allowed both to score on RBI singles by Mike
Lansing and Jeffrey Hammonds. The Rockies pushed across two more runs before
Rodriguez fanned Brian Hunter for the third out.
</P>
