<HEADLINE> Fishermen find body in Mohawk River  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GLENVILLE, N.Y. (AP) - Detectives said they must rely on dental
records to identify the body of a man believed to be from
Flagstaff, Ariz., that was found in the Mohawk River.
</P>
<P>
   Two fishermen discovered the body after it had been in the river
for five days.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of the level of decomposition ... we can't rely on his
photo ID or a relative to identify him,'' said police Lt. Lewis
Moskowitz.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sign of violence and town police said their
preliminary cause is drowning. Police are contacting a person in
Colorado who may be a relative of the man to get dental records.
</P>
<P>
   The fishermen noticed a heel sticking up out of the water then
saw the body. Police said the man carried identification papers
that showed he was from Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   His name was being withheld until police could tell his family.
</P>
<P>
   Glenville is 22 miles northwest of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
