<HEADLINE> The cow comes home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Maybe the grass was greener on the other side of
the park.
</P>
<P>
   A fiberglass cow was found late Tuesday in another part of the
Queens park where it went missing a day earlier, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The cow, one of 500 placed around the city as part of CowParade
New York 2000, was reported stolen at about 11 a.m. Monday from its
spot in Forest Park, in the Richmond Hill section.
</P>
<P>
   A man cycling in the park Tuesday spotted the bovine sculpture
near a horse trail and notified a local television station. The
station contacted police, who met the cyclist in the park. The cow
was recovered just before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-pound cow, which was decorated by a seventh-grade student
at a Queens public school, was taken to the 102nd Precinct, short
one horn. It was unclear how long the cow would spend in police
custody.
</P>
<P>
   The cow, called Moo-Stripa, is 7 feet long, 4 feet tall and 3
feet wide and is painted with orange, red, white, blue and green
stripes.
</P>
<P>
   The organization sponsoring the exhibit, CowParade Holdings
Inc., has offered a $1,000 reward for information leading to the
arrest and conviction of anyone responsible for stealing or
damaging any of the cows.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cows are here for everyone to enjoy,'' company president
Jerome Elbaum said. ''Pet them, kiss them, take your picture with
them. But why would anyone want to damage these beautiful cows,
which were decorated with such love and creativity by talented
artists, including New York City schoolchildren?''
</P>
</TEXT>
