<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newcomer Smith Upsets Cook in Utah  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT GEHRKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Political rookie Derek Smith upset
embattled Rep. Merrill Cook in Utah's Republican primary Tuesday,
handily beating the two-term incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Smith received 29,592 votes, 59 percent, to Cook's 20,847 votes,
41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''For an absolute political unknown to come out of nowhere and
come from behind in just 12 weeks and win the Republican nomination
says this is still the greatest country in the world,'' Smith said
in his victory speech Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, whose seat was considered one of the most vulnerable, had
been stung by news reports over the last two years about his
combustible temper and accusations of erratic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional GOP leaders -- hoping to maintain their 11-seat
advantage in the House -- had jumped to Cook's defense, but fellow
Republicans in Utah were less supportive, sending him into the
primary against the millionaire computer company founder Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't win when (state) party big shots won't stand up for
you,'' Cook said Tuesday night, adding that he plans to return to
politics. ''This guy's not finished yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook becomes only the second incumbent to lose in a primary this
year, and the first Republican. The other incumbent was nine-term
Democratic Rep. Matthew Martinez of California.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Utah Gov. Mike Leavitt easily defeated
conservative challenger Glen Davis in the GOP gubernatorial runoff.
Early returns show Leavitt had a wide lead over Davis. With 94
percent of precincts reporting statewide, Leavitt led 62 percent,
107,652 votes, to 38 percent, 66,590 votes.
</P>
<P>
   And in primary runoffs in South Carolina, GOP voters chose a
candidate for a congressional district on the coast, and re-elected
a state representative being challenged by her estranged husband.
</P>
<P>
   In Utah, some Republicans had said Cook was too weak a candidate
to fend off Democrat Jim Matheson, son of the late Gov. Scott
Matheson, a Utah political hero and the last Democrat to hold the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 35, stepped into the race minutes before the filing
deadline. He had no political experience, but spent $509,000 of his
own money on the race.
</P>
<P>
   Early polls showed Smith far ahead of Cook. But weeks of
negative ads tightened the race to a statistical dead heat,
according to one recent poll. Another showed Cook still trailing
badly.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cook, 54, and Smith, 35, are conservatives who oppose gun
control and abortion rights. The race has focused instead on Cook's
temper and accusations of erratic behavior from former staffers.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, after a half-dozen unsuccessful campaigns for everything
from school board to governor, won the House seat in 1996. In years
past, he angered many by running a citizens' initiative against a
GOP tax increase and briefly leaving the party to challenge a
Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Cook was briefly banned from state GOP
headquarters after a foul-mouthed tirade days before the November
election. Soon after he won his second term, Cook fired chief of
staff Janet Jenson, who accused him of delusional behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ''Merrill has taken up permanent residence in whacko land,''
Jenson wrote in an office e-mail. ''If he asks you to fax his
underwear to the speaker's office, please just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook said the accusations were unfounded, though he acknowledged
having a temper.
</P>
<P>
   In Leavitt's primary, the two-term governor was forced to defend
his record against conservative businessman Davis, who raised
questions about the governor's role in the Olympic scandal and his
support for limited gun control. Leavitt outspent his opponent more
than 7-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, domestic discord led to a bitter race between
two-term Republican state Rep. Shirley Hinson and her estranged
husband, retired school principal Jimmy Hinson.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Hinson captured 52 percent of the vote Tuesday to win
her third term. She is assured of the seat because there is no
Democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The race was steeped in the details of the Hinsons' troubled
marriage, including allegations of death threats and infidelity.
Shirley Hinson said her husband was simply seeking revenge; he said
he could do a better job.
</P>
<P>
   And in the race for an open seat in Congress, state Rep. Henry
Brown defeated former state Transportation Chairman H.B. ''Buck''
Limehouse to win the GOP nomination to replace retiring three-term
GOP Rep. Mark Sanford, who kept a term-limit pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial results Tuesday showed Brown with 55 percent of the
vote to Limehouse's 45 percent. He will face Democrat Andy Brack, a
former spokesman for Democratic Sen. Ernest Hollings, in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Republican Congressional Campaign Committee
http://www.nrcc.org
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee: http://www.dccc.org
</P>
</TEXT>
