<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Voters Stirred By Oil Issues  </HEADLINE>
By TRACI CARL
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The threat stirs crowds at campaign rallies
and grabs headlines in newspapers: Elect top opposition candidate
Vicente Fox as president and he will sell out Mexico, including its
state-run oil company.
</P>
<P>
   There's little chance Pemex, the world's sixth-largest oil
company, will cease to be a state monopoly anytime soon. But the
campaign threats are part of a larger debate about the dreaded
p-word: privatization. And Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive who
has said he sees no reason why Pemex couldn't be privatized, is an
easy target.
</P>
<P>
   For most Mexicans, privatization has meant enrichment for the
politically connected -- or foreign exploitation of the country's
resources. But as government funds for state-run sectors become
more scarce, officials have looked for ways to find outside
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The question in the air is: How do we think about having the
private sector assume some of the risk for projects and receive
some of the rewards?'' said George Baker, editor of Mexico Energy
Intelligence, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   But in Mexico, talking about private investment is only a little
easier than talking about privatization. Eduardo Olivo Aguilar, a
25-year-old former bank employee who is studying finance, said any
money would likely come from American investors who would
eventually exploit Mexican workers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has succeeded in selling some
state-owned industries -- including telecommunications and banking --
attempts to privatize state-owned utilities have failed, and
ruling-party presidential candidate Francisco Labastida and leftist
candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas have repeatedly accused Fox of
wanting to privatize Pemex, largely considered sacred in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has repeatedly denied planning to privatize the oil monopoly
if he is elected president, acknowledging that the move would be
political suicide.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, however, he said the money used for Pemex would be
better spent on education and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the past, (Pemex) had a strong responsibility in creating
jobs, but today that responsibility is much less,'' he said. ''In
the past, the transformation and formation of Pemex represented a
high percentage of Mexico's raw material. Today, that's not the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over Pemex has been one of Labastida's many attempts
to portray Fox -- who is trying to end the ruling party's 71 years
in power -- as a traitor. Polls show the two locked in a statistical
dead heat before Sunday's election.
</P>
<P>
   Armand Peschard-Sverdrup, director of the Mexico Project at the
Center for Strategic and International Studies, said the threats
paint Fox ''as someone who would try to sell Mexico to
foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There is the perception that oil is the last frontier of the
Mexican identity,'' he said. ''The fact that they would lose that
to a foreigner, there's a kind of psychological'' impact.
</P>
<P>
   In 1884, Mexico's government surrendered the state's ownership
of the subsoil, opening the oil industry to foreign investment --
largely by British and American companies. But in 1938, foreign oil
companies refused to raise wages, and Cardenas' father, Lazaro,
expropriated the companies in one of his most memorable moves as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Mexican government has kept a tight hold on the
oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-government union is also a powerful influence, with its
members historically backing the ruling-party candidate in
elections. Yet that is changing. Prosecutors are investigating a
complaint by workers at Pemex that executives used company
information and resources to support the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has 28.4 billion barrels of proven oil reserves, the
second-largest in the Western Hemisphere after Venezuela. Oil
accounts for a third of the government's revenues and 7 percent of
the country's total export earnings. More than half the country's
net oil exports go to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The government, however, has been forced to cut subsidies and
funding for Pemex. To raise money, officials have considered
opening the company to more private investment -- an idea Labastida,
Cardenas and Fox all support.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said the private sector also could introduce improved
technology and more research, something labor-intensive Pemex has
lacked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 0131 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Pushes Prescription Drug Bill  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans are pushing their Medicare
prescription drug bill toward passage in an atmosphere of intense
partisanship, with Democrats mounting an all-night campaign of
opposition and threatening a walkout to interrupt debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Older Americans deserve financial security and health
security. Our plan would ensure both of them,'' House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said Tuesday as the GOP high command
counted votes in advance of Wednesday's showdown. ''When it comes
to prescription drug coverage, the time for politics is over and
the time for progress is now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats said politics and Republicans' fear of a backlash
from senior citizens was driving them to propose a sham bill that
would principally benefit the pharmaceutical industry. ''Not only
is it empty promises, it is empty pill jars,'' Rep. Patrick
Kennedy, D-R.I., jabbed at one point, holding an empty vial aloft
to dramatize his point.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton joined the GOP-bashing, telling an audience
Tuesday night that Republicans were afraid to let a costlier and
more generous Democratic plan come to a vote. ''Why?'' he asked
rhetorically. ''Because it might pass in an election year. Because
they're just five seats in the majority and they figure there might
be six or seven of them that might figure out that the voters back
home may ... actually look at the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled vote capped a brief but intense struggle over the
issue likely to resonate into the fall campaign, in which Democrats
are mounting a major effort to overturn the narrow GOP majority in
the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill envisions a blend of private insurance
companies and federal subsidies to spread prescription drug
coverage nationwide to any Medicare-eligible senior citizen who
wants it. The bill, estimated to cost about $40 billion over five
years, includes subsidies for low-income seniors as well as those
with high drug expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic proposal, with a price tag nearly double the GOP
plan, calls for a program in which the government establishes a
uniform drug benefit to be made available nationwide. It, too,
contains subsidies for the low income, and more generous benefits
for seniors with high drug costs than Republicans provide.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the debate over policy differences, though, lie
competing political calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, cautioned by their pollster that passing
legislation is a ''political imperative,'' pushed the bill through
committee last week on a party-line vote and expressed confidence
they could do the same on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, determined to attract senior citizen support as part
of their campaign to win the House this fall, labored to hold
defections to a minimum, part of a strategy to deny GOP claims that
their measure was a bipartisan solution to a problem vital to 39
million senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   They demanded that Republicans permit them a vote on their
costlier alternative, but that seemed unlikely Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they warned that denial likely would trigger a program of
disruptive tactics on the House floor, including demands for a
series of procedural roll calls that could kill hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''One time during impeachment ... we had a walkout,'' Democratic
leader Dick Gephardt said Tuesday. ''We entertained that idea too''
for the Medicare drug battle.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Democrats turned a basement room in the Capitol
into a mock pharmacy, and arranged for a succession of lawmakers to
be available around the clock for talk radio programs and other
appearances designed to underscore their opposition to the GOP
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans countered with some political theater of their own.
</P>
<P>
   They touted their proposal at a ceremony on the steps outside
the Capitol on Tuesday, with entertainment provided by a
retirement-age barbershop quartet.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and other supporters of the bill walked to the
microphones serenaded to the tune of ''Happy Days Are Here Again,''
a virtual anthem for Democrats for more than a generation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 0133 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Divers Convicted of Poaching  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- Two decorated Canadian navy divers
were convicted of poaching dozens of lobsters from the ocean floor
that later were served at a private party.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer Anne Menard and Leading Seaman Joe Tremblay of the
Atlantic Fleet Diving Unit admitted Tuesday they helped colleagues
nab about 100 pounds of lobsters in September 1999 and transport
them to a military base to be cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Nancy Koppang, a military prosecutor, said the illegal
lobster hunt occurred at a time when the government was involved in
a high-profile dispute with native fishermen over lobster fishing
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''The navy's name was tarnished as a result of this,'' Koppang
said.
</P>
<P>
   Menard was found guilty of fishing for lobster during a closed
season and using a military vessel, and was fined $1,300. Tremblay
was convicted of fishing out of season and possessing undersized
and female lobsters. He was fined $2,600.
</P>
<P>
   Nine divers from the 98-member unit were charged. One case was
dropped for lack of evidence; another diver was convicted and fined
$2,000; and five await military court trials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 0135 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds May Keep Interest Rates Steady  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the economy showing signs of cooling, the
Federal Reserve may decide to hold the line on interest rates
Wednesday rather than continuing to raise them.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times since
last June to slow down economic growth and there are indications
that its policy is working: the nation's unemployment rate rose to
4.1 percent in May up from a 30-year low of 3.9 percent in April;
retail sales were lackluster the past two months; and the housing
market has slowed a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been some whiffs of an economic slowdown, which
have been refreshing,'' said Sung Won Sohn, Wells Fargo's chief
economist, echoing the main reason why many economists believe the
Fed will stay on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Economists also suggested that some of the Fed's previous rate
increases have yet to work their way through the economy, a process
that can take anywhere from six months to a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Open Market Committee, composed of Fed board members
and regional bank presidents, is scheduled Wednesday to conclude
two days of closed-door discussions with Fed governors about
interest rates. An afternoon announcement is expected.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the Fed is going to stand pat but very possibly issue
a statement which suggests it is quite prepared to tighten at the
next meeting'' on Aug. 22, said Paul Kasriel, chief economist for
Northern Trust Co.
</P>
<P>
   If Fed policy-makers do nothing this time around, economists
believe the central bank probably will boost interest rates in
August by a quarter point to hold down economic growth and limit
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is strong evidence that the interest rate increases the
Fed has done to date are taking hold. They are effective. But more
needs to be done,'' said Ken Mayland, an economist with ClearView
Economics.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists believe that the economy, which was roaring
ahead at a 5.4 percent growth rate in the first three months of
this year, may have slowed to 4 percent rate or less in the current
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed doesn't want a repeat of the last two years, when
growth slowed in the spring only to reaccelerate sharply for the
rest of the year, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan and his colleagues are seeking to
achieve a soft landing in which growth slows enough to keep
inflation under control but not so much that it threatens the
country's record 9&AMP;frac12;-year economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   At its last session on May 16, the Fed boosted rates by a half
point, double the normal quarter-point moves. That pushed its
target for the federal funds rate, the interest banks charge each
other, to 6.5 percent, the highest level in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates six times since last June, when the
funds rate stood at 4.75 percent. Those increases have pushed
banks' prime lending rate, the benchmark for millions of consumer
and business loans, to a nine-year high of 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the debate over whether growth has really slowed,
Fed policy-makers are also discussing how much of a slowdown will
be needed to keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Laurence Meyer raised the possibility in a recent speech
that the Fed may need to bring about ''a period of below-trend
growth'' to keep inflation in check, comments that were viewed as
indicating that Meyer may be urging further rate increases to push
growth down and unemployment up.
</P>
<P>
   But 16 House Democrats wrote Greenspan and his colleagues
earlier this month warning that further rate hikes would lead to
''increases in unemployment and real economic damage to our least
prosperous citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   While conventional wisdom holds that the Fed does not like to be
changing interest rates as a presidential election heats up,
analysts believe the central bank will run that risk to make sure
inflation is being controlled.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Financial Markets Center, a research institute
based in Philomont, Va., showed that the 1.75 percentage point
increase in rates already engineered by the Fed exceeds the rate
increases of all previous pre-election periods over the last four
decades with the exception of 1967-68, when inflation was rising
rapidly at the height of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve: http://www.federalreserve.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 0147 </TRAILER>
