<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV-infected man accused of sex with child first charged under HIV law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - An HIV-infected man accused of sexually
assaulting a child has become the first person in New Jersey
charged under a law that made it a crime to have intercourse while
knowingly infected with the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities on Tuesday announced the arrest of Ora Dwayne
Battles, 40, of Newton, saying the Sussex County Community College
student sexually assaulted the child several times between April 1
and June 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Sussex County Prosecutors Office declined to release details
of the alleged incidents, but said the child was younger than 13
and not related to Battles.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the victim's mother became aware of the abuse
and notified police after seeking medical advice.
</P>
<P>
   Known by most people at the college as David, Battles was a tour
guide, a member of the student senate and an officer in a club -
called AIDS Brigade - that disseminates information about the
disease and holds fund-raisers, according to Heidi Gregg,
coordinator of athletics and student activities.
</P>
<P>
   Battles is charged with first-degree aggravated sexual assault,
endangering the welfare of a child, sexual assault, and committing
acts of sexual penetration while knowingly infected with HIV or
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   He was being held at Sussex County jail Tuesday in lieu of
$250,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against him mark the first use of the AIDS law,
which went into effect in August 1997. A spokesman for the state
Division of Criminal Justice said the agency's database shows no
other arrests or convictions under the law.
</P>
<P>
   Morris County First Assistant Prosecutor Karin Kelly-Weisert,
who said her office was involved in an investigation that could
have resulted in a charge under the statute, said it can be
difficult to meet the law's requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In the Morris County case, a woman learned a man with whom she
had engaged in sex was HIV-positive and sought to have him
prosecuted. But Kelly-Weisert said it was difficult to establish
when the man had learned he was infected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kelly-Weisert was surprised that there had been no
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ''One would think the issue would be raised more often,'' she
told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Wednesday's editions. ''It's
possible that victims either don't know about the statute or just
don't want to go public with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
