<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premium Gas Users Paying More  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID SHARP
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- Marianne Tarraza gave little thought to
fuel costs when she bought her Lincoln Navigator last summer. Gas
was cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's getting walloped by soaring gasoline prices and she's
also paying more than most: Her sport utility vehicle is one of a
growing number of models that work best with premium grade gas.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I made the purchase, I wasn't thinking of premium gas at
all. I was mostly concerned about lugging my children around, and
gas wasn't a consideration,'' Tarraza said.
</P>
<P>
   For a 30-gallon tank of gas, she spends about $50, about $5 more
than a tank of regular.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, more motorists are finding themselves in the same
situation as the number of new cars for which premium gas is
preferred creeps upward, said Bob Reynolds, president of Downstream
Alternatives, an Indiana fuel consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   A computer analysis of EPA fuel economy data by The Associated
Press shows the number of car models recommending premium gas
jumped to 26 percent this year after hovering around 20 percent
since the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of just luxury and performance-oriented cars like BMWs
and Mercedes, mid-priced cars like the Volkswagen Passat, Nissan
Maxima and some versions of the Mazda 626 and Mitsubishi Galant are
coming equipped with engines that perform best using premium or
mid-grade gas.
</P>
<P>
   The cost difference is substantial -- premium gas can cost nearly
20 cents per gallon more than regular -- at a time when fuel prices
are rising steeply.
</P>
<P>
   The national average price last week was $1.65 per gallon for
regular unleaded gas and $1.81 for premium, both about 50 cents
higher than a year ago, according to the American Automobile
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are even higher in the Midwest, with premium gas going
for about $2.36 a gallon last week in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Cars that use premium fuel generally can get by without it,
thanks to computerized ''knock sensors'' that allow engines to
accommodate gas with lower-than-recommended octane levels, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   But the higher octane gas translates to greater horsepower, one
of the selling points for such cars, said David Champion, director
of automobile testing for Consumers Union, the nonprofit publisher
of Consumer Reports.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're trying to get more performance out of the same
engine,'' Champion said from his office in Colchester, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Nissan tweaked the engine in its Maxima, boosting
the horsepower from 200 to 222 in its 2000 model. Nissan recommends
mid-grade fuel with a rating of 89 octane or better, while regular
87 octane was fine for the old Maxima.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their Japanese and European counterparts, many American
manufacturers seem to be resisting the trend toward higher octane
gas.
</P>
<P>
   For example, General Motors will begin recommending regular
instead of premium for models using its Northstar engine next year,
said Bob Furey, a fuel specialist for GM in Warren, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Magliozzi, who hosts National Public Radio's ''Car Talk''
program with his brother, said those in the market for a new car or
truck should consider the extra cost of premium gas because the
difference can add up to thousands of dollars over the car's life.
</P>
<P>
   ''That may not bother you if you're driving a Mercedes S600, but
if you bought a Passat, it may be a very rude surprise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.consumersunion.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 0211 </TRAILER>
