<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commission Torn on War Crime Papers  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some members of a federal commission that is
unearthing Nazi and Japanese war crimes documents favor a ''bulk
declassification'' that would more quickly make public millions of
U.S. government-held papers.
</P>
<P>
   But the CIA, FBI and Pentagon are resisting, citing possible
compromises from information now a half century old.
</P>
<P>
   The Nazi War Criminal Records Interagency Working Group reported
to Congress Tuesday that it may be able to identify and declassify
all World War II documents related to Germany by an October 2001
deadline. But it reported no real progress in exposing documents on
Imperial Japan, saying that could take at least a year longer.
</P>
<P>
   More than halfway through the commission's three-year task, at
least 70 percent of the millions of World War II documents related
to war crimes remain secret, commission members said.
</P>
<P>
   But intelligence and military representatives on the commission
insist, however, that their page-by-page, and sometimes
line-by-line declassification is moving along rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Panel chairman Michael J. Kurtz, who is also an assistant
national archivist, said not every document needs the painstaking
analysis insisted upon by intelligence agencies. He said bulk
declassification would speed up a process which has so far
declassified 1.5 million papers.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Baer, another commission member, said historians prefer
mass declassification because it would preserve original documents
and their relationships to each other. Some documents have been
released piecemeal after censorship by intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Levit, CIA special counsel who sits on the commission,
said the CIA opposes bulk declassification because it needs to
protect its sources and methods.
</P>
<P>
   John Collingwood, an FBI member on the panel, said the FBI has
been declassifying documents at ''an incredibly fast pace'' but
also could not agree to a blanket release.
</P>
<P>
   Army representative Col. Lewis Thompson said the Pentagon also
opposes any sweeping declassification, but has made progress by
converting old microfilms to computer-searchable files. He said
Army teams are processing up to 70,000 pages a week.
</P>
<P>
   Disclosure of Japanese documents is complicated by the need for
Japanese cooperation, commission members said at a hearing,
although they indicated no steps have been taken to get it.
Millions of documents captured during the war were returned to
Japan in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not even begun to get our arms around the Japanese
issue,'' said commission member Richard Ben-Veniste.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires all U.S.-held papers related to possible war
crimes and looted property to be declassified by October 2001. The
law covers Germany, Imperial Japan and their allies.
</P>
<P>
   Officials expect between 5 million and 8 million pages to be
declassified. The commission started with 600 million pages in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Nazi War Criminal Records Interagency Working Group:
www.nara.gov/iwg
</P>
<P>
   Simon Wiesenthal Center http:/www.wiesenthal.com
</P>
</TEXT>
