<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 03:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo OK Colombia Emergency Bill  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Breaking a months-long deadlock, top lawmakers
hope to sign off Wednesday on details of an emergency package
financing Colombia's war against drug producers, U.S. troops in
Kosovo and rebuilding from fires, storms and other disasters at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Following a closed-door meeting Tuesday evening among leaders of
the House and Senate Appropriations committees, Rep. Bill Young,
R-Fla., said bargainers had agreed on the outlines of a compromise
package. He said he believed party leaders would ''finalize
everything'' on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Young, chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, would not
reveal a precise final figure. But he said it would be between $9
billion and the $12 billion ceiling that House and Senate leaders
set for the bill last week -- about double the $5.2 billion
President Clinton proposed earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Top Republicans hope to push a final bill through Congress and
ship it to Clinton by Friday, when lawmakers plan to begin their
weeklong Fourth of July recess. Republicans want to finish the bill
by then to avoid blame for any problems the Pentagon might face as
it juggles money to pay for U.S. peacekeepers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ''That would be an embarrassment for all of us in Congress if we
would allow that to happen,'' Young said at a brief public session
of the bargainers earlier in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Young said the measure would include $1.3 billion to help
Colombia's embattled government fight drug traffickers who control
broad swaths of the country, along with their leftist guerrilla and
right-wing paramilitary allies. Included is money for purchasing
helicopters and other supplies and training Colombian troops.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a victory for Clinton and House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., who have pushed for the aid as a way to combat
drug use in the United States. Colombia supplies most of the
cocaine used in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Still unresolved is whether to include compromise language
struck Tuesday that would lift the four-decade-old U.S. food
embargo against Cuba. There is strong opposition to that deal among
some senators, and Young indicated it might be left for inclusion
in some later bill.
</P>
<P>
   Aides and lawmakers had said earlier that to keep the bill
acceptable to Clinton, they would avoid including controversial
provisions changing laws.
</P>
<P>
   They said they would therefore omit a provision pushed by
Schering-Plough Corp. to win an extension of its patent for
Claritin, the popular and profitable allergy drug. Also left off
the bill was language by Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., aimed at
extending a lucrative patent his alma mater, Columbia University,
has on a process its scientists invented for making some widely
sold biotechnology drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those measures could end up on other bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not want a veto of the bill,'' said Senate
Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, when
bargainers held a brief public session.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., had criticized
earlier, larger versions of the package for being too costly and
containing unnecessary items, and Senate work on the measure
virtually halted for two months.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved $13 billion in March, mostly by adding extra
money for the Pentagon, while the Senate approved roughly $9
billion last month.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, participants said that as part of the final package,
the House and Senate would each get a $100 million kitty for
various lawmakers' home-district projects.
</P>
<P>
   Young would reveal few details of the bill. But earlier,
participants said that besides money for Colombia, the compromise
would include $2.05 billion to repay the Pentagon for the costs of
5,700 American troops serving with the NATO peacekeeping team in
Kosovo; at least $660 million for rebuilding from the
government-set fires that ravaged Los Alamos, N.M.; and $250
million to help North Carolina and other states recover from last
September's Hurricane Floyd and other agricultural problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 0316 </TRAILER>
