<DOCNO> APW20000628.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Honors Korean War Casualties  </HEADLINE>
By KYONG-HWA SEOK
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSAN AIR BASE, South Korea (AP) -- The U.S. Air Force challenged
Korean War history Wednesday, claiming that the first American
casualties in the conflict were airmen, not ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Three Air Force planes suffered heavy damage in attacks by North
Korea and crashed in bad weather on their way to their base in
Japan, said Deryl D. Danner, chief U.S. Air Force historian in
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The six occupants of the planes -- two B-26 invaders and one F-82
twin Mustang -- were killed on June 28, 1950, three days after the
war began, and became the first American victims, Danner said.
</P>
<P>
   The ground troops of Task Force Smith from Japan had been
considered the first U.S. casualties, while engaging advancing
North Korean troops south of Seoul on July 5, 1950.
</P>
<P>
   ''The timing of the efforts (to set records straight) is related
to the 50th anniversary of the Korean War,'' Danner said, adding
that the findings have been sent to Washington for review.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service Wednesday in Osan, the headquarters of the
U.S. Air Force Command in South Korea, honored the six slain
airmen.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the 50th anniversary of their sacrifice, we collectively
thank them for their steadfast courage. Today, the legacy of these
airmen lives on,'' said Lt. Gen. Charles R. Heflebower, commander
of the U.S. Air Force in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ''The significance of the ceremony is that the first Americans
who have lost their lives in defense of freedom have been given
credit at last,'' Danner said.
</P>
<P>
   The war began June 25, 1950 when communist North Korea invaded
the South. The northern forces advanced quickly, pushing back
unprepared southern forces.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council voted to send in forces, and on June
28 a dozen Air Force planes flew from Japan to destroy railroads
north of Seoul to stop the North's advance.
</P>
<P>
   The six killed that day were Lt. Raymond J. Cyborski of
Illinois; Lt. Remez L. Harding of Texas; Lt. Vernon A. Lindvig of
North Dakota; Lt. Derrell B. Sayre of Ohio; Staff Sgt. Jose C.
Campos Jr. of Arizona and Staff Sgt. William J. Goodwin of
Washington, Danner said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had not done research before to display Air Force history
like this,'' Danner said. ''There were a lot of problems and
inconsistencies, so we had to do research on the National Archives
and contact veterans' associations and Air Force units.''
</P>
<P>
   The war ended July 27, 1953 with an armistice. More than 36,000
Americans were killed in the conflict, and the United States still
keeps 37,000 troops stationed in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrations marking the 50th anniversary of the start of the
war were muted after the first-ever summit of the nations' leaders
earlier this month, at which both agreed to promote peace and
pursue eventual reunification.
</P>
<P>
   After living half a century in isolation, North Korea is slowly
trying to open ties with other countries to expedite foreign aid
and investment for its devastated economy.
</P>
<P>
   David Morton, who coordinates U.N. assistance to Pyongyang, said
in Beijing on Wednesday that with the worst of a five-year famine
over, North Korea foresees feeding itself in two years' time given
good weather and $250 million in aid.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea has agreed to donate 200,000 tons of fertilizer this
year, a $40 million contribution, Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   If the rest of the aid comes in, North Korea will be able to
feed its 22.5 million people in 2002, ending years of dependence on
international food deliveries, Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's economy teetered after its trade partners
disappeared along with the Soviet bloc. Floods and drought
beginning in 1995 ruined the economy and produced a famine that
killed at least 220,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, improved weather, $138 million in aid and limited
agricultural reforms have helped North Korea over the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ''The country is moving along the road from relief to
recovery,'' Morton said, but called the recovery fragile, dependent
on good weather.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's state news agency warned Wednesday that crops are
''severely affected by shortages of water caused by heat and
drought.'' Pastures have dried up, leaving domestic animals short
of fodder, the Korean Central News Agency reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
