<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 46; Nasdaq Gains 38  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher in early trading
Wednesday as Wall Street awaited a decision from the Federal
Reserve on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the start of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 45.60 at 10,550.06.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 5.02 at 1,455.57, and the
Nasdaq composite index was up 37.85 at 3,896.81.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed was expected to announce Wednesday afternoon whether it
will raise interest rates for the seventh time since last June.
</P>
<P>
   In recent sessions, signs of a slowdown have convinced many
analysts that the Fed will leave rates unchanged. The Fed began its
long course of rate increases in a bid to cool off inflationary
pressures in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But mixed signals abound. Wednesday morning, the Commerce
Department said orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket
manufactured goods shot up 6 percent in May, led by a burst in
demand for electronics equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Economists cautioned that the durable-goods data tend to be
volatile, but worried that the report signified that the
manufacturing sector has not cooled off as much as many analysts
had believed.
</P>
<P>
   With the Fed's decision looming, investors continued moving
money from sector to sector. Technology and telecommunications
stocks fared best, with Hewlett-Packard rising $4.563 to $121.188
and WorldCom up $3.563 at $43.25.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 127.15 million
shares, ahead of Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.47 to 510.55.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.5 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.4 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.6 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
