<HEADLINE> Iranian Head Appoints Police Chief  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran's supreme leader appointed a new police
chief, Iran's official news agency reported Wednesday, replacing a
hard-liner who was widely considered responsible for last year's
student riots.
</P>
<P>
   Ayatollah Ali Khamenei appointed by decree late Tuesday Brig.
Gen. Mohammad Baqer Qalibaf as the commander of the Law Enforcement
Forces, as the police are called. He replaces Brig. Gen. Hedayat
Lotfian, the official Islamic Republic News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency gave no reasons for the replacement, but pro-reform
groups allied with President Mohammad Khatami had long called for
Lotfian's dismissal after police and vigilantes with clubs stormed
a Tehran student hostel last July, provoking the worst riots since
the 1979 Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Although no charges have been brought against Lotfian, his
deputy Brig. Gen. Farhad Nazari and 19 others are awaiting a
verdict after a lengthy trial for their roles in storming the
Tehran University dormitory on July 9, 1999. At least one student
was killed and scores were injured in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Lotfian's sacking comes just two weeks before the first
anniversary of the riots.
</P>
<P>
   Nazari has been charged with ordering the illegal entry of the
hostel, disobeying orders and tarnishing the image of the police.
The other accused -- 11 officers and eight low ranking policemen --
are charged with being accomplices to the crime and destroying
public property. If found guilty, they face prison sentences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
