<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Gains 57; Dow Adds 12  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher in early trading
Wednesday as Wall Street awaited a decision from the Federal
Reserve on interest rates. Technology names were driving the gains.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index
was up 56.93 at 3,915.89.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 11.98 at 10,516.48 and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 4.66 at 1,455.21.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed was expected to announce Wednesday afternoon whether it
will raise interest rates for the seventh time since last June.
</P>
<P>
   In recent sessions, signs of a slowdown have convinced many
analysts that the Fed will leave rates unchanged. The Fed began its
long course of rate increases in a bid to cool off inflationary
pressures in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's going to be some recognition that the economy has
decelerated,'' said Michael Strauss, managing director of
Commonfund Asset Management. Strauss was anticipating that the Fed
would leave rates unchanged at this meeting, but would leave the
door open to a possible rate increase in August.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's still a very, very cautious Fed,'' he said. ''They have
some room to hold off on a tightening now, but the economic numbers
in July and August could paint a picture of a stronger economy than
they really want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, certain economic gauges have been pointing to continued
growth. Wednesday morning, the Commerce Department said orders to
U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods shot up 6 percent
in May, led by a burst in demand for electronics equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Economists cautioned that the durable-goods data tend to be
volatile, but worried that the report signified that the
manufacturing sector has not cooled off as much as many analysts
had believed.
</P>
<P>
   With the Fed's decision looming, investors continued moving
money from sector to sector. Technology and telecommunications
stocks fared best, with Hewlett-Packard rising $6.188 to $122.813
and WorldCom up $4.813 at $44.375.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 321.35 million
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said end-of-the-quarter buying and selling was
preventing the market from hitting the lull that typically precedes
Fed announcements.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.11 to 512.19.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
