<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Defends Taiwanese President  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- The Taiwanese president's willingness to
accept an agreement that once helped start historic meetings with
China was not a compromise gesture with the island's communist
rival, Taiwan's top official on China affairs said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai Ing-wen, chairwoman of Taiwan's Mainland Affairs Council,
spoke one day after President Chen Shui-bian made front-page news
by saying he could accept a 1992 deal with China which Taiwanese
refer to as ''one China, each side can have its own
interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal once allowed both sides to disagree about how to
describe Taiwan's political status. Taiwan has enjoyed de facto
independence from China since the two sides split amid civil war 51
years ago, and China considers Taiwan a renegade province that will
one day be reunited with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and the local media viewed Chen's announcement to be a
significant policy shift and a goodwill gesture toward Beijing. In
recent months, some Taiwanese officials have said the 1992
agreement is outdated, and Chen had never before specifically said
he could accept the 1992 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But during her brief news conference, Tsai told reporters, ''His
(Chen's) position has always been consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Chen had never before accepted the agreement, he did say
in his inauguration speech that he would like to build on the
foundation left by the previous Nationalist Party government, which
made the 1992 deal with Beijing. Chen also urged the two sides to
''agree to disagree'' on long-standing disputes that might take
years to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing scrapped the 1992 consensus last year after former
Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui began insisting that both sides
have equal ''state-to-state'' relations. China viewed this position
to be a radical move toward independence and canceled an envoy's
trip to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chen has said he agrees with Lee's view, the president
has downplayed the position, which is rarely mentioned now by
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Since Chen's March election victory, Beijing has been demanding
that he agree with its ''one-China principle,'' which holds that
Taiwan is an inseparable part of China -- not a sovereign,
independent state.
</P>
<P>
   Chen and most Taiwanese oppose the ''one-China principle,''
fearing that it means that the ruler of the country would be the
repressive communist government in Beijing. On Wednesday night,
Tsai repeated Chen's stance: ''There is no way we can accept this
position.''
</P>
<P>
   China did not immediately respond to Chen's latest comments.
</P>
<P>
   C.M. Liang, a political science professor at Fu-jen Catholic
University in Taipei, said Chen is accepting the 1992 agreement now
because he is on the front line of the China debate and is becoming
more sensitive to Beijing's pressure. Liang also said Chen realizes
that he needs a deal with China to calm Taiwan's jittery stock
market and maintain economic stability.
</P>
<P>
   ''His China policy will have to be much more flexible,'' Liang
said. ''There should be a breakthrough during his term.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
