<HEADLINE> Japanese: Volcano As Neighbor OK  </HEADLINE>
By YURI KAGEYAMA
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMITSUKI, Japan (AP) -- Mount Oyama may be a fearsome neighbor,
with its periodic threats of eruption, but residents here say
they're willing to forgive the volcano, given the pleasures of
living on an island surrounded by clean waters filled with tasty
fish.
</P>
<P>
   After days of quakes that rattled Miyakejima island, the danger
of the 2,686-foot mountain's erupting appeared to be fading
Wednesday, raising hopes among hundreds of evacuated residents that
the latest scare was ending.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuruko Kawahara, a 75-year-old cookie factory worker, has lived
through two eruptions by Mount Oyama. Still, she said she wouldn't
dream of living anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ''For those who live on the island, the island is good,'' she
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I leave the house all day with the doors unlocked and the
windows open. I would be much more afraid to live with crime in the
big cities,'' she said. ''A volcano only erupts every once in a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Many island dwellers echoed Kawahara's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sea is great,'' said 49-year-old fisherman Motoharu
Komuro. ''I was born and raised here. It'd take a lot of energy to
break out of that lifestyle. I love nature here.''
</P>
<P>
   Seismologists in Tokyo told reporters Wednesday the earthquakes
that are still shaking the island are drifting out to sea, and
there is little chance of the mountain spewing lava on Miyakejima.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation warning was issued Monday after intensifying
earthquakes signaled a possible eruption at Mount Oyama, a
curvaceous tree-covered mountain that seems to spread out to all
corners of Miyakejima, 120 miles from Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The warning involved more than 2,000 residents -- many of whom
moved to centers elsewhere on the island -- and it is now up to
officials on the island and in Tokyo to decide when to lift it.
About 4,000 people live on Miyakejima.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainties about the volcano's activities this time have
been puzzling. Although Mount Oyama has erupted several times in
the last 60 years, including in 1983, the blasts usually came
quickly and were over in a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   In previous eruptions, residents saw a pillar of fire shoot up
with a bang and sparks scatter like fireworks explosions.
</P>
<P>
   When it erupted in 1962, Kawahara had to flee on foot to a
junior high school. ''It was frightening,'' she recalled. ''But
I've never felt that I don't want to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was killed or injured in that quake, or the one in 1983,
because the residents were evacuated in time. A 1940 eruption
killed 11 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1152 </TRAILER>
