<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Jonathan Kozol  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Nine books and 35 years after he took up the
fight that's shaped his adult life, Jonathan Kozol was growing
weary of the outrage that had been his stock in trade.
</P>
<P>
   The crusading writer was aching for a respite from the
exhausting work of bringing the lives of the poor -- especially
children -- to the attention of a nation that often acts as if it
would rather ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   He turned to a seemingly unlikely refuge -- a gritty,
oft-maligned neighborhood that had touched his heart once before.
And the South Bronx, whose name is shorthand for the woes of urban
America, helped restore his tired spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt at home here,'' says Kozol, 63, whose often searing
books have chronicled the real-life impact of the gap between rich
and poor. ''I don't have children of my own, so this was the place
where I thought I had a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozol's hundreds of trips to the South Bronx neighborhood known
as Mott Haven -- for social visits, classroom stops, religious
services and long afternoons at a church after-school program --
began in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the nation's poorest areas, and Kozol had spent
time there before, researching his 1995 book ''Amazing Grace,'' a
wrenching account of the impact of poverty, violence, disease and
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, he was looking for more than just the makings
of a book -- although he eventually got that, too. Worn down by the
pressures of writing and advocacy and saddened by the illness of
his elderly parents, the Harvard-educated writer sought solace amid
a network of poor black and Hispanic children, most of them still
in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kept coming back here when I was feeling low,'' he says.
''The children would always cheer me up and comfort me if they
could see I was upset.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every book I've written up until now has had an agenda,''
Kozol continues, recalling works on homelessness, educational
inequality and illiteracy. ''When a writer has a specific agenda,
the whimsical and unpredictable things that children say become
distractions. ... This time, I wanted to enjoy the interruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozol smiles when he speaks of the small, sweet ideas that
occupy the minds of young children, largely the same in the South
Bronx as they are in wealthier places -- things like crayons,
birthdays, pets, baby brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The innocence he saw in the schoolchildren of this troubled
neighborhood is central to ''Ordinary Resurrections,'' the book
that was born from his visits.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of Kozol's earlier works, ''Ordinary Resurrections''
is highly personal, filled with vivid descriptions of children's
lives and personalities and of the friendships he formed with them.
</P>
<P>
   While books like ''Death at an Early Age,'' ''Savage
Inequalities'' and ''Amazing Grace'' exposed some of the ugliest
parts of American life, ''Ordinary Resurrections'' finds beauty
even in a neighborhood filled with sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol describes small encounters over the hundreds of hours he
spent at St. Ann's Church, an inviting stone building where
neighborhood children play, do homework and munch snacks after
school. He also made frequent visits to nearby P.S. 30, a public
school that thrives -- despite many obstacles -- thanks to the work
of a devoted principal.
</P>
<P>
   The children Kozol meets ask to see pictures of his dog, make
bracelets from jelly beans and describe their ideas about God and
heaven. While some may worry about fathers in prison or go home to
mothers who don't have money for food, they are still children --
playful, curious and loving.
</P>
<P>
   ''St. Ann's is not a place of sorrow, but ... of irresistible
vitality and energy and sometimes complicated hope, and now and
then uncomplicated joy,'' Kozol writes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ordinary Resurrections'' clearly reflects his fascination with
children, and the joy he takes in observing the quirks that make
each one unique. But Kozol's new focus on life's softer elements
doesn't mean his passion for political and social change has
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   By introducing readers to youngsters like inquisitive, exuberant
Elio and self-assured Pineapple, he hopes to inspire outrage about
the poverty in which they live and the inferior, underfunded
schools they attend.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol recalls one reader who suggested that ''in a way, it's my
most political book, because I don't speak politically, but the
narrative leads a reader to inevitable political conclusions. I
hope that's true.''
</P>
<P>
   A slight man in a rumpled suit and scuffed shoes, Kozol bursts
with excited energy as he chats with teachers and administrators on
a recent visit to P.S. 30, and he seems happiest with children
tugging at his sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   But ask him about the social and economic forces that may limit
his young Bronx friends, and he responds with an outrage that's
gone out of fashion since he was a young Boston teacher in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol points to schools that are 99.8 percent black and Hispanic
and spend about $5,000 per year for each student. He calls these
''academies of apartheid,'' comparing them to schools in wealthy
towns that spend as much as $18,000 per child.
</P>
<P>
   ''School inequality ought to be the easiest issue for a rich
democracy to resolve,'' Kozol says, leaning in over a table at a
coffee shop around the corner from St. Ann's. ''This country is
rich enough to give every child in the South Bronx the kind of
education it's giving to children in the richest suburbs and not
take a dollar away from the suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although neighborhoods like the South Bronx are benefiting from
a recent drop in crime, the economic boom has hardly been felt in
the area served by St. Ann's, where Kozol says unemployment is
still more than 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After more than three decades of writing angry books, delivering
impassioned lectures and testifying before Congress on poverty and
school inequality, he sometimes wonders what his life's work has
really accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's heartbreaking after 35 years to see public schools that
are more separate and less equal than they were when I started
out,'' he says. ''There is a sense of futility about doing this and
seeing so little change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1204 </TRAILER>
