<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gallery To Show Art by Blind  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE SCHREINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- To cut through the haze of near
blindness, Dorothy M. Mullins presses close to the canvas to apply
brushstrokes to her vision of a dazzling Southern California
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The work is slow going. Her face and clothes are smudged with a
rainbow of colors as she leans in to capture details. A white cane
rests at her side. It helps her to get around as she pursues her
craft.
</P>
<P>
   The union of a white cane -- a welcome tool for the blind -- and
art supplies usually stirs curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ''They say you can paint? I say 'sure,''' says Mullins, who has
been legally blind since birth.
</P>
<P>
   New Vision Enterprises Foundation wants to dispel such
preconceptions by promoting the works of blind or visually impaired
artists, and opens a gallery Thursday to showcase their creations.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the blind say New Vision Art Gallery, in downtown
Louisville overlooking the Ohio River, will illuminate the talents
of many people who create paintings or sculptures with limited or
no sight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people will be surprised,'' says Rosalie Copeland, art
program specialist at The Braille Institute of Los Angeles.
''People tend to look for stereotypes. The variety and quality of
art will amaze them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gibbons, president and chief executive officer of National
Industries for the Blind in Alexandria, Va., says the gallery will
reveal the talents and diversity of the blind.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just speaks a powerful message to blind people to go where
their hearts and abilities take them,'' he says. ''It gives them an
opportunity to create and to move and contribute in ways that make
sense to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a place to permanently display such artwork was the
motivation in opening the gallery, according to Bob Jarboe, chief
executive officer of New Vision Enterprises. An art buff, Jarboe
says the gallery's main purpose is to create career opportunities
for blind or visually impaired artists.
</P>
<P>
   The artwork will be available for sale. The gallery also hopes
to promote works for display in larger galleries across the
country, and generate a following for the artists.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our philosophy is that nothing should remain in the gallery
longer than it has to be,'' Jarboe says.
</P>
<P>
   New Vision Enterprises, a private, nonprofit job-development
foundation for the blind, will fund the gallery through
contributions and a small commission from art sales. Visitors will
be admitted free to the gallery, which is across from a local
landmark -- the Louisville Slugger Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Jarboe expects the gallery to draw curious visitors, and
predicts the art will open their eyes to the abilities of the
blind.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just for the blind and visually impaired, it's for
everybody,'' says curator Albertus Gorman. ''We want people to walk
in and engage the work and learn from it or even want to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman admits he ''did a double take'' when approached about the
job. Once the concept sank in, he was drawn by the gallery's
uniqueness.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're into opening the world for these folks,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As the 60-plus pieces of artwork arrived from Florida to
California for the opening show, Gorman says he has been pleased
with the quality.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the works are exactly as I imagined, both sincere and
accomplished,'' Gorman says, taking a short break from preparing
for the gallery's opening. ''It looks like art to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Such acceptance is welcomed by Mullins, a West Hollywood,
Calif., resident who contributed two paintings to the inaugural
exhibition which runs from June 29 to Aug. 27. She is among 28
artists from seven states whose art will be featured.
</P>
<P>
   Though her works have been shown in galleries, Mullins sometimes
endures long dry spells between sales. Like other artists, she says
she draws inspiration from natural beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Landscapes are very intriguing, especially the sunrise, the
clouds, the ocean and the mountains,'' Mullins says. ''I think it's
so beautiful what Mother Nature does and I try to go from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman says her two paintings for the opening show -- a landscape
and a seascape -- are ''very expressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullins uses her limited sight to capture a scene from a
magazine or on a television documentary. Sometimes she ventures to
locations in the Los Angeles area, but seeing details is difficult.
She is able to capture the outlines of a scene and envisions the
rest, putting her interpretive flair into the painting.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland, who teaches art to the blind, says the lack of sight
can free her students to become uninhibited in their painting.
''Much of the work is not pretentious,'' she said. ''It reflects a
very genuine quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman, former curator for the Louisville Visual Art
Association, finds much of the work charming and personal. ''Some
of the works have a sense of humanity,'' he says. ''It tends to be
more intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   His goal is for the gallery to stage six exhibitions each year.
Some shows may present works of just one or two artists, giving
them the ''kind of validation artists require to build careers,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jarboe's hope is to create a multidimensional cultural center
that also features the talents of sight-impaired writers and
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   And Gibbons plans to be among the visitors. He says the gallery
could inspire others to assist the blind in pursuing their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's another avenue to focus on people's capabilities and what
they do bring as opposed to what they can't do, which is simply
see,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
