<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Victorian Cook Is Flavor of Month  </HEADLINE>
By SUE LEEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- It was 1856, and 20-year-old Isabella Mayson was
planning her wedding to publisher Sam Beeton. But she could find
little information for new brides about running a home.
</P>
<P>
   Mayson was not your average Victorian middle-class woman,
though. A journalist, she decided to produce her own wifely
handbook.
</P>
<P>
   First published in installments between 1859 and 1861, ''Mrs.
Beeton's Household Management'' became the housekeeping bible of
the burgeoning Victorian middle class, offering advice on how to
instruct a scullery maid, deal with childish fits and handle
poisons.
</P>
<P>
   It also offered recipes for such delicacies as turtle soup
(''cut the head off the turtle the preceding day''), ox cheeks and
carrot jam.
</P>
<P>
   Revised many times, the latest brick-sized edition now has been
published under the Oxford University Press' World Classics imprint
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''What makes 'Household Management' a classic is not the
recipes, but the breadth of a complex text which, read closely, has
a perennial relevance,'' Guardian columnist Bel Mooney wrote.
</P>
<P>
   This is no ordinary cookbook. Tucked between the recipes are
snippets of philosophy, poems by William Cowper and the wisdom of
Samuel Johnson, details of natural history, moral advice and
hygiene tips.
</P>
<P>
   Readers learn that the ancient Egyptians adored cabbage, and
that the Roman general Lucullus had a canal cut through a mountain
to bring fish direct to his villa near Naples.
</P>
<P>
   The Beetons married at the start of a new industrial age, when
cities were sprouting suburbs -- caught, as the editor of the new
edition, Nicola Humble, puts it, ''between the old world and the
new, poised between modernity and nostalgia.''
</P>
<P>
   While others campaigned for women's suffrage, Beeton staked out
a woman's position in the home. A wife, she insisted, ''is the
first and last, the Alpha and Omega in the government of her
establishment; and ... it is by her conduct that its whole internal
policy is regulated.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a book of contradictions -- a rigid household charter
written by a woman who ran wild as a child under the grandstand at
Epsom race course, and a harbinger of the horrors of intensive
farming that also nostalgically evokes the days when you could milk
a cow straight into your baking bowl.
</P>
<P>
   On the page opposite a recipe for luxurious turtle soup is Mrs.
Beeton's ''Useful Soup for Benevolent Purposes,'' which she smugly
reports having made in large quantities in 1858 for the poorer
families of west London.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of her philosophy was the need to lure her adored
husband -- the publisher of ''Uncle Tom's Cabin'' -- back home to
suburban west London for dinner, when many men of his class dined
in town.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her offerings, including ''Boiled Calf's Feet and
Parsley and Butter'' and ''Giblet Pie,'' sound unappetizing and are
difficult to procure, but Mooney tried ''Sole in Cream Sauce'' and
found it to be delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the recipes came from readers of the English Woman's
Domestic Magazine, published by Sam Beeton, and from Eliza Acton, a
contemporary food writer who was the first to list ingredients,
quantities and times separate from the cooking method.
</P>
<P>
   Although Beeton tested the recipes in her own kitchen to
establish quantities, she could not specify temperatures for the
variable stoves of the day. But she did offer for the first time
recipes with a known, repeatable outcome.
</P>
<P>
   And she became a lifestyle: The 1861 edition sold more than
60,000 copies and, by 1968, sales had topped 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   She tolerated the new trend for bought food, advising those who
could not make her macaroons to ''purchase such articles at a good
confectioner's.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Beeton's book was embellished to include
luxurious recipes that famously included instructions like ''take
18 eggs'' or ''first catch your hare '' -- what biographer Kathryn
Hughes once called ''domestic porn.''
</P>
<P>
   Humble has pared it back to its sparer origins, in which the
reader can still detect the Victorian emphasis on thrift and
cleanliness (''doorsteps must be cleaned and whitened daily'').
</P>
<P>
   Minute instructions are given on household routine (after a cold
bath at 7 a.m. a wife must supervise her husband's breakfast), and
on protocol (''on entering the kitchen, invariably say, 'Good
morning, cook,' a courtesy much appreciated below stairs).
</P>
<P>
   Mooney believes ''Household Management'' has lasted ''because it
epitomizes an order ... for which there is still a deep craving.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is difficult to read Mrs. B on the importance of family
meals without mourning their passing in this era of TV 'grazing'
when the poor eat badly and the rest watch cookery programs,'' she
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Humble, the editor, adds that Beeton also ''captured the mood of
her time,'' and although young, she reassured readers by giving the
appearance of ''a matronly expert.''
</P>
<P>
   Beeton's own happiness was short-lived. In February 1865, soon
after having her fourth child, she died from a fever. She was only
29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Livelyhood Studies the Night Shift  </HEADLINE>
By DOUGLAS J. ROWE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It's a four-letter word that's on our minds
maybe more than we care to admit: WORK.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as much as it preoccupies so many of us, television largely
ignores that part of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   That's where ''Livelyhood'' comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ''Night Shift,'' the latest installment of the quarterly PBS
series (Friday at 9 p.m. Eastern on many stations), focuses on the
one in five Americans who are on the job while most of us sleep.
</P>
<P>
   It looks at real people who work what's sometimes called the
graveyard shift, and offers a life-affirming hour about the dignity
of work that brings to mind echoes of Bela Lugosi's Dracula saying:
''Children of the night -- what muuuusic they make.''
</P>
<P>
   The program looks at the strains and benefits of the shift,
focusing on, among others, an emergency-room nurse in San
Francisco, a single mother of four at a Lucent Technologies plant
in Allentown, Pa., a cross-country trucker, and a Minnesota woman
who helps her husband manage a dairy farm after her nightly 10
hours at an e-commerce and catalog warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   With factoids that scroll across the screen, we learn about the
downside, including the fact that 73 percent of night-shift workers
have sleeping problems -- and a total of 78 sleep disorders exist.
We see how even for people willingly working overnight, like the ER
nurse, the hands of time move excruciatingly slowly as dawn
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the last hour of my shift,'' she says, casting an eye
toward the wall clock. ''Tick-tock, tick-tock.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the upside is voiced by a security guard at a Times
Square office building: ''In the daytime, everybody moving is your
boss. You understand? And you really gotta be on your toes. After 5
o'clock, you might as well say, 'I'm in charge of the whole
building.'''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-based political humorist Will Durst serves as
series host and sounds particularly qualified for the post: He says
he's had 108 jobs in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''Livelyhood,'' which debuted in 1997, aims ''to give normal
people a voice,'' says the 47-year-old Durst, a self-described
third-generation blue-collar guy who grew up in West Allis, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mostly instead of going to experts to find out what's
happening with work, it's going to the people who are experiencing
the problems and the people who are coming up with the solutions,''
says Durst, who has several jobs now besides working half of his
time on ''Livelyhood'' -- standup comedian, columnist on the Web and
commentator on National Public Radio. ''It's a solution-oriented
show, I would like to think.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is. When someone on the program says the ''toughest part
of working nights is getting a good night's sleep, starting at 9
a.m.,'' Durst segues into a segment of helpful hints punctuated
with visual gags.
</P>
<P>
   While his voiceover notes that among the don'ts is drinking
alcohol before hitting the rack, Durst is swigging from a tequila
bottle. And while suggesting that among the do's is reading a
''soothing book,'' Durst is abed reading ''The Silence of the
Lambs'' and looking terrified.
</P>
<P>
   If ''Night Shift'' has a problem, it's that it tries to pack too
much in. The real people we see ARE interesting, as Durst suggests,
but we don't get an in-depth sense of their travails and
adaptability.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the program fills a void. With some notable exceptions,
the same few professions repeatedly are depicted on television, and
even if a drama or sitcom is set at a workplace, most of the action
has little or nothing to do with the job.
</P>
<P>
   The series has been accused of taking a Panglossian look at
working, but Durst responds: ''It's not our job to be pollyanna on
PBS. That's not who we're trying to be. But we are looking for
solutions, and we're looking for people who can share something in
the positive area that can help everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Durst, who gained some notoriety earlier this year as a
''lifeline'' on the game show ''Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' by
giving a contestant the wrong answer, has a ready answer to the
question: Why would anyone want to come home from work and watch a
show about work?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something that we do for half of our waking life.
Somebody might be interested in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.pbs.org/livelyhood
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
   NEWFANGLED BONNIE AND CLYDE?: FBI agents say they are the
modern-day version of Bonnie and Clyde: two bank robbers who are
also lovers. ABC News correspondent Chris Cuomo reports on the duo
-- 39-year-old Craig Pritchert and 27-year-old Nova Guthrie -- who
are suspected of robbing more than 12 banks in the West.
Pritchert's high school friends say he was a top athlete with
dreams of a career in pro baseball, while Guthrie is a small-town
girl, raised by fundamentalist parents. What turned them to a life
of crime? Find out on ''20/20 Downtown'' tonight at 10 p.m.
Eastern.
</P>
</TEXT>
