<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of July 2-8:
<TEXT>
<P>
   70 years ago: Lon Chaney starred in ''The Unholy Three,'' his
only sound film.
</P>
<P>
   45 years ago: ''The Lawrence Welk Show'' debuted on ABC-TV. The
program ran for 27 years, both on the network and in syndication.
</P>
<P>
   And ''Baby Let's Play House'' was Elvis Presley's first national
chart single, reaching No. 10 on Billboard's country chart.
</P>
<P>
   35 years ago: Marty Balin and Paul Kantner formed a folk-rock
group that eventually became the Jefferson Airplane.
</P>
<P>
   And ''Catch Us If You Can,'' a feature film starring the Dave
Clark Five, premiered at the Rialto Cinema in London.
</P>
<P>
   25 years ago: Pink Floyd headlined the Knebworth Pop Festival
near London. The band performed a spectacular show that included
real Spitfire planes and quadraphonic sound.
</P>
<P>
   20 years ago: Robert Hays, Julie Hagerty, Lloyd Bridges and
Leslie Nielsen starred in ''Airplane!''
</P>
<P>
   The Beach Boys gave a free concert in Washington, D.C., attended
by 500,000 fans. The Fourth of July concert became a regular date
on the band's calendar throughout the decade.
</P>
<P>
   And the original lineup of Led Zeppelin played what would be its
final concert, at Eissporthalle in West Berlin. The concert
occurred on the 12th anniversary of the breakup of the Yardbirds,
which gave birth to the group.
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: Blue-collar rocker Bruce Springsteen closed out
his 12-city European tour in Leeds, England, bringing about 80,000
cheering fans to their feet to sing along with him. ''I may have
been born in the U.S.A.,'' Springsteen yelled to the delighted
crowd, referring to the title of his theme song, ''but Europe has
become my hometown today.''
</P>
<P>
   And ''Back to the Future,'' starring Michael J. Fox, opened in
theaters across the country.
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: Bruce Willis starred in ''Die Hard 2,'' directed
by Renny Harlin.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: The Grateful Dead performed at Chicago's Soldier
Field. It would the band's last concert with lead guitarist Jerry
Garcia, who died one month later.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: The rock group Eurythmics staged a miniconcert on
the River Thames in London to announce the band's first major tour
in 10 years, to benefit Greenpeace and Amnesty International.
Appropriately, band members Annie Lennox and Dave Stewart performed
their short set on the Rainbow Warrior II, a Greenpeace vessel.
</P>
<P>
   And the Red Hot Chili Peppers were back after a four-year layoff
following severe drug relapses and another switch in guitar
players. The Los Angeles group consisting of Anthony Kiedis, Flea,
Chad Smith and rehired former guitarist John Frusciante had a new
album ''Californication,'' and the band was back on the road doing
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken 15 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been singing all my life, that was no challenge. But
acting is something that meant getting outside of me and viewing
myself every day.'' -- Tina Turner, on why she accepted a part in
the film ''Mad Max Beyond Thunderdome.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken one year ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to be one of the kid actors that went away. I
never gave up.'' -- Rick Schroder, on joining the cast of ABC's
''NYPD Blue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1214 </TRAILER>
