<DOCNO> APW20000628.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nashville Sound: Western Beat  </HEADLINE>
By JIM PATTERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Early in its first episode, ''Western
Beat With Billy Block'' reveals itself as a different kind of
country music TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it's done: A large man comes on the screen. His name
is Lonesome Bob. He sorely lacks the shape and looks of
country-music pinups Tim McGraw and Bryan White.
</P>
<P>
   But Lonesome Bob's sing-along about a woman who can't quite put
her finger on why her life is so dissatisfying (''Heather's All
Bummed Out'') is filled with a depth and humor that is missing in
today's mainstream country music.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just try to be honest when I write a song,'' Lonesome Bob
explains during an interview on the show, ''and drunk when I
perform it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Western Beat With Billy Block'' offers a look into a rich side
of the Nashville music scene that doesn't get much exposure. The
show premieres Sunday (July 2) at 11 p.m. Eastern on CMT, a cable
network that reaches about 40 million homes and specializes in
country music videos. The show repeats Monday (July 3) at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Performers on the first show are Lonesome Bob with harmonies
from Allison Moorer, Charlie Robison and Trisha Yearwood. Videos by
Moorer and Kim Richey are included. Promoter Block and his wife
Jill conduct interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Western Beat, also known as Alternative Country or No Depression
music, is country music with the rough edges firmly in place. Some
of the best country music you've never heard comes from this genre.
Although some performers try to pass off amateurism as
authenticity, the good stuff is very good.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the industry as a whole is looking at what we're doing
as possibly the future of country music,'' Block said. ''Music Row
has been serving vanilla for so long, and I'm offering
Neapolitan.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is expecting Western Beat music to topple Shania Twain
from the top of the charts, but some in Nashville believe it can
attract a new audience.
</P>
<P>
   There's some evidence that it could work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Transcendental Blues,'' the new album by alternative country
star Steve Earle, sold 20,000 copies during its first week of
release, good enough to debut at No. 5 on the country album chart
with virtually no airplay from country radio stations. Moorer,
Robison and Eric Heatherly have snagged record deals in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   All that's missing is a breakthrough hit or artist to convince
radio programmers that there is an appetite for rawer music.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to combine the mainstream with the alternative.
Sometimes (mainstream country music) seems a little too
manufactured, a little too contrived. There's a reality factor
that's kind of missing for me,'' Block said.
</P>
<P>
   Yearwood, one of mainstream country's brightest stars, agrees.
She hopes her appearance on the show will draw an audience to
Lonesome Bob and other Western Beat artists.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've lived in Nashville for 15 years,'' Yearwood said. ''I
wanted to find a way to support the local cool things that are
going on in this town. ... It's a good way to draw attention to
something that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Block started doing live Western Beat shows at clubs around
Nashville in 1996. He patterned his shows after the weekly Ronnie
Mack Barn Dance shows at the Palomino Club in Los Angeles, where
Block was the house drummer for nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now based at the Exit/In nightclub, the shows are the
centerpiece of a growing Western Beat empire that includes a radio
show, magazine, Internet site and record label. ''It has
exploded,'' Block said. ''So obviously there's an audience for this
music.''
</P>
<P>
   CMT hopes the show will attract new viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we didn't think that it had mass appeal, we wouldn't be
doing it. It's that simple,'' said Chris Parr, head of programming.
''I think that someone in Atlanta would enjoy this because it's
entertaining, but I also think it might be that one thing that
grabs someone's attention who's watching in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully, it will make them realize that this country music
really isn't so bad after all.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Western Beat home page on the Web is:
http://www.westernbeat.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
