<HEADLINE> Panel: Customs Needs Outside Advice  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Customs Service, accused of harassing
minorities, should get outside experts to review techniques that
agents use to decide which airline passengers to stop and search,
according to an independent panel.
</P>
<P>
   That was among the recommendations included in the four-member
panel's report aimed at improving the agency's personal search
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released Wednesday, was based on a year of work and
visits to 14 airports that handle 66 percent of the air passengers
arriving in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also suggested that the Customs Service seek judicial
approval ''at the first opportunity'' after determining that a
passenger should be detained. In general, customs officials can
detain passengers for long periods of time without court approval.
</P>
<P>
   Customs, in a new policy announced last year, said it would seek
legal advice from U.S. attorneys whenever it wants to hold an
airline passenger for more than eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly has taken a number of steps
to address allegations of unfairly targeting minorities and of
abusive searches including setting up the panel in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly has repeatedly stated that the agency does not use racial
and ethnic profiling as part of its procedures to select passengers
to stop and possibly search.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, agents operate on, among other things, training
information on smuggling trends, patterns of past seizures,
intuition and experience. They make observations on behavior and
physical condition, ask questions and analyze documents.
</P>
<P>
   These factors should be ''reviewed by professionals outside the
Customs Service to determine whether they are based on stereotypes
and for the findings of that review to be made public,'' the report
said. Psychologists or sociologists should be part of that review.
The panel also suggested customs bring in outside diversity experts
to help train agents.
</P>
<P>
   A General Accounting Office report, released earlier this year,
found that black women were much more likely than other passengers
to be subjected to strip searches and X-rays. The report was based
on 1998 data.
</P>
<P>
   Customs' searches are intended to catch smugglers who hide
cocaine or heroin inside their clothes or who swallow drug packets.
The searches usually begin with a pat-down and, with reasonable
suspicion, can proceed to a partial or full strip search, an X-ray
or a monitored bowel movement.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also recommended customs simplify paperwork associated
with body-scanning machines -- which can detect whether a passenger
is concealing drugs under clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The report said only 13 percent of passengers given the option
of the body scan have chosen it over the body search. Many
passengers have complained that it takes more time, in part because
of the time to fill out forms before the scanning.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was chaired by Constance Berry Newman, former
undersecretary at the Smithsonian Institution. Other members were
Hubert Bell, a 29-year veteran of the Secret Service, now at the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission; Robin Renee Sanders, a State
Department official, previously with the National Security Council;
and Ana Maria Salazar, the Defense Department's deputy assistant
secretary for drug enforcement policy and support.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Customs' web site: http://www.customs.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
