<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paul Revere, Raiders Still Rocking  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF SIMONS
<TEXT>
<P>
   TESUQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Party on, Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the past 40 years, Paul Revere and the Raiders have
carved out a niche as America's quintessential rock 'n' roll
pranksters.
</P>
<P>
   ''From day one, we've always been a party band that accidentally
had some hit records and accidentally got on a hit television
series,'' said Revere, 62, outfitted in a Revolutionary War-era
tunic, epaulettes, knee-high boots, black jodhpurs and a plumed
colonial tricorn hat.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, at the Camel Rock Casino, Revere and company
resurrected the era of eight-tracks and AM Top 40 hits. During a
two-hour set, the band punched out tight covers of ''Gimme Some
Lovin','' ''Great Balls of Fire,'' ''Joy to the World'' and Joe
Cocker's gritty rendition of ''With a Little Help From My
Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   In between, with Revere perched behind the facade of a mock
Edsel, the Raiders strutted through a sampling of originals that
included ''Kicks,'' ''Good Thing,'' ''Him or Me...What's It Gonna
Be?'' and ''Louie Louie,'' a three-chord dinosaur that was a big
hit for the Kingsmen.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's probably easier to understand our version than the
Kingsmen's, because in their version, the lead singer in the middle
of the song forgot the lyrics,'' Revere said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He started mumbling and repeated a verse and kind of mumbled
through it because he didn't want to sound like he was repeating
himself. And he wore braces and couldn't say 'Lou-ee, Lou-ee,' so
it came out 'Lou-Eye, Lou-Eye.'''
</P>
<P>
   While interpretations about muffled rock lyrics are legion,
Revere has the inside scoop on this classic.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no dirty lyrics in 'Louie, Louie','' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 600 at Camel Rock was a dancing, clapping,
pumped-up mix of twenty-somethings and baby boomers. Even after the
band delivered a full-tilt cover encore of ''Takin' Care of
Business,'' the fans begged for more.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've seen great bands that couldn't keep an audience,'' said
''Crazy'' Dave Rarick, the show's master of ceremonies. ''This band
can. As an oldies band, they're right at the top. Revere is the
last madman of rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders drew big cheers when they dedicated the Animals'
''We Gotta Get Out of This Place'' to all the Vietnam veterans in
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The Raiders) bring back a lot of old memories, and it
especially touched me when they dedicated that song to Vietnam
vets,'' said Roman Solano, a veteran who lives in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   Revere was born Paul Revere Dick, a derivative of the Dutch
VanDyck, in 1938. He grew up on a farm near Caldwell, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, he got a jump-start as an entrepreneur, running
three barber shops and managing his own drive-in restaurant. He
also taught himself to play piano. In the late '50s, he put
together his first band, which quickly developed a strong following
at parties and dances across the state.
</P>
<P>
   His first recording was ''Beatnik Sticks,'' a rock variation on
''Chopsticks.'' A year later, he scored his first big hit, ''Like
Long Hair.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Revere formed a new version of the Raiders and moved to
Portland, Ore. One year later, Revere and the Raiders became the
first rock group to sign with Columbia, recording ''Louie, Louie.''
</P>
<P>
   Their string of 20 consecutive hits during a 15-year period
included ''Just Like Me,'' ''Hungry'' and 1971's ''Indian
Reservation,'' which sold 3 million copies. The band has recorded
26 albums and 41 singles, and has sold more than 50 million
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hard part was the early years -- having the hits,'' Revere
said. ''After you have some success, you're afraid it's gonna go
away and you need to take advantage of it, so you work as hard as
you can, because it might disappear tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess that's part of why I've always worked so hard. It's
because next year, nobody's gonna want to see Paul Revere and the
Raiders.''
</P>
<P>
   The band got its big break in the mid-1960s when Dick Clark's
''Where the Action Is'' TV show was in full stride. Revere and the
Raiders were a regularly featured act in 1965 and 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somebody from (Clark's) company had seen us and recommended us
because we were visual and fun and crazy and were America's answer
to the British music invasion,'' Revere said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Revere and the Raiders co-hosted ''Happening,'' another
Dick Clark production. In the late '60s and early '70s, the band
appeared on hundreds of other TV shows including ''The Ed Sullivan
Show,'' Johnny Carson's ''Tonight'' show and ''The Smothers
Brothers Comedy Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I chased the rock 'n' roll business to see if I could be
lucky, and we were lucky,'' Revere said. ''And I know everybody
likes to hear other reasons for being successful, but in the
entertainment business, it's luck.
</P>
<P>
   ''Had we come along earlier, it would have been too early. If
we'd have come along later, it would have been too late. We just
happened to be at the right time and had the right name and had the
right gimmick.''
</P>
<P>
   That gimmick included flashy costumes, a choreographed martial
two-step and sparring guitarists.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I started my band, I wanted them to move,'' he said. ''I
hate seeing a band that stands there like they're dead because
people hear with their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like to see people sweat and move, and if you ain't sweatin'
and you ain't movin', you're in the wrong band.''
</P>
<P>
   The current lineup -- Dan Krause (keyboards), Carl Driggs
(vocals), Ron Foos (bass), Omar Martinez (drums and vocals), Doug
Heath (guitar) and Revere (keyboards) -- has played together for 20
years and averages 150 to 200 shows a year.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, Heath and Foos were part of the Raiders when Mark
Lindsay, the band's original lead singer, left in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Revere rests a little easier on his laurels.
</P>
<P>
   ''As time goes on, the work is always going to be there because
your fans grow up with you,'' he said. ''And until they die,
somebody's going to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The official Paul Revere and the Raiders Web site is:
http://www.paulrevereraiders.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
