<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diana Ross: This Time I Can Enjoy It  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN ROGERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The best thing about being a Supreme again,
says Diana Ross, is that this time, she really gets to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   The first time, Ross was just out of her teens -- and Detroit's
rough-and-tumble Brewster Projects -- with one overriding ambition:
to sing. And there she was, singing with one of the biggest pop
groups of its time.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of Beatlemania in 1964, the Supremes strung
together six consecutive No. 1 hits, starting with ''Where Did Our
Love Go.'' By the end of the decade, they had 12, ending with
''Someday We'll Be Together.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you can be looking too far into the future or too
inside your own head,'' Ross said of those days. ''This time, it's
like when you're sitting outside and you really see the trees. You
know what I mean? I'm really seeing the audience this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 56, she believes it's time to be a Supreme again, that
for at least one summer it can be 1964 again. It can be a time when
three young women from Detroit put on the most outlandish evening
gowns and sang and danced their way into the public's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very interesting time in my life,'' Ross said from her
home in Connecticut. ''It's like going full circle and coming back
and just watching the journey.''
</P>
<P>
   She had just returned from Atlanta, where she performed as part
of Diana Ross and the Supremes for the first time in 30 years,
before an audience of 16,000 delighted fans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to ask the audience to sit down so I could sing to
them,'' said Ross, speaking in an excited, nonstop,
stream-of-consciousness, hardly-got-time-to-take-a-breath rush of
exuberance, as she recounted the show.
</P>
<P>
   She sounded like a happy school kid who had just aced a test,
which is at odds with her better-known image as the icy-cool diva.
But this is the one, she said, that is really her.
</P>
<P>
   ''As you can see, I'm long-winded. For that, I apologize,'' she
giggled with embarrassment when she finally came up for air.
</P>
<P>
   But for Ross, there's so much to do this year and so little time
to stop and talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   First came the weeks of rehearsals with the newly constituted
Supremes, backup singers Scherrie Payne and Lynda Laurence.
Although both are former members of the group, they didn't join
until well after Ross had left in 1970, and had never worked with
her.
</P>
<P>
   She said the new trio quickly clicked. ''There's just so much
love and respect between us that it just makes me very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she would have liked for things to have come together
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ''Absolutely. I wish, I wish, I wish,'' she said when asked if
there is sadness that Mary Wilson and Cindy Birdsong, her
contemporary Supremes, aren't there, negotiations with them having
broken down.
</P>
<P>
   But the odd thing, she said, is that she never intended to bring
the group back together.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had recorded a new album and we were going on tour to
promote it,'' she said. ''The promoters said maybe it would be nice
to have a nice segment of Supremes songs to help sell the tour. I
said, 'Sounds like a good idea to me.'
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, I don't know how it got on the Internet and in the
media, but suddenly it was everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The word was the Supremes were getting back together.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was doing the Image Awards show, and you know how you go
down the red carpet when you walk in there?'' Ross continued. ''I
was doing that and the fans and the press were all there saying to
me, 'Is this really going to happen?'
</P>
<P>
   ''I finally turned to them and I said, 'Is this what you guys
want? Because if it is, I'll try to make it happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   So she contacted Wilson, her Supremes co-founder, and Birdsong,
who had replaced the group's other founding member, the late
Florence Ballard, in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ''I called them and said, 'Have you been hearing the rumors?'
And of course they had. So I said, 'What I need to know from you
guys is are you willing to make a commitment for 30 shows for the
summer?'''
</P>
<P>
   When they said they were, Ross turned the matter over to the
show's producers.
</P>
<P>
   ''And that's the last I heard from Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   The next the public heard was that Wilson was balking at going
on the road for 15 or 20 times less money than Ross would get. Then
Wilson and Birdsong were out and Payne and Laurence were in.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just don't think that Mary had the vision at all to
understand that this was not about money,'' said Ross, whose
handlers point out she is contributing a portion of her earnings to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really think it's shortsighted, if you know what I mean.
Because five years from now, we wouldn't be able to do this tour.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it's getting harder for her to sing ''Baby Love''
and ''Love Is Here and Now You're Gone'' in the same high register
she used in her 20s.
</P>
<P>
   But she insists that she will sing all of her old hits in the
keys she recorded them in. Even ''Love Child.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really high. It has those, you know, those 'Ohhhh, ohhhh,
ohhhhs' at the end,'' she said, bursting into song to demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   With mild embarrassment, she quickly caught herself. ''No! I'm
not even going to try to sing for you. Not today,'' she laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there aren't plenty of other songs she can still do
easily. Since leaving the Supremes, she has had a string of hits,
including ''Reach Out and Touch (Somebody's Hand),'' ''Upside
Down'' and ''Good Morning Heartache.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been several movies as well, most notably ''Lady
Sings the Blues,'' which earned her an Oscar nomination for her
portrayal of Billie Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   She credits her varied success to Berry Gordy Jr., the Motown
mogul who shepherded her career from its earliest days with the
Primettes, the forerunner of the Supremes that put out eight failed
singles before changing its name and finally hitting with ''Where
Did Our Love Go.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Berry Gordy was absolutely visionary in my career because all
I wanted to do was sing,'' she said. ''We used to say we were a
team. If he could dream it, I could do it. I have always said if
somebody believes in me, I'll figure out a way to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
