<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regis Brings Fashion to Masses  </HEADLINE>
By FRANCINE PARNES
For The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Former Cosmopolitan editor Helen Gurley Brown
once joked that it took an act of Congress to get men out of the
basic white shirt and regulation tie.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, it is quiz-show host Regis Philbin, a newly minted
menswear purveyor, who is legislating this summer's hot new look, a
cotton men's dress shirt with the same-color glossy necktie, both
in solids, in black, tan, blue or green.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings powerhouse attracted a crowd that snaked out the
door and on to the sidewalk at Macy's Herald Square during the
recent launch of the Regis by The Van Heusen Company label.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Cole, Richard Tyler, Hugo Boss and Joseph Abboud have
sent the monochromatic look down the runways. And a squadron of
Hollywood's hottest, from Tom Cruise to Tom Hanks, have worn it on
the red carpet. But it took Philbin, host of ABC's ''Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire,'' to bring it to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll probably see (the Regis look) in middle America in
droves only because, remember, his 'Millionaire' show is the
top-rated show across America; it's a phenomenon and it's on
several nights a week. Now that's what I call penetrating a
market,'' said Mike Cannon, men's fashion editor at Town &AMP; Country
magazine, who expects the Regis-label ensemble to saturate Kiwanis
Clubs across the heartland, even if it doesn't show up at
social-page soirees.
</P>
<P>
   ''Regis Philbin is cool to a lot of guys -- real men, not
style-setters,'' said Cannon. ''I think his universal appeal will
penetrate the country much like the Farrah Fawcett hairstyle and
the pashmina (shawl) did for women, and the Cabbage Patch doll did
for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no accident. ''What made this so exciting is that Regis
had the ability to not only introduce fashion to mass America,''
said Lee Terrill, president of Van Heusen, ''but give it an
acceptability and a comfort level. We are getting calls from all
over America and Canada because people feel like they know him.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend ''might prove that men are less influenced by fashion
designers and runway presentations than the industry would like to
believe,'' said Karen Alberg, editor of MR, a menswear trade
magazine. ''Television and music and sports today are far more
important to the typical American man.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Pacers basketball coach Larry Bird wore a beige
shirt-and-tie combo during this season's NBA finals. And the host
and two commentators on CNBC's ''Squawk Box'' gave the Regis look a
recent tryout on the early morning financial news program.
</P>
<P>
   Van Heusen projects retail sales of $50 million for the Regis
line this year. ''We found that despite the fact this look is not
fashion-forward or new, a lot of America really didn't relate to it
or wasn't aware of it,'' Terrill said.
</P>
<P>
   The ''dark tonal look where the tie almost blends into the
shirt'' was launched on runways about two years ago, Alberg said.
It became popular at the higher end, thanks to Calvin Klein,
Giorgio Armani and other prominent designers.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the typical middle-America consumer always associated ties
with bright red or yellow; that power-tie look of bold stripes that
contrast to the shirt,'' she said. ''This monochromatic look was
the exact antithesis, so it never caught on at the middle level.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it has a bright future. Men relate to clothes that take the
guesswork out of getting dressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't go wrong even if you wanted to,'' said Elina Kazan,
public relations director of Macy's East. ''It's like gift-giving
101.''
</P>
<P>
   Launched at her Herald Square store as $77.50 boxed sets, the
shirts, about $40 to $45, and ties, about $38 to $42, will be
rolled out at department and specialty shops nationwide mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   The look has legs, said trend analyst Tom Julian of Fallon
advertising agency. ''As I have traveled around the country, (I see
that) it should continue strong as a trend for the fall as well as
the holiday season. The shirt-and-tie market has been quiet through
the end of the '90s, and now the renewed interest is a direct
result from Regis.''
</P>
<P>
   The shirt-and-tie combo just might reinject the $56
billion-a-year menswear industry with a turn away from casual
Friday clothing, Alberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks like there is a resurgence in dressing up,'' she
said, noting recent increases in sales of suits and ties.
''Executives are frustrated with how shlumpy the whole casual thing
has gotten. Now there's somewhat of a backlash to all this casual
dressing in the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a rebirth,'' Cannon said. ''Six months ago, people were
saying, 'The tie is dead. The tailored shirt is dead. The suit is
dead.' If Regis has piqued even 100 people's interest in more
sartorial dressing, God love him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cannon, recently named to the International Best-Dressed Poll,
added, ''It's not my favorite look by any means. But I'd much
rather see a man in a tone-on-tone Regis shirt and tie than in a
generic polo shirt and Capri pants and sandals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
