<HEADLINE> Serbs Mark First Loss of Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE JAHN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OBILIC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a bitterly symbolic ceremony, Serb
religious leaders Wednesday commemorated their first loss of Kosovo
centuries ago, little more than a year after Serbs were forced to
accept another defeat in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Patriarch Pavle, head of the Serb Orthodox Church, preached a
nonpolitical message to the small crowd of priests, nuns and other
Serb faithful gathered at the stone monument marking the loss of
Kosovo to the Turks in 1389.
</P>
<P>
   As black-robed clergy swung incense burners and others lit
beeswax candles in memory of past heroes, Pavle urged the gathering
to pray for ''those who shed their blood for the cross.''
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, he was more outspoken. In comments alluding
to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, the frail, white-bearded
churchman blamed Serb defeats on ''leaders who messed things up
leaving the people to suffer for their mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   In separate comments critical of Milosevic, Father Sava Janjic
said that unlike the battle against the Turks, led by Serb Prince
Lazar, ''in the last Kosovo battle, we didn't have a noble prince
but a criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Kosovo belongs to the people who live here,'' he added. ''It
cannot belong to only Serbs or (only) Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   The monument, erected a former battlefield just north of
Pristina where a Serb-led Christian army was defeated by Ottoman
Turk forces more than 600 years ago, also has a more recent place
in Kosovo history.
</P>
<P>
   It was from here in 1989 that Milosevic set loose the Serb
nationalism that he used to climb to power as he unleashed wars
first in Croatia, then in Bosnia and finally in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Serb history books define Kosovo as the heart of medieval
Serbia, a land of Slavic culture and religion with few, if any,
ethnic Albanians among them.
</P>
<P>
   Serb dominance began to fade on June 28, 1389, with the Turkish
defeat. But over the centuries, the loss grew into a mythological
triumph of the Serb soul and became the founding legend of Serb
nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   In a fiery speech 11 years ago, Milosevic told hundreds of
thousands of cheering Serbs that their dominance would never be
questioned -- in Kosovo and elsewhere in Yugoslavia. His resulting
popularity allowed him to back Serb rebellions, first in Croatia
and then in Bosnia, even as he cracked down on Kosovo's ethnic
Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   He lost both those wars, and support for him plummeted. Still --
because of the special place Kosovo holds in the hearts of most
Serbs -- he again managed to rally popular sentiment against
Kosovo's Albanians. The fight was lost this time to NATO, which
last year forced a Kosovo settlement through 78 days of bombing
that made Milosevic pull his forces out and let NATO peacekeepers
in.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands would gather at the tall stone marker to
commemorate the battle against the Turks in past years, when the
Serbs still ruled.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear sign of how things have changed, no more than 100
people came Wednesday -- all under heavy NATO and U.N. police
escort. NATO peacekeepers swept the area for mines the day before
the ceremony and surrounded the monument with armored vehicles and
sandbagged fortifications to prevent possible attack from Kosovo's
new masters -- the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 100,000 Serbs remain in Kosovo, less than half of
their original number. Most others have fled the rash of attacks by
members of the ethnic Albanian majority seeking to avenge the Serb
crackdown ordered by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Dragan Todorovic was in the crowd listening to Milosevic 11
years ago. On Wednesday, his eyes lit up as he reminisced about the
heady emotions the speech aroused.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were all sky high, nothing could stop us then,'' he said.
''Now, our souls are blackened by fear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1218 </TRAILER>
