<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-CT--Murder in Greenwich, 3rd Ld-Writethru,600  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - Robert F. Kennedy Jr. and other members
of his extended family turned out Wednesday to support Michael
Skakel, accused of beating a Greenwich teen-ager to death in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's father, Rushton Skakel Sr., is a brother of Ethel
Kennedy, the widow of Sen. Robert F. Kennedy. Robert Jr. and Skakel
are cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel is charged in juvenile court with beating Martha Moxley
to death on Oct. 30, 1975. Both he and Moxley were 15 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing that began last week and continued Wednesday will
determine whether there is enough evidence to proceed with the case
against Skakel, and whether he should be tried as a juvenile or as
an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Jr. said Wednesday that he and Mrs. Kennedy want to
support Skakel.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a horrible, unspeakable tragedy, but it only compounds
it to blame Michael Skakel, who is innocent,'' Kennedy said. He
said Mrs. Kennedy was planning to attend Wednesday's court session
but had to cancel at the last minute because of a family
obligation.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Michael Sherman began presenting his case
Wednesday, calling a former student at the Elan School, a
residential drug and alcohol treatment center in Maine which Skakel
attended as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   Last week two former students at the school testified that
Skakel had confessed to them that he killed Moxley, who was
bludgeoned with a golf club. The 6-iron used in the murder was
traced to a set owned by the Skakels.
</P>
<P>
   One student, John Higgins, said Skakel confessed to him one
night 20 years ago during an erratic, tearful conversation. But
Higgins admitted he lied to investigators when they initially
questioned him about the alleged confession. He also admitted
asking about a $50,000 reward.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Coleman, another former Elan student, said Skakel told
him he drove Moxley's skull in with a golf club and declared: ''I'm
gonna get away with murder. I'm a Kennedy.'' Coleman went on to
describe his own life - filled with alcoholism, drug addiction, a
criminal record, homelessness, and living under a bridge at times.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, former student Alice Dunn said she never heard
Skakel admit to killing Moxley, even while undergoing therapy that
involved being pummeled in a boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   ''He denied vehemently, over and over again, 'No, no, no, no!'''
Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel was subjected to the treatment after he ran away from
Elan, Dunn testified. The ring was used to break down students'
resistance and force them to confront the root cause of their
emotional problems, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear from the testimony whether school employees or
other students struck the patients in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn cast doubt on Higgins, saying he had ''a terrible
reputation for truthfulness'' and that she doubted Skakel would
confide in him.
</P>
<P>
   She also said she was present during a ''primal scream'' therapy
session and disputed allegations by Coleman that Skakel confessed
during the session.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict,
Dunn admitted telling the one-judge grand jury investigating the
case that Skakel had made statements indicating he was involved in
Moxley's death.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict said her grand jury testimony included a recollection
that Skakel said, ''I don't know if I did it myself, or my
brother.''
</P>
<P>
   On another occasion, she said, Skakel told her that ''as far as
he was concerned, he might have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   But she insisted that Skakel never confessed to the crime to her
and that she never heard of a confession while she was at the
school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
