<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 50 Years Ago, Greatest Soccer Upset  </HEADLINE>
By BRIAN TRUSDELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The score flashed across the news wires: England
0, United States 1. Newspaper editors throughout Britain
immediately assumed it was an error, and the actual score was
England 10, United States 1.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the many legends that grew from the World Cup
game in Belo Horizonte, Brazil, on June 29, 1950. And no, it was
not a mistake. It was, instead, the greatest upset in World Cup
history.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's 50th anniversary has rekindled memories of a game
that has taken on epic proportions in the soccer world.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the stories about the match, none is more indicative of
its mythical nature than Charlie Colombo's late-game tackle of
England's Stanley Mortensen.
</P>
<P>
   In about the 80th minute, with England repeatedly pushing
forward looking for the tying goal, Mortensen broke free of Colombo
and was bearing down on U.S. goalkeeper Frank Borghi.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then Charlie takes a headlong dive and hits him at the
knees,'' U.S. right back Harry Keough recalled. ''Most (American)
football guys don't tackle that well.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something he should have been thrown out of the game
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombo grabbed Mortensen just outside the penalty area, but by
the time they stopped tumbling, they were on top of the penalty
spot. Referee Generoso Dattilo immediately whistled a foul and a
free kick, but instead of ejecting Colombo, the Italian ref
supposedly came up to him wagging his finger, saying ''Buono, buono
(Good, good)!''
</P>
<P>
   ''Charlie claimed that to his dying day,'' Keough said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to England's frustration, on the ensuing free kick, Billy
Mullen bounced a header downward that got behind Borghi. But Borghi
reached back and palmed it away for Keough to clear.
</P>
<P>
   England claimed the ball crossed the line, but Dattilo said no.
</P>
<P>
   That was England's last gasp, to the delight of about 20,000
fans at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ''The longer the game went on, the more the crowd was on our
side,'' said Walter Bahr, the U.S. left halfback. ''I'm sure they
were expecting a slaughter. I thought a three- or four-goal loss
would have been respectable.''
</P>
<P>
   Borghi was expecting an even bigger defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought when we did score a goal, the roof would cave in and
they would score like crazy,'' he said. ''I was hoping to keep them
to six or seven goals.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a disastrous day for English sports, with the national
cricket team routed by the West Indies. As the Daily Herald wrote
in its front-page headline: ''England lose by 1 goal and 326
runs.'' And another headline read, ''England Fall to U.S.
Amateurs.''
</P>
<P>
   By the strictest definition, the Americans weren't amateurs.
Bahr was getting all of $25 a game playing with the Philadelphia
Nationals at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But Bahr also was a school teacher; Joe Gaetjens a dishwasher;
Keough a postman; Borghi was driving a hearse; and Gino Pariani was
working the line at Continental Can Company.
</P>
<P>
   The English lineup had Alf Ramsey and Tom Finney, both of whom
would go on to be knighted for their soccer exploits.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the result was met with little fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times ran a story on the fourth page of its sports
section, behind baseball, Wimbledon, a track meet between the
United States and Finland in Helsinki, and a local women's amateur
golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Only one American reporter traveled with the U.S. team to the
World Cup -- Denton McSkimming of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, who
was there on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   There was some controversy about the makeup of the U.S. squad.
Three players weren't even Americans: Gaetjens was from Haiti, Joe
Maca from Belgium and Eddie McIlvenny from Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Eligibility rules were looser in those days and the U.S. Soccer
Football Association used players who merely had declared their
intention to become citizens. Later in 1950, FIFA would absolve the
USSFA of any wrongdoing. Maca was the only one of the three who
later became a citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans didn't exactly outplay the English, who were
plagued by poor finishing. Shots went high, wide and off the
crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The goal by Gaetjens wasn't particularly artistic, either.
</P>
<P>
   ''The right wing (Bahr) came down, moved inside and took more of
a shot than a center,'' recalled England fullback Laurie Hughes.
''And the ball struck (Gaetjens) on the side of the head and ended
up in the top corner of the net. I consider that a fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Borghi remembers is being carried off the field by the
locals.
</P>
<P>
   ''They carried me to the clubhouse,'' Borghi says. ''They picked
up Gaetjens, they picked up John Souza and carried him off.
</P>
<P>
   ''People came at us and I didn't know if they were mad at me or
what.''
</P>
<P>
   England's players for the most part conceded they were beaten
fairly, although some groused about the result.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pitch wasn't very good and the dressing rooms were bad,''
halfback Billy Wright told the London Daily Mail in 1993. ''But we
lost, history was made and they will never let us forget it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
