<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Envirotest to pay $1 million to guard against fraud  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Stung by allegations that its inspectors
were taking bribes, the company that runs Connecticut's auto
emissions testing centers is spending $1 million to safeguard
against future problems.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland announced Wednesday that Envirotest will
pay for 16 more emissions inspectors to be stationed at testing
facilities around the state. Those inspectors will come from the
state Department of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The company also will pay the state as much as $250,000 to hire
a private auditor who will evaluate the company's 25 testing
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, four former testing inspectors pleaded guilty to
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, the leaders of the Legislature's Transportation
Committee said they will hold hearings July 12 to determine how
useful the emissions program has been in cutting down on air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to find out exactly what is going on, where the
problems lie, and what we can do as a legislative body to help
remedy the situation,'' said Sen. Biagio Ciotto, D-Wethersfield.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Sanders, a spokeswoman for Envirotest, said the company
is willing to work with the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very glad the governor and the lawmakers are taking an
interest in the testing program,'' Sanders said. ''Any issues that
crop up we take very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Envirotest agreed to install video cameras to record emission
inspections, and will hire people to review the videotapes of
questionable cases. The company also will require supervisors to OK
re-inspections of vehicles that fail the emissions test and are
re-tested the same day.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are real solutions,'' Rowland said. ''Nothing is 100
percent, but clearly having the supervision will have a huge impact
on the employees there and, most importantly, bring back public
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said he believes the problems with Envirotest are not
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ''The truth is, there have only been five instances of abuse,''
Rowland said. ''Those employees have been fired and we are looking
at some ways to improve the system and return public confidence to
the testing program.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, four Bridgeport residents - Thadius Bullock, 24;
John Ricky Brown, 43; Frank Norris, 28; and Roxann LaFountain, 46 -
pleaded guilty to two counts of second-degree forgery.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State's Attorney Charles Stango said he will recommend
prison time when the four are sentenced in August. However,
Superior Court Judge Burton Kaplan said he may consider imposing
terms of probation instead.
</P>
<P>
   State police said the four would run a ''passed'' car through
the Bridgeport emissions station twice, then use the false report
to cover a failed vehicle after receiving cash from the owner of
the failed car.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Melendez, 21, of Stamford, an inspector at the Darien
station, was later arrested on similar charges. His case is
pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1441 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eagle Scout turned lessons against Boy Scouts  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - James Dale, a troop leader expelled by the Boy
Scouts for being gay, said Wednesday that the scouting organization
will ultimately suffer for its exclusionary policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dinosaurs became extinct because they didn't evolve,'' Dale
said hours after the Supreme Court ruled against him. ''The Boy
Scouts are making themselves extinct, and that's a very sad
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale, 29, said other youth groups have an opportunity to fill a
void created by the Boy Scouts' anti-gay declaration. ''Gay kids
need resources,'' he said. ''Gay kids are coming out at younger and
younger ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale waged a 10-year battle against Boy Scout policy that
considers homosexuality contrary to the oath requiring scouts to be
''morally straight.'' The fight landed at the U.S. Supreme Court
and culminated Wednesday with the high court's 5-4 decision that
the Scouts can bar homosexuals from serving as troop leaders - a
loss for Dale.
</P>
<P>
   Dale lives in New York City and is advertising director for POZ
magazine, which addresses the needs of people who are HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   Friends say he was helped on his legal crusade by a supportive
family and a healthy attitude toward the public spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not gotten a big head and he doesn't enjoy all these
(public appearances), but he's a soldier for the cause,'' said
James Anderson, faculty adviser to the Rutgers University gay and
lesbian organization, through which he became friends with Dale.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's always been very good on his feet, talking from his heart
as well as his head,'' Anderson said. ''So that part has been
relatively easy to him. He's also managed to maintain his life and
his privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in April after the Supreme Court heard
arguments in the case, Dale said he does not consider himself the
leader of a movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only person I am is me, and I've always been true to
myself, and I think that's the most important thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dale - who changed his name before the dispute with the scouts -
grew up in New Jersey, the younger of two sons of Gerald Dick, a
lieutenant colonel in the Army Reserve, and his wife Doris.
</P>
<P>
   He was a Cub Scout at 8, a Boy Scout at 11, an Eagle Scout at
17. At 18, he became an assistant scoutmaster.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from a military high school, Dale attended
Rutgers University. He accepted his homosexuality the summer
between his freshman and sophomore years and joined the campus gay
and lesbian organization, becoming co-president after three months.
</P>
<P>
   It was in that capacity that Dale attended a daylong conference
in 1990 on the struggles of lesbian and gay adolescents. A story on
the conference in the July 8, 1990, Newark Star-Ledger quoted Dale
describing his difficult path toward accepting his homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The article drew the attention of officials at the Monmouth
Council of the Boy Scouts, which 16 months earlier had made Dale an
assistant scoutmaster of Troop 73 in Matawan, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The council revoked Dale's registration, citing ''the standards
for leadership established by the Boy Scouts of America, which
specifically forbid membership to homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale sued the scouts under a 1992 New Jersey law protecting the
civil rights of gay people.
</P>
<P>
   He lost round one in 1995, but last year the New Jersey Supreme
Court ruled unanimously in Dale's favor. The court called the Boy
Scouts a public accommodation to which anti-discrimination laws
apply.
</P>
<P>
   In public comments over the years, Dale has spoken highly of his
scouting experience. He even said he looks forward to rejoining the
national organization if its ban on homosexuality is dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I first learned the definition of morally straight, when
I was 11 years old and in the Boy Scouts, it said to respect and
defend the rights of all people, to be honest and open in your
relationships with other people,'' he told reporters after the
Supreme Court heard his case. ''That's what being morally straight
is all about: standing up for yourself and being honest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1442 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German States Agree on Attack Dogs  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL GEITNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Nadia Rouhani is close to tears as she talks about
the vicious killing of a 6-year-old boy mauled to death in a
schoolyard by two attack dogs as his classmates watched in horror.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're shocked, stunned, full of sorrow and rage,'' said the
mother of two at a protest by worried parents, holding flowers and
pushing their own tots in carriages.
</P>
<P>
   If the government can't keep such ''attack machines'' off the
streets, she asked, ''What are the conclusions? Should we arm
ourselves?''
</P>
<P>
   Months of mounting concern about dangerous dogs on the streets
of German cities exploded into outraged cries for action after
Monday's attack in Hamburg by a pit bull and a Staffordshire bull
terrier.
</P>
<P>
   ''Away with these beasts!'' the nation's most-read newspaper,
Bild, screamed across its front page Wednesday after two more
attacks sent an elderly man and a young jogger to hospitals this
week.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, German officials announced nationwide bans on
breeding and importing attack dogs and other measures, including
possible jail time for violators.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Otto Schily, who had advocated a ban for
months, said the measures would be drafted and presented to the
Cabinet in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that these steps are necessary in view of the
immense danger that comes from such aggressive animals,'' he said.
''It's unacceptable that children especially ... are endangered
because of the quirks of dog owners.''
</P>
<P>
   The action would bring Germany in line with some of its other
European Union neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   A law that took effect in January in France requires dangerous
dogs to be sterilized -- a move aimed at eliminating pit bulls from
France within 10 years. Britain has had a similar law since 1991.
Italy is planning to introduce one this year.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is a country where dogs are coddled, even allowed to
accompany their owners into stores and sit under tables at fancy
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Attack dogs, though, tend to be favored by neo-Nazis and other
young toughs, usually in low-income areas where the dogs are
brandished like weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Some breeders accused the government of going too far with a
ban, saying irresponsible owners are to blame if a dog is trained
to fight, not the animals.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Weder raises pit bulls and Staffordshires as a hobby at
his Top Gun Kennel in Atzendorf, about 90 miles southwest of
Berlin. The three pit bulls he keeps in his apartment have never
posed a danger to his children or anyone else, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're totally normal dogs like any other ... good with
children,'' he said. ''The greatest danger is from the people'' who
raise them improperly.
</P>
<P>
   While the attack in Hamburg was regrettable, he said, the
government's action is ''extremely excessive'' and will hurt
professional breeders.
</P>
<P>
   Although federal and state officials discussed curtailing
ownership and breeding of attack dogs in May, no concerted action
was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is determining which breeds to classify as
attack dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The southern state of Baden-Wuerttemburg drew up a list of 11
banned breeds in 1992, but it was thrown out by a court that said
it violated the rights of dog owners to equal treatment. Some
breeds that weren't on the list -- such as German shepherds or
Rottweilers -- had just as many biting incidents recorded as those
listed, the judges said.
</P>
<P>
   Schily said the Agriculture Ministry will prepare a breeding ban
that will apply not only to pit bulls and Staffordshires but also
to especially aggressive individual animals of other breeds or
mixtures.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin officials intend to require permits for existing pit
bulls, American Staffordshires, and Staffordshire bull terriers.
They would be granted only to adults who can prove the dogs are
needed for protection. The city says it has no estimates of how
many exist, but a similar rule in Munich since 1992 has brought the
number registered there down to four.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of eight other breeds, from mastiffs to Rhodesian
Ridgebacks, will have to get a certificate from a veterinarian
attesting that the dog is not dangerous. Other measures include
requirements that the animals be muzzled and on leashes when in
public places.
</P>
<P>
   The parents who gathered Wednesday outside the federal Interior
Ministry in Berlin say they will continue their protests to make
sure the government follows through on the laws -- and enforces
them.
</P>
<P>
   They note the two dogs who attacked the first-grader in Hamburg,
who was identified only as Volkan S., had bitten three dogs in
April and were supposed to be kept muzzled and on leashes when in
public. They had neither when they jumped over a school fence and
went for the boy's throat.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs' owner faces up to five years in prison if convicted of
negligent homicide.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are five attack dogs I know of in my neighborhood -- one
woman has three,'' said one of the protesters, Angelika Schueller,
a 33-year-old mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   ''So far they haven't attacked anyone,'' she said. ''But I don't
want my children to be the first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1442 </TRAILER>
