<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Gains 102; Dow Rises 101  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks held their gains Wednesday after the
Federal Reserve said it would leave interest rates unchanged for
now but warned that inflation risks remain in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Fed announced its decision, the Nasdaq
composite index was up 101.64 at 3,960.60.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 101.11 at 10,605.57 and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 16.40 at 1,450.55.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were responding enthusiastically to the Fed's decision
to hold interest rates steady. Six rate increases within the past
year have shown some evidence of slowing the economy to a more
sustainable level. Yet the rising rates, which make it more
expensive to borrow money, have also taken a toll on some
companies' earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to hold rates steady was largely expected, but the
Fed gave investors little room to rejoice, warning that inflation
dangers may be lurking and hinting that higher rates could be
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed said it believes the ''risks continue to be weighted
mainly toward conditions that may generate heightened inflation
pressures in the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, certain economic gauges have been pointing to continued
growth. Wednesday morning, the Commerce Department said orders to
U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods shot up 6 percent
in May, led by a burst in demand for electronics equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Economists cautioned that the durable goods data tend to be
volatile, but worried that the report signified that the
manufacturing sector has not cooled off as much as many analysts
had believed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's still a very, very cautious Fed,'' said Michael Strauss,
managing director of Commonfund Asset Management. ''They have some
room to hold off on a tightening now, but the economic numbers in
July and August could paint a picture of a stronger economy than
they really want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The market's gains broadened after the Fed's decision.
Technology and telecommunications stocks fared best, with
Hewlett-Packard rising $7.375 to $124 and JDS Uniphase up $5.125 at
$124.125.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom rose $5.063 to $44.75. Salomon Smith Barney analyst
Jack Grubman ''strongly'' reiterated his buy rating and $87 price
target on the stock, despite the Justice Department's threat to
block the company's proposed merger with Sprint Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint fell $4.75 to $53.625.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which were lower for most of the session, made
some gains. Citigroup rose 81.25 cents to $81.25.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume was running ahead of
Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said end-of-the-quarter buying and selling was
preventing the market from hitting the lull that typically precedes
Fed announcements.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.89 to 514.97.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
