<HEADLINE> Cuba Urges Calm, Dignity for Elian  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cubans arranged a small airport homecoming
ceremony for Elian Gonzalez, and the government urged the public to
remain calm Wednesday after the way was cleared for the boy to
return home.
</P>
<P>
   President Fidel Castro was expected to greet the 6-year-old, his
family and his schoolmates upon their arrival Wednesday night from
the Washington area, where the group had lived together during the
last court appeals by Elian's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's friends in his hometown of Cardenas, meanwhile, were
preparing to travel to Havana to greet Elian as he returned after
seven months in the United States, residents told journalists
there.
</P>
<P>
   The government announced in a statement on state-run television
that the U.S. Supreme Court had refused to hear the appeal of the
Miami relatives, who were seeking to keep Elian in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now more than ever, our population must behave with the most
dignity, serenity and discipline,'' the statement said. ''Let us
remember that at all times, our fight has just begun and that a
long road before us still remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro has said that even after Elian returns, Cubans must not
take a moment's rest in demanding an end to the four-decade-old
U.S. embargo on the island and American policies that allow Cubans
who reach U.S. soil to remain.
</P>
<P>
   In Havana on Wednesday, there were little visible signs that the
country's seven-month-long campaign was nearing an end. Along the
seaside boulevard Malecon, a construction worker plastered a new
poster on a billboard: ''Return Elian to his country.''
</P>
<P>
   The muted reaction by Cubans appeared to be part of a determined
effort by the government to make Elian's return as low-key as
possible in contrast to what government officials have called the
''circus'' that surrounded much of his life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wait with tranquility the triumph of justice and the end of
the kidnapping,'' ran a headline Wednesday in Granma, the official
daily of Cuba's Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, Castro promised there would be no street
celebrations, no parades when the boy returns -- despite a national
campaign in Cuba that put Elian's face on billboards, placards and
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wednesday afternoon, foreign correspondents were
advised of an airport welcoming ceremony that would be televised
live by state television. Castro's official cameraman was expected
to attend, an indication the Cuban leader might personally greet
the boy and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Many Cubans were cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until he arrives, we won't believe it,'' said Ana Julia Villa,
a housewife from the eastern city of Santiago de Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Although plans had called for Elian to live discreetly during
his first three months back in a specially prepared boarding school
in Havana, there are indications he may just return to his hometown
of Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over Elian began in late November when the child was
rescued off the Florida coast. His mother and 10 other people
drowned when their boat sank en route from Cuba to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was turned over to his Miami relatives, who began fighting
to keep him with them. The boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
fought to have the child returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Cubans backed the effort to return the boy to Cuba --
a campaign that has seen over 100 government organized rallies
across the country attended by hundreds of thousands of Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Sambiente, sitting on a park bench in Havana's Parque
Central, said Elian and his family should remain in the United
States because they would have a better life than in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm one of the 50 percent who wants him to stay,'' Sambiente
said. ''The mother wanted him to stay. She died doing that. It was
the last wish of the mother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
