<DOCNO> APW20000628.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Standard and Poor's lowers Nassau's bond rating  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) - A state bailout plan is only a good first
step toward reviving the fiscal health of Nassau County, the Wall
Street agency Standard &AMP; Poor's said Wednesday in announcing
another drop in the county's bond rating.
</P>
<P>
   ''While the county has made limited progress by reducing some
expenses and enhancing some revenues, thus far most of the actions
taken in fiscal 2000 are non-recurring, and therefore do not
benefit upcoming fiscal years,'' S&AMP;P said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The county - where the median annual income is $58,155, one of
the highest in the nation - got into the financial mess in part
because its property tax assessments had not been updated since
1938.
</P>
<P>
   The new rating, triple-B-minus, is just one notch above junk
status but still investment-grade and is assigned a ''stable
outlook,'' S&AMP;P said. The previous rating was triple-B. The lower
the bond rating, the more a municipality must pay in interest on
its borrowing; theoretically, the money lost to interest could have
been used for something else, for instance, youth programs or new
traffic lights.
</P>
<P>
   The rating drop follows a bailout that was approved by the state
legislature earlier this month. The state created an independent
financial oversight board to review the county's finances, and
committed $105 million in bailout funds over the next four years.
For their part, county officials agreed to cut spending about $200
million over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The Nassau Interim Finance Authority held its first meeting
Wednesday and approved more than $50 million in budget cuts.
Without the cuts and the state aid, the county's 2000 budget
deficit had been projected at $117 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think S&AMP;P acted in a professional way,'' said Frank G. Zarb,
chairman of the interim finance authority. ''Frankly, had it not
been for the formation of this august panel ... it would have
turned to junk. And that would have been a pity, because the people
of Nassau County would have had to pay for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Jacobs, the presiding officer of the county legislature,
said she was ''disappointed we were downgraded one notch. ... I
really believe we're on the right track and I think that Wall
Street recognizes that.''
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P noted that it approved of the state action to create the
Finance Authority, but still expressed concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, adverse economic conditions or changing circumstances
are more likely to lead to a weakened capacity of the obligor to
meet its financial commitments,'' S&AMP;P said.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County had been projected to see its budget deficit soar
to $300 million by 2003 before the Finance Authority was created.
If local officials fail to take a fiscally prudent course, the
panel will turn into a formal financial control board with more
direct budgeting powers.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Parolla, the county's Republican comptroller, blamed the
problems on the county going eight of the last 10 years without a
property tax increase while expenses grew because of the county's
contract with police unions and other obligations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1520 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
