<HEADLINE> Terrorism Hearing Postponed in Canada  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- An extradition hearing for an Algerian man
suspected by the United States of links to an alleged terrorist
plot was postponed Wednesday, the second delay in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled Wednesday hearing for Mokhtar Haouari, 31, was
moved back to July 17 to give both sides more time to prepare, said
Ronald Schacter, who is representing the U.S. government in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari faces seven U.S. charges in connection with an alleged
plot by Ahmed Ressam, also Algerian, to smuggle explosives across
the border from Canada. U.S. authorities believe Ressam was
involved in plans to bomb millennium celebrations in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam was arrested in December at Port Angeles, Wash., after
bomb-making materials were found in the trunk of the car he was
driving. He and another Algerian suspect, Abdelmajid Dahoumane,
were charged with several counts, including illegal possession of
explosives. Ressam awaits trial in the United States in February,
while Dahoumane remains on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari arrived in Canada in 1993 and made an unsuccessful claim
for refugee status. Because Canada halted deportations to Algeria
in the mid-1990s due to political instability in the North African
country, Haouari continued to live in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari won his first extradition hearing postponement on June
13, when he showed up for the hearing with a swollen right jaw that
his lawyer said was broken in a jailhouse fight. The case was
delayed until Wednesday to allow Haouari time to recover.
</P>
</TEXT>
