<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philosophical 'shifts' not so dramatic, or one-sided  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - There is the tendency in Albany to see the
just-completed state legislative session as conclusive evidence of
the Republican state Senate's swerve from the right to the middle
philosophically.
</P>
<P>
   But left-of-center Democrats in the state Assembly made some
philosophical concessions, too.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, both sides worked hard to lay claim to the middle
ground heading into the elections of 2000. The lawmakers elected
this November will redraw the lines of the 211 Assembly and Senate
districts for the next five elections, essentially meaning that
control over the Legislature for the next decade will be decided
this Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Both Assembly Democrats and Senate Republicans aim to guarantee
that their pre-eminent positions will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Both majorities clearly concluded that 2000 was not the time for
the ideologues among their ranks to dominate their agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Both were willing to work with each other and Republican Gov.
George Pataki - another middle-grounder - to get the bills passed
they believe their members needed to face the voters this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The two most publicity-grabbing bills approved at the end of the
2000 session were a gun-control measure and legislation creating
special penalties for ''hate crimes.'' Both bills approved were
substantially the same as measures proposed by Pataki and both
concepts were long championed by Democrats in the Assembly and long
opposed by Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Their passage was regarded as either the abandonment of
long-held Senate principles - by those who opposed their passage -
or by supporters as a reasonable acknowledgment by the Senate
Republicans that their continued opposition made less and less
sense.
</P>
<P>
   As Bruno acknowledged repeatedly in the days leading up to the
end of the session, ''times change.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a member of the Senate in its more conservative days,
said it would be wrong to be too cynical about the Senate's
acceptance at last of the hate crimes bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe ultimately, at the end of the day, a majority of the
senators thought that this was the right law for the people of New
York,'' he said. ''I believe they thought it was the right law not
for just political reasons but because they believed, as I did,
that bias crime is something that tears us apart as a society and
should have a higher level of penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Other bills approved by the Senate after opposition in the past
were measures requiring people to be formally notified about the
impending use of pesticides at their neighbors' house and to
require that the work and educational histories of physicians be
made available to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly, meanwhile, accepted a complex sex crimes bill
containing some provisions that its liberal Democratic members have
had problems with philosophically in the past. It also acceded to
the fingerprinting of prospective teachers and other parts of an
anti-school violence package pushed by Republicans which it has
balked at in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said both Assembly Democrats and Senate Republicans
deserve credit for making what were sometimes unpopular choices
internally.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of these issues were difficult and the Assembly has had
difficulty for years in passing them and some others the Senate has
had difficulty passing for years,'' the governor said. ''And we
were able to put aside those differences and put the public
interest first.''
</P>
<P>
   By being amenable to certain issues - sometimes surprisingly so
- the majorities in each chamber in 2000 also accepted many ideas
that were initially proposed by the minority parties in their
chambers. They didn't actually give those minority party
legislators credit, of course, but both Assembly Minority Leader
John Faso and Senate Minority Leader Martin Connor were more than
willing to make the connections where valid.
</P>
<P>
   In the tightly orchestrated and constrained world of the state
Legislature, this is about as close as minority party legislators
will get to participating in a meaningful way in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the gun-control bill, Connor praised Bruno for
having the ''courage to put it out here for a vote,'' knowing that
19 of Bruno's 36 Republicans in the 61-member Senate would vote
against it. That and some other key bills were passed at the end of
the Senate's 2000 session with the help of Democratic votes,
counter to Bruno's usual practice of getting the 31 votes bills
need for approval from among his own Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''That really is what this Senate ought to be, a small 'd'
democratic body where these issues are worked out by
representatives of the people expressing themselves and voting for
the interests of their constituencies,'' Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   On minority party legislators getting credit for being the first
with some issues, Connor paraphrased the late speaker of the U.S.
House, Tip O'Neill: ''There is no limit to what you can accomplish
in a representative body if you're willing to let someone else take
credit for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
