<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate linked to homicides from 1987, 1990  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - Two old Westchester County killings
have been linked to each other - and to a prison inmate - by
investigators who had to wait for DNA technology to catch up with
their suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   County Police Commissioner Louis D'Aliso said Wednesday that a
blood sample taken from Patrick Baxter, 31, connected him to the
slaying of a Yonkers girl in 1987 and a Tuckahoe woman in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ''His DNA was linked to certain evidence found at the scene,''
the commissioner said. He would not elaborate, but both victims had
been sexually assaulted and The Journal News, which first reported
the story, said the evidence was semen collected from both bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Baxter, who is serving a prison term for reckless endangerment
and possession of stolen property, has not been charged in the
killings and the office of District Attorney Jeanine Pirro would
not comment. D'Aliso said additional evidence is being sought but
he expects a grand jury to hear the case against Baxter ''in the
very near future.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no rush on this guy,'' he said. ''We don't think Mr.
Baxter's going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said detectives from the county force and the
Yonkers Police Department began working together in 1995 when they
compared cold cases and ''came up with some common notes of
interest'' - each had a killing in which Baxter had been a suspect:
</P>
<P>
   -Michelle Walker, 14, of Yonkers, was sexually assaulted and
strangled on June 5, 1987, while returning to her home after buying
pizza and milk. Baxter, 18 at the time, lived on the same block.
</P>
<P>
   -Lisa Gibbens, 25, was sexually assaulted and shot in the head
with a shotgun on July 17, 1990, on county property in Tuckahoe. It
was the village's first homicide in 15 years. Baxter's name came
up, though he was never charged, in connection with a shotgun
carjacking in nearby Yonkers a few hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been interested in Mr. Baxter for a number of years,''
D'Aliso said.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal News said the DNA sample taken from the 1987 crime
scene was too small to be tested under existing technology, even in
1995, so detectives decided to wait for a more advanced method. In
the past, a dime-sized sample was needed. Now, the sample can be as
little as a 16th of an inch in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   By this year, the county forensics lab was able to determine
that the same person was involved in both killings. The district
attorney's office then obtained a court order to test Baxter's DNA,
D'Aliso said. Baxter's lawyer, Eugene Traynor, fought the testing,
but an appellate judge refused to block it, and Baxter's blood was
drawn on Friday at a prison in Fishkill.
</P>
<P>
   Traynor did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, technicians matched Baxter's DNA to the crime-scene
evidence, rewarding the investigators' long pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Detectives from both police departments were bulldogs,'' the
commissioner said. ''The tenacity was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Walker's mother, Elaine, also praised the detectives,
saying, ''God sent them to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Baxter, she said, ''I hate him. I know I shouldn't, but I
hate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, an inmate at Sing Sing was linked through DNA
to a 21-year-old killing in Mount Vernon. That was the result of a
1999 law that added robbery to the list of offenses requiring a
convict to supply a DNA sample. Baxter's convictions are not
included in the law, so the court order was needed to obtain a DNA
sample.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1550 </TRAILER>
