<HEADLINE> 12 Russians Killed in Chechen Fight  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Russian soldiers pulled back from a battle
with a large group of rebels in Chechnya on Wednesday after two
days of close combat killed 12 Russians and wounded 16 others,
military officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting began Monday when Russian Interior Ministry troops
approached the town of Serzhen Yurt, southeast of the capital of
Grozny,to conduct document checks and ran into a band of rebel
fighters in nearby woods, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   After a shootout, paratroopers and army special forces units
were rushed to the area and encircled the rebels, government
spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two days of fighting in the forest ensued before troops pulled
back Wednesday to let federal artillery and fighter jets pound the
area, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The battle near Serzhen-Yurt was apparently the fiercest in
Chechnya in weeks. As of Wednesday, 12 Russian soldiers had been
killed and 16 wounded, military officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Yastrzhembsky, speaking on NTV television, said the battle could
last for days, citing previous pitched fights in Chechnya's thick
beech forests.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are adept at evading detection in the wooded slopes
of their republic, which are lush with greenery in the warm
Chechnya summers. They hide in dugout shelters during the day and
move about at night, and have held off vastly larger Russian
detachments for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fighting is continuing,'' Yastrzhembsky said. ''The area
is tightly surrounded,'' while the Russians were bombarding the
rebels, he told NTV television.
</P>
<P>
   The military said up to 60 rebels had been killed by government
fire. The claims could not be confirmed, and Russian officials
often understate their casualties and overstate enemy losses.
</P>
<P>
   The battle began a day after Russia's top general in Chechnya,
Gennady Troshev, said Sunday that all coordinated rebel resistance
had abated.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Europe's top human rights watchdog is debating
suspending Russia's membership over the 9-month-old Chechnya war. A
vote is expected Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Council of Europe has already denied Russia voting rights
until progress is made in punishing perpetrators of human rights
violations in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces took control of lowland Chechnya soon after
entering the republic in September, but have stalled in the
southern mountains. Rebels, meanwhile, have continued hit-and-run
attacks behind Russian lines, inflicting casualties with ambushes,
sniping, car bombs and remote-controlled mines.
</P>
<P>
   Four Chechen men died Wednesday when a bomb exploded inside
their car near the village of Gremenchug, in the same district
where the fighting near Serzhen-Yurt was under way, the Interior
Ministry reported.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen fighters won de facto control of the breakaway region in
a 1994-96 war with Russian forces. Russian forces returned last
year after Chechnya-based militants attacked villages in the
neighboring Russian region of Dagestan, and after about 300 people
died in apartment bombings the government blames on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1556 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
