<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Parliament Targets Hunting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The French parliament adopted a law Wednesday
shortening the hunting season on migrating birds -- a first step
toward bringing France into line with European Union directives it
had been violating.
</P>
<P>
   The National Assembly passed the law 269-255, with 36 deputies
abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   The measure allows hunting from Aug. 10 through Feb. 10, shorter
than the previous July 14-Feb. 28 season. That should reduce the
period when the hunting season may overlap with birds' nesting
period.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the EU decided to take France to court for failing to
guarantee complete protection of wild birds during their return to
breeding grounds and during nesting and rearing.
</P>
<P>
   The new law did not pass without strong opposition. Hunters have
denounced Environment Minister Dominique Voynet, a member of the
Green party who drew up the bill, and at least one National
Assembly deputy used foul language Wednesday when referring to
Voynet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to shortening the hunting season, the law
temporarily lifts a ban on night hunting in some regions, makes
Wednesday a non-hunting day and lets landowners ban hunting on
their property and prevent hunters from crossing their lands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1557 </TRAILER>
