<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Supreme Court Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The Supreme Court took these actions Wednesday:
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Narrowly struck down Nebraska's ban on ''partial-birth''
abortions -- a decision sure to escalate the bitter national debate
over abortion. By a 5-4 vote, the justices said the law violates
women's constitutional rights by imposing an ''undue burden'' on
their decisions to end their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gave states greater leeway to restrict anti-abortion
demonstrations outside health clinics, upholding 6-3 a Colorado law
that bars people from counseling, distributing leaflets or
displaying signs within 8 feet of others without their consent
whenever they are within 100 feet of a health clinic entrance.
</P>
<P>
   -- Said the Boy Scouts can bar homosexuals from serving as troop
leaders, in a 5-4 ruling that may also let the organization reject
gay boys as members. The justices said forcing the Scouts to accept
gay troop leaders would violate the organization's rights of free
expression and free association under the Constitution's First
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   -- Decided 6-3 that taxpayer money can be used to buy computers
and other instructional materials for religious schools. The
decision lowered the figurative wall of separation between church
and state and should speed federal efforts to connect every
American classroom to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rejected a last-ditch effort by Elian Gonzalez's Miami
relatives to keep the 6-year-old shipwreck survivor in this
country, ending a seven-month international custody battle. The
court turned down a formal appeal by the Miami relatives and a
separate emergency request aimed at postponing his departure. The
action was announced in a brief order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
