<HEADLINE> Russians Sparkle in Synchro Swim  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Russians Olga Brusnikina and Maria
Kisseleva turned in a sparkling performance Wednesday to win the
technical routine in synchronized swimming's duet competition at
the European Swimming Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Competing in the 12-day meet's opening event before a sparse
crowd in Helsinki's new swimming arena, the defending champions
collected 34.650 points from the judges.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just the beginning and I don't know what will happen
after tomorrow,'' Kisseleva said. ''But our coaches said it was not
bad, so it's good for us. We believe our coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginie Dedieu and Myriam Lignot, former European champions
from France and runners-up last year, were second with 33.908
points followed by Italians Alessia Lucchini and Maurizia Cecconi
with 33.250 points.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the duet, the free routine, is Saturday with
the final set for later that day. The top 12 pairs out of 19
advance to the final, when only the free routine is performed.
Points from the first two sessions are not carried over to the
final.
</P>
<P>
   The European Championships is the last major meet before the
Sydney Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
