<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Secrets in Zimbabwe  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- The opposition movement that made
sweeping gains in Zimbabwe's weekend elections has denounced
President Robert Mugabe's economic policies, his decision to send
troops to the Congo and his threats to seize white farms.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposition, called the Movement for Democratic Change,
has given few details of its own policies. It plans to keep its
strategies secret at least until it stands across the aisle from
the ruling party in Zimbabwe's colonial-style parliament house.
</P>
<P>
   Movement leader Morgan Tsvangirai, who was defeated in the
legislative election but will run in the 2002 presidential
election, said Wednesday the party will take immediate legal action
to contest 10 election results that they alleged were rigged. He
also announced that party vice president Gibson Sibanda will lead
the parliamentary opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement released after party leaders met for the
first time since they won 57 seats this weekend, Tsvangirai offered
no insights into what their parliamentary strategy will be.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our real work begins now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The labor-backed party Tsvangirai formed just nine months ago is
wise not to show its hand, said Brian Kagoro, legal adviser in the
National Constitutional Assembly, a coalition of reform groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's smart. If there's a time to be ambivalent, it's now,''
Kagoro said. ''Mugabe still controls the coercive arms of the state
and on past form he has never hesitated to use them.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, he said, could be tempted to get into a
''bare-fisted fight'' with Mugabe and his Zimbabwe African National
Union Patriotic Front to appease voters it attracted by tapping
into popular anger, especially among younger voters.
</P>
<P>
   But ''they would be well advised to marry activism with
constraint and, more importantly, work toward building their
experience and public profile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bruising campaign leading up to the parliamentary vote here
left at least 30 people dead and thousands driven from their homes.
Despite alleged voter intimidation, the Movement for Democratic
Change managed to capitalize on discontent with the floundering
economy to make huge gains.
</P>
<P>
   The MDC will control 57 of 150 seats in the new parliament, up
from just three before the vote. It is the first time since
Zimbabwe achieved independence 20 years ago that any opposition has
won enough seats to prevent the ruling party from achieving a
two-thirds majority -- the margin needed to change the constitution
and entrench the autocratic president's powers.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition candidates fell short of the majority needed to
force Mugabe and his party to adopt economic reforms. Mugabe's
party won 62 seats, and the constitution permits him to appoint 30
members to the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   During the election campaign, Tsvangirai's party promised to
fight to restore law and order. Mugabe has allowed ruling party
militants to occupy hundreds of white-owned farms illegally. The
opposition says it also wants to rebuild strained relations with
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Tsvangirai said Tuesday, his newly elected
lawmakers will lead a campaign for change and accountability in
government.
</P>
<P>
   With their new strength, opposition lawmakers should be able to
force the ruling party to disclose policies that until now were not
questioned or publicly aired. Tsvangirai said among these are the
costly and unpopular deployment of 11,000 Zimbabwe troops to back
President Laurent Kabila in the distant Congo civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe had one of Africa's strongest economies at independence
in 1980. Today, it is wracked by corruption and economic
mismanagement. Unemployment and inflation have soared and fuel and
hard currency shortages have crippled agriculture, industry and
transportation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
