<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armstrong Brings Message of Hope  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE GANLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Lance Armstrong saw a message of hope in his Tour
de France victory last year -- an affirmation of life that touched
millions.
</P>
<P>
   With its daunting Alpine peaks and winding passes, the
millennial edition of cycling's premier race, which begins
Saturday, will give the Texan who defeated cancer a chance to
reaffirm the message he pronounced on the victory podium on the
Champs-Elysees:
</P>
<P>
   ''We can return to what we were before, and even better.''
</P>
<P>
   That could serve as the mantra for the 180 riders in the 87th
Tour, a grueling three-week trek around France.
</P>
<P>
   It also could serve as a motto for the Tour, still trying to
recover from a doping scandal that nearly did in the 1998
competition and sullied the image of a beloved summer ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers are so determined to clean up the Tour, they decided
to test for the banned performance-enhancing hormone
erythropoietin, or EPO, which was at the center of the 1998 scandal
-- even though there is no approved testing method. Urine samples
are to be saved for analysis once the test is validated, probably
in three to six months.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the current situation, I don't think we can be more
dissuasive than this,'' the head of the International Cycling
Federation, Hein Verbruggen, told the French sports daily L'Equipe.
</P>
<P>
   Even Armstrong was not spared sneers last year in the French
media, suspicious that drugs helped him to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong replied, indirectly, in a recently published
autobiography ''It's Not About The Bike,'' written with Sally
Jenkins, and, directly, in a television commercial for Nike.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody wants to know what I am on. What am I on? I'm on my
bike ... six hours a day,'' goes the ad.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, subtitled ''My Journey Back to Life,'' Armstrong
says he was transformed in a ''second life'' with his recovery from
testicular cancer. The cancer, diagnosed in 1996, spread to his
abdomen, lungs and brain.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he would rather have the title of cancer survivor
than winner of the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The counterclockwise tour around France -- with five high
mountain climbs -- starts at Futuroscope in the west with the
traditional time trial. It dips into Switzerland -- Lausanne -- and
Germany -- Fribourg-En-Briscau -- on its 18th and 19th legs after
moving through central France, the Basque country, the southern
Provence region and northward through the Alps. There are two rest
days and two transfers -- one by plane and one by train.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,250-mile course is 36 miles shorter than last year's.
However, Dan Osipow, operations director for Armstrong's U.S.
Postal Service team, said he considers the course about 10 percent
harder, due notably to three mountaintop finishes and a July 4 team
time trial.
</P>
<P>
   The mountain stages, one ending at the ski resort of Courchevel,
could prove ominous, and the 14th stage, at Briancon, with three
6,000-foot-plus peaks, could decide the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Unknowns on the 2000 Tour include some strong climbers and
riders who have been lying low.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Tour winner, Deutsche Telecom's Jan Ullrich -- who did
not ride in last year's tour -- is back, as is Italian cycling star
Marco Pantani, winner of Italy's Giro and the Tour de France in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani and Frenchman Richard Virenque, riding for Polti, are
both known for their climbing skills and are embroiled in the legal
aftermath of doping scandals.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Pantani was ordered to stand trial for his alleged use
of EPO in a 1995 race. Virenque and nine others are to appear
before a French court in October in connection with the 1998 Tour
scandal that exploded around his former Festina team.
</P>
<P>
   Among the less-visible but still-skillful riders who have chance
of pulling an upset are French star Laurent Jalabert and Spain's
Abraham Olano, both riding for Spain's ONCE team; and Belgian
Franck Vandenbroucke of France's Cofidis.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service team is confident.
</P>
<P>
   Osipow said the team has been streamlined to meet this Tour's
demands. Armstrong -- not known as a climber -- is backed by Tyler
Hamilton, winner of the Dauphine Libere in June, with Armstrong,
who supported him, placing third.
</P>
<P>
   An addition to U.S. Postal, Frenchman Cedric Vasseur is known
for his climbing skills, while Russian Vjatceslav Ekimov is a
strong time-trial rider.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong ''physically, is at least equal to what he was last
year,'' said Osipow. ''And we feel, mentally, he is stronger than
last year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
