<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A life of crime -- and eluding police -- ends with apparent drug overdose </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - On his first day on the lam, Jamal Hightower
managed to steal some clothes and score some drugs. On his second
day, Hightower was found dead of an apparent drug overdose in the
Bronx, wearing a stolen Rite Aid vest.
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange end for a man who had some success - at least
for a time - at running away from police.
</P>
<P>
   His body was in a park across from the 40th Precinct
stationhouse Wednesday, blood pouring out of his nose, drug
paraphernalia strewn about him. The medical examiner's office will
determine the exact cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   In April, he had held police at bay, shooting at them and using
a woman as a human shield during a terror-filled chase in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the 24-year-old Bronx native apparently faked
seizures - using an Alka Seltzer tablet to create foaming at the
mouth - and was taken to a Bronx hospital. Early Tuesday, he
managed to walk calmly out of the emergency room, eluding three
corrections officers.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower's body was found near a shopping bag filled with
clothes he had apparently stolen, police said. Why he was wearing
the drugstore vest remained a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The police and court cases are now closed, but the city
Corrections Department has suspended its three officers pending a
review of how Hightower escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower's life of crime began with robberies. In 1994, he was
arrested for a pair of robberies, where he also sexually abused his
victims. He was paroled in September 1998, having served two-thirds
of his sentence. But after assaulting his parole officer in October
1999, Hightower went back to prison, then was paroled on March 15.
Six weeks later, he graduated to attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, Hightower and two men went to the Bronx apartment
of Michael Ortiz where they got into a fight. Hightower stabbed
Ortiz and his mother, Miriam Ortiz, apparently over drugs.
</P>
<P>
   With a gun stolen from Ortiz, Hightower and his friends fled.
When they saw a police cruiser, Hightower opened fire. Officers
fired back, and a bystander was struck in the face; he remains in a
coma.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower fled with police in pursuit. Hightower then boarded an
out-of-service city bus and held a gun to the driver's head, but
the driver ran to safety. Back on the street, Hightower headed for
the Metro-North railroad tracks near Fordham University.
Hightower's two friends were captured, but he grabbed a bystander,
used her as a human shield, and fired once at police. A detective
fired back and missed.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower released his hostage, jumped onto the tracks, but was
finally nabbed as he tried to climb a fence. Hightower was taken to
Rikers Island, where he remained until he faked his seizure.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to Lincoln Hospital in the Bronx, where he spent
the night. Shortly before 7 a.m. Tuesday, Hightower asked to go to
the bathroom and his leg shackles were removed. Hightower then
pushed his way past two of the officers - the third was not in the
area - and fled down the eighth-floor hallway. Hightower was seen
on a surveillance tape leaving through the emergency room entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower eluded police for a day, despite a search for him.
Then Wednesday morning, police received a complaint about a drunken
man on a park bench. Officers responded and noticed the resemblance
to Hightower, down to a scar on his right cheek. Fingerprints
confirmed the dead man's identity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1630 </TRAILER>
