<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Disclosure Bill Passed  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After an overwhelming vote in the House, the
Senate is poised to approve legislation that would force popular
but secretive groups to disclose the money sources of their
television commercials and other political activities.
</P>
<P>
   Senate GOP leaders, who have fought the measure, have agreed to
a quick vote on the bill, although there was talk Wednesday of a
delay until after lawmakers' July Fourth recess, said Sen. Russell
Feingold, one of the measure's backers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a great victory that will give us substantial momentum
for broader campaign finance reform,'' said Feingold, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The bill cleared the House early Wednesday by a 385-39 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Senators have approved similar legislation and passing the House
version would send the bill to President Clinton, who is ready to
sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said that Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott pushed for
an agreement that would permit a vote if key campaign finance
reformers Feingold and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., would not push
any other such legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We rejected out of hand,'' Feingold said. ''This is about
momentum to do more if possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would require disclosure of groups that organize
under section 527 of the tax code, which allows nonprofit groups to
run campaign-style commercials as long as they do not directly
advocate the election or defeat of any candidates.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, at a White House news conference Wednesday,
praised the House vote. The legislation, he said, will shine light
on ''mysterious interest groups whose financial backers are cloaked
in secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the disclosure measure note that every day of
delay allows groups to collect more secret cash. Even if a bill
does become law, groups will not have to disclose the names of
anyone who donates money before the legislation is signed.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has a ''very narrow window'' to pass the legislation in
time for disclosure to mean anything for the 2000 elections, said
Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas. He suggested opponents purposely have
delayed the bill to keep the cash rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill approved Wednesday is similar to Democrats'
originally proposal. Republican leaders blocked those efforts,
saying the legislation should be broadened to include unions and
other nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats complained that if unions were included,
corporations should be, too. Republicans balked.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also complained that such a broad bill was probably
unconstitutional. The GOP version included year-round nonprofit
activity, whereas Democrats wanted to limit it to activity within a
month or two of an election.
</P>
<P>
   ''You shoot as high as you possibly can and end up with
something the majority feels is the best practical solution,'' said
Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., who led the Republican effort.
</P>
<P>
   The final legislation covers any 527 group that raises at least
$25,000 a year. It requires those that do not already report to the
Federal Election Commission to report to the Internal Revenue
Service, which will make the reports public.
</P>
<P>
   Section 527 is reserved for political groups, giving them
certain tax advantages. It was created for political parties and
political action committees, which report their spending to the
FEC.
</P>
<P>
   But a new brand of 527 reports to no one. As far as the FEC is
concerned, these groups claim to be involved in issues, not
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Other nonprofits also avoid disclosure with the FEC by claiming
to be involved in issues, although they also spend large sums on
television ads that attempt to influence elections. Still, unlike
527s, these other groups do face some limit on how much political
activity they can conduct without losing their nonprofit tax
status.
</P>
<P>
   Using a 527, a pair of Texas brothers ran $2.5 million in ads
praising Texas Gov. George W. Bush and attacking McCain in the days
before a crucial GOP primary election. Another 527, with ties to
House Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, is assisting a variety of
Republicans running for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who did not participate in the House debate, said in a
statement that the bill ''is reality nothing more than a last-ditch
effort by the Democrats to protect their vulnerable incumbent
members from valid attacks on their positions and beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 4762.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Congress: http://www.thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1630 </TRAILER>
