<DOCNO> APW20000628.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Economic Program Approved  </HEADLINE>
By ANNA DOLGOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's Cabinet on Wednesday approved an
ambitious 10-year economic reform plan with a pro-market bent
likely to please foreign lenders -- but analysts said it may end up
existing only on paper.
</P>
<P>
   The plan urges introduction of private land ownership, an end to
barter, encouragement of greater competition and firm guarantees
against re-nationalization of private property. It also envisages
social reforms designed to narrow the huge divide between the
nation's rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan contains few details of how the government will
implement its goals in a country that had one of the world's
worst-performing economies over the past decade. Russia's
bureaucracy and rampant corruption have proved immune to several
previous reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''This program is rather general, and rather contradictory,''
said Natalya Orlova, an economic analyst with Alfa-Bank. ''There
are different views within the government on what should be done,
and the program includes only compromises. So there is a very big
question about how it will be realized.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The risk that reforms will be purely cosmetic is very high,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the approval of the program lifts the main stumbling
block in Russia's talks with the International Monetary Fund, which
has refused to discuss more loans with Russia until the government
presents a detailed economic program.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement with the IMF will also clear the way for
negotiations with other lenders, most immediately the Paris Club of
government creditors, which is considering alleviating Russia's
huge debt burden.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has missed a number of payments to the Paris Club and
other creditors, but tried to stay current on its IMF loans. The
Finance Ministry reported paying $60 million to the fund on
Wednesday, the ITAR-Tass news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The draft program calls for a minimum of 5 percent growth
annually, which would lead to a 150 percent increase in the gross
domestic product by 2010. Inflation is to be held to a maximum of
10 percent annually, and internal investment should rise by 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   As one way of attracting investment and preventing capital
flight, the plan proposes a law that would guarantee that
privatization results will not be reversed. Many Russians resent
post-Soviet privatization, which has enriched a few insiders, but
Prime Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said most deals were legal and
would stay in place.
</P>
<P>
   ''The privatization processes that took place, took place on the
basis of laws ... And even if these laws and regulations seem
imperfect from today's point of view, there can be no talk of
reversing privatization results,'' Kasyanov said.
</P>
<P>
   The program also calls for Russians' private bank accounts to be
guaranteed by the state. Many Russians lost their savings in the
1998 economic crisis, which saw the bank system virtually collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ''A market economy is not a goal in itself, but a method of
providing benefits for all the citizens of the country,'' Kasyanov
told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The government will introduce supporting legislation for the
reform plan in the fall, Kasyanov said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1630 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
