<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal agency warns water systems to do quality reports  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A federal agency warned nearly 400 water
systems throughout New York to provide customers with reports on
the quality of their drinking water by this Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency said Wednesday the
systems were supposed to have had the water quality reports to
customers by Oct. 19, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Fox, EPA's regional administrator, said the rate of
noncompliance in New York with that requirement was about 16
percent of the approximately 2,400 water systems in the state. She
called that percentage ''relatively high.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Fox noted that most of the recalcitrant water systems
were tiny ones covering only a few customers each. Ninety-nine
percent of New York's water consumers have had systems generate the
reports, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The list used by EPA was compiled by the state Health
Department. The EPA has the power to enforce the water quality
reports and other requirements established in amendments in 1996 to
the federal Safe Drinking Water Act.
</P>
<P>
   The water reports are designed to provide people with
information about the purity of the drinking water and details of
any instances where federal water quality standards were violated
within the past year. If there were such instances, the effects on
human health of the contaminants must also be provided, EPA
spokeswoman Mary Mears said.
</P>
<P>
   The first report went out by Oct. 19, 1999, and by this
Saturday, July 1, water systems throughout New York are supposed to
send out their second reports. Mears said that under the 1996
federal law, the July 1 date will become the deadline for annual
reports in subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   Any residents get a water bill are also supposed to get the
water quality reports. Some larger systems have also posted theirs
on the Internet, according to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   Mears said scores of water systems in the state have generated
the required reports since warnings went out from the EPA in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, the EPA's regional office reported that 187
systems were still not in compliance and 26 others were not public
water systems in the meaning of the federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the systems served small areas such as trailer parks,
mobile home parks, housing developments or apartment complexes and
institutions like adult homes.
</P>
<P>
   Mears said the districts are subject to penalties including
fines if they ignore the reporting requirements but she could not
say what the range of those fines would be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
