<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fugitive pleads case Wednesday  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A man convicted of selling $20 worth of
drugs three decades ago who fled to Canada returned to court
Wednesday where he was sentenced to four years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Harvie Richardson, 50, and his wife pleaded for leniency
before Monroe County Court Judge John J. Connell. The judge said
his decision ''brings me no happiness'' but that he had no choice
but to order Richardson to complete his initial sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Richardson sold LSD to an undercover police officer at
the Rochester Institute of Technology, where he was a student.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's defense lawyer that he deserves mercy because he
became an exemplary citizen and poses no threat to society.
</P>
<P>
   ''The man who is coming to court is a very different man from
the young, impetuous and reckless student of 30 years ago,''
Michael Kennedy told the Democrat and Chronicle of Rochester, who
is Richardson's lawyer in Vancouver, where Richardson has lived
since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also argued his incarceration will have a dire effect
on his wife, Amalia, who suffers from breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've tried to be a good man and a just man,'' Richardson said
at the sentencing. He told the court he was sorry for the acts of a
''foolish, radical young man'' and decided to surrender to make
peace with the justice system and pay his debt to society.
</P>
<P>
   Letters of support for Richardson could be reviewed by a parole
board to help determine when he could be released. District
Attorney Howard R. Relin, who opposed setting aside the sentence,
said Richardson likely could be released within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Relin was unavailable for comment after the sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting Richardson's arguments previously and ordering his
surrender to finish his sentence, Connell said Richardson needs to
take responsibility for his actions and shouldn't be rewarded for
escaping.
</P>
<P>
   Because Richardson was a prison escapee, he could have been
taken into custody when he entered the United States. He was
allowed to voluntarily surrender.
</P>
<P>
   When he was convicted in 1971 of selling for $20 worth of LSD,
the New York City native and Vietnam War protester served six weeks
in Attica Correctional Facility, a maximum-security prison. He then
was transferred to Camp Georgetown, a minimum-security work camp in
Madison County.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was at the work camp for six weeks when the riot and
retaking of Attica killed 43 inmates and correctional officers. He
said he walked away from the camp and fled to Canada when a guard
told him that he would return to Attica.
</P>
<P>
   The past of the research technologist who lives in a $700,000
home was revealed in 1998 when New York authorities tracked him to
Vancouver. Because Richardson had not changed his citizenship,
Canadian immigration authorities ordered him to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
