<HEADLINE> Business news in brief from around New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CRANFORD, N.J. (AP) - Mack-Cali Realty Corp. announced Wednesday
that it has agreed to buy Prentiss Properties Trust, a Dallas-based
real estate investment trust, in a deal worth $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Mack-Cali will pay $988.2 million
in stock, $245 million in preferred stock and assume $1 billion of
debt.
</P>
<P>
   The merger will create the fourth-largest office real estate
trust in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Cranford-based Mack-Cali is to obtain Prentiss's 191 properties
in 10 markets. The combined company would have 457 properties in 16
states and a market value of $5.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Mack-Cali Chairman John J. Cali, 81, will become chairman
emeritus but remain a director. William L. Mack is to be appointed
co-chairman along with Michael V. Prentiss, who founded the company
that bears his name.
</P>
<P>
   Mack-Cali was created in a $1.1 billion merger of Cali Realty
Corp. and the Mack Co. in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON, N.J. (AP) - Foster Wheeler Corp. said Wednesday that it
will build a new drug-making facility for Lundbeck Pharmaceuticals
Ltd., the United Kingdom subsidiary of Denmark's H. Lundbeck A/S,
in Teesside, England.
</P>
<P>
   The project is worth $48 million.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton-based Foster Wheeler said it will provide engineering,
procurement and construction management services for the project,
which is a bulk pharmaceutical production facility to be located at
Lundbeck's Seal Sands site. The plant is expected to be operational
by early 2002.
</P>
<P>
   TOMS RIVER, N.J. (AP) - OceanFirst Bank announced Wednesday that
it has agreed to buy the privately held Columbia Equities Ltd., of
Tarrytown, N.Y., for an undisclosed amount.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, Columbia would operate as an
independent subsidiary. It offers residential mortgages in New
York, New Jersey and Connecticut through three branches, a Web site
and a network of independent mortgage brokers. Columbia approved
$275 million in loans for the year ending May 31.
</P>
<P>
   OceanFirst Bank, which is part of OceanFirst Financial Corp.,
has $1.6 billion in assets and 14 branches in Ocean, Monmouth and
Middlesex counties.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) - RCN Corp. said Wednesday that it has
received local approval to provide its bundled telephone, cable and
high-speed Internet services over its Megaband Network to residents
of Beverly Hills and Gardena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton-based company will have access to more than 35,000
homes in the two towns when its fiber optic network is built. The
company already offers its broadband services in the California
towns of South San Francisco, San Mateo and Dale City.
</P>
<P>
   RCN's integrated network allows customers to buy local and long
distance telephone, cable and Internet services from one company.
The company, which targets densely populated areas, has plans to
cover 44 percent of the residential communications market.
</P>
<P>
   HADDONFIELD, N.J. (AP) - The Translation Group Ltd., a company
that offers Internet-based translation services, said Wednesday
that it has changed its name to InSage, but it will continue
over-the-counter trading under the symbol THEO.
</P>
<P>
   ''The launch of InSage is our way of telling the world that we
have successfully completed the integration of all our services and
are truly the first company to offer a full range of multilingual
Web solutions,'' said CEO Randy Morris.
</P>
</TEXT>
