<HEADLINE> Ebersol: NBC Will Turn Profit Games  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD FENDRICH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It won't be live. It will be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Sports expects to make money with its broadcasts of the
Sydney Olympics, where all the action will be tape-delayed for U.S.
audiences half a world away.
</P>
<P>
   NBC paid $705 million for the rights to the 2000 Olympics, which
will run Sept. 15-Oct. 1, as part of a $3.5 billion package that
gives the network exclusive U.S. broadcast rights to the next five
games, through 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the time of the deal, we anticipated losing money with
Sydney, in the environs of $50-$75 million,'' NBC Sports chairman
Dick Ebersol said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are already assured of a small profit. Our (advertising)
sales target for these games was $780 million, $100 more than
Atlanta, where $680 million was a record in terms of gross sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are still selling and we anticipate closing up around Labor
Day at just over $900 million.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the IOC bribery scandal, centering on Salt Lake City's
winning bid for the 2002 Winter Olympics, ''never affected our
sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol spoke at a news conference held -- inappropriately enough
-- at the studio used for ''Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be nothing live about NBC's coverage from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the 15-hour time difference between Sydney and the
East Coast, and the number of evening finals at the Summer
Olympics, particularly in higher-profile events such as swimming
and track, all competition will be shown on tape.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for the 162&AMP;frac12; hours on NBC plus the 279 on cable
outfits MSNBC (214) and CNBC (65). There is a slightly decreased
number of hours from the 1996 Atlanta Olympics on NBC proper (171&AMP;frac12;)
-- but more than double overall.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was really important for us to come 100 percent clean and
say what we were going to do,'' Ebersol said of letting audiences
know the games will be entirely on tape. ''The first three days of
the Olympics we've made a commitment to telling viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   If competition were shown live, it would be on in the early
morning hours in the United States, when, Ebersol said, ''there's
nobody watching TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of NBC's daily coverage, with Bob Costas as host, will
be in prime time from 7 p.m. to midnight EDT/PDT, and Ebersol said
he anticipates the average national Nielsen rating to be between
17.5 and 18.5.
</P>
<P>
   NBC averaged a 21.6 rating at the 1996 games.
</P>
<P>
   A rating point for NBC represents 1,080,000 households, or 1
percent of the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The competition is tougher with pro football, prime-time fare,
maybe some meaningful baseball pennant races,'' Ebersol said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I never look at (the Olympics) as having a particularly
tough road to hoe against other sports.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable channels will be used as outlets for team sports,
including women's soccer and softball, and boxing.
</P>
<P>
   As always with the Olympics, viewers can expect plenty of
feature pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ''Storytelling is our mantra,'' said David Neal, head of
production. ''It's what we do. It's what Americans expect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1705 </TRAILER>
