<HEADLINE> Farm-State Democrats Rip EPA  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farm-state Democrats blasted the Clinton
administration Wednesday for moving forward with a plan to clean up
polluted waterways despite strong opposition from agricultural
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rep. Charles Stenholm, the House Agriculture Committee's
senior Democrat, told officials with the Environmental Protection
Agency and the Agriculture Department that the program was
''ill-conceived'' and certain to face ''strenuous opposition in
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tim Holden, D-Pa., accused the EPA of displaying
''arrogance'' and a ''complete lack of concern'' for the views of
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which the EPA intends to make final this summer,
would require states to submit plans within 15 years to clean up
every waterway that fails to meet water quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   Landowners would be required to get a pollution discharge permit
if the EPA found they were contributing to nearby water quality
problems and if a state had failed to draft an adequate plan for
improving water quality.
</P>
<P>
   The agency estimates more than 20,000 streams and lakes don't
meet water-quality standards, or about 40 percent of all lakes,
rivers and streams in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a serious problem on our hands and the people of this
country have made it clear that they expect us to respond,'' Fox
told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   EPA has exempted forestry operations from the plan because of
opposition from the wood-products industry. But opponents of the
program still say it would impose huge costs on farms and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the hostility that the plan has met with, Rep.
Marion Barry, D-Ark., demanded that Fox and a USDA official who
accompanied him take an oath before testifying before the committee
Wednesday. The House committee almost never swears in witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Barry said the clean-water plan, which is known by the acronym
TMDL, for Total Maximum Daily Load, had no ''scientific or
practical basis.''
</P>
<P>
   James Lyons, the USDA official, conceded that the plan was
unpopular, saying that ''TMDL is the new four-letter word in rural
America.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said, ''The facts are that there are 20,000 impaired
bodies of water in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Congress hasn't done enough to clean up waterways
because it hasn't provided enough money for farm-conservation
programs that pay farmers to take environmentally sensitive land
out of production.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans also oppose the clean-water plan, although
they let Democrats take the lead in criticizing the administration
at Wednesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   EPA probably should withdraw the proposal ''so that the public
and Congress can have another opportunity to work through the
difficult issues,'' said the committee's chairman, Rep. Larry
Combest, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Combest and Stenholm have introduced legislation that would
delay implementation of the program while the National Academy of
Sciences studied the issue. An appropriations bill approved by the
House earlier this month contained a provision that would at least
temporarily delay the EPA plan.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, meanwhile, has disputed the EPA's
claim that the program would cost governments and the private
sector less than $100 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1705 </TRAILER>
