<HEADLINE> Abortion Ruling May Affect Race  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN O'HANLON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- The U.S. Supreme Court's rejection of
Nebraska's ban on a late-term abortion procedure opponents call
''partial-birth abortion'' was a legal defeat but not necessarily a
political one for the state's attorney general, who has built his
Senate campaign around defending the law.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Don Stenberg, a conservative Republican, argued
the abortion case in front of the high court in April -- two weeks
before soundly winning Nebraska's GOP primary -- and has often
pointed that out in his campaign advertisements and speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ''This negative decision may have a positive payoff in that it
might energize his conservative Christian support to elect him all
the more,'' said John Comer, a political scientist at the
University of Nebraska-Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Stenberg is up against Ben Nelson, a moderate Democrat who left
the governor's office in 1999 with an 80 percent approval rating.
The two candidates are seeking the seat being vacated by Democrat
Bob Kerrey.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were on the right side,'' Stenberg said Wednesday. ''There
isn't a single founding father of this nation, when they wrote the
Constitution ... who would have said, 'We are proud to have done
this so that children can be pulled from their mothers' wombs and
killed in the most barbaric fashion.'''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Jon Bruning promised to introduce a bill on the first
day of the 2001 session to ban the procedure. ''My intention is to
do the most careful research and drafting of this bill so there is
almost no chance of it being struck down by the court again,''
Bruning said.
</P>
<P>
   In this largely conservative, GOP state, Nelson has wide support
among Republicans because of his moderate views. GOP officials even
approached him in the past about switching parties. And he made
sure Wednesday not to alienate those voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am pro-life, and as governor I signed the bill into law,''
Nelson said, referring to the ban. ''I abhor the procedure and hope
the Legislature will go back and make the changes needed to make
the ban work in Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   Comer emphasized that as much as Stenberg would have liked to
have won the case, it probably won't make a difference to most
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''People pretty much have made up their mind already on Don
Stenberg,'' he said. ''Elections seldom turn on the outcome a
Supreme Court decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Stenberg, 51, is a Harvard Law graduate who was elected attorney
general in 1990 and re-elected in 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Stenberg said the abortion issue will instead affect the
presidential election and confirmation hearings for Supreme Court
justices
</P>
<P>
   ''My test as a U.S. senator in confirming justices to the U.S.
Supreme Court is going to be whether they limit themselves to
following the Constitution or whether they want to impose their own
social views on America,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1711 </TRAILER>
