<HEADLINE> USC CB Simmons May Miss 2000 Season  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Senior cornerback Antuan Simmons, a
three-year starter at the University of Southern California, may
miss the 2000 season due to recovery from surgery to remove an
abdominal tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Trojans coach Paul Hackett said Wednesday that Simmons, who had
surgery May 16, may sit out the season as a redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Antuan underwent a very serious operation but he has fought
through it in an extraordinary way,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Donald G. Skinner, who performed the surgery to remove a
non-cancerous growth near Simmons' left kidney, said it is expected
Simmons would achieve ''a complete recovery in his ability to
return to competitive athletics without limitations in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons has made 175 tackles, seven interceptions and blocked
six kicks for USC over three seasons. He missed the last two games
of 1999 and spring practice this year due to herniated disc
surgery, not related to his May surgery.
</P>
<P>
   USC plays Penn State on Aug. 27 in the Kickoff Classic at Giants
Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
