<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: President's Curiosity Key  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the assessment of the departing incumbent,
a president's curiosity is more important than raw brain power.
President Clinton passed up an opportunity Wednesday to assess
whether the presumptive GOP presidential nominee has enough of
either.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's so much a question of intelligence,
generically. I mean, I think it's more a question of curiosity and
willingness to learn what you think is important,'' Clinton said
during a White House press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, himself a Yale graduate, Rhodes scholar and generally
acknowledged smart fellow, paused before answering a question about
whether Texas Gov. George W. Bush, also a Yale graduate, is an
intellectual lightweight. After all, some scholars say Ronald
Reagan was effective by concentrating on a few big ideas while
leaving the details to others, a reporter said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a dead-bang loser, isn't it?'' Clinton said, laughing.
''No matter what I say, I'm in a big hole.''
</P>
<P>
   He did say that while voters should not be satisfied with a
president who simply takes the recommendations of good advisers, it
is also important not to micromanage from the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ''So what you try to do is to find a balance between this,
because it's a deciding job,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said as president he tried to learn as much as he could
so he could best evaluate the advice he got.
</P>
<P>
   As for his plans for when someone else is president, Clinton
seemed to rule out a run for the Senate, as first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton is now doing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think maybe I'll run for the school board someday. That's
about the only thing I can imagine doing,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who leaves office in seven months, has said he intends
to work closely on establishing his presidential library in Little
Rock, but has otherwise offered few insights to his post-White
House plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want to be a good citizen,'' Clinton said Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
