<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Con Ed, feeling the heat, says there is enough power to meet demand </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - While saying it's relatively certain there's
enough power to meet city demand as temperatures rise, Consolidated
Edison has already steamed Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for its handling
of a brownout barely one week into summer.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Giuliani questioned the company's response to
power problems on the Upper East Side that caused a hospital to
switch to its backup generator earlier this week. The mayor said he
had tired of wondering if the city could make it through a summer
without a power failure.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea that they just don't have enough power doesn't make
any sense at this stage,'' Giuliani told a news conference. ''It's
no excuse to say people use too much power. Con Edison should be
prepared for people using too much power.''
</P>
<P>
   Utility officials have said the latest brownout - which prompted
a request for Mount Sinai Hospital to switch to its own generator -
was caused by a problem with feeder cables.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed has also said it's stretched to provide sufficient energy
because a thriving economy increases demand for power, more people
are using air conditioning, and because fuel prices are so high.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Donohue, Con Ed's senior vice president of electric
operations, said the energy supply is ''tight - very, very tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could guarantee that there would be no blackouts
this summer, Con Ed spokesman Joseph Petta said utility officials
believe they have enough power to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   He also said, however, that the amount of power the utility can
supply the city is limited because there are too few power plants
from which to buy electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ''Another summer and another crisis is what we have,'' said
Ashok Gupta, a senior economist with the Natural Resources Defense
Council.
</P>
<P>
   And although Petta said more power plants are needed, City
Council Speaker Peter Vallone said no new ones should be built
until the old ones are torn down and electric companies guarantee
the new facilities will be cleaner burning and more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone also said blaming problems on insufficient power is
simply Con Ed's latest excuse. During last year's 19-hour blackout
in Washington Heights, for example, the company blamed failing
cables.
</P>
<P>
   ''Frankly, we don't know what ... they're doing,'' said Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed plans to spend $315 million over the next five years to
improve the city's power supply system, and has spent $100 million
replacing feeder cables and upgrading substations since the
Washington Heights blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Wednesday that he will meet with Con Ed officials
next week, and both the mayor and Vallone said they will charge
separate task forces with investigating the city's power problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1725 </TRAILER>
