<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karolyi Displeased Over Panel  </HEADLINE>
By EDDIE PELLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of the four people in charge of choosing the women's U.S.
Olympic gymnastics team haven't seen the athletes perform in the
monthly training camps team coordinator Bela Karolyi has held to
track their progress.
</P>
<P>
   It's a quite different scenario than Karolyi envisioned when he
agreed to work with the team, hoping to pump life into the
struggling U.S. program in time for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ''The selection situation, it's still messy,'' Karolyi said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, officials at USA Gymnastics named 1984
Olympian Tracee Talavera, longtime U.S. judge Marilyn Cross and
either gymnast Chari Knight or Larissa Fontaine to team with
Karolyi to choose the six members of the Olympic team after the
trials in August.
</P>
<P>
   It's a more subjective process than in years past, when weighted
scores from the trials and the U.S. Championships were the main
criteria in the selection. This year, finishing in the top six
won't guarantee a spot on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at USA Gymnastics insist the scores will still play a
major role in determining the team.
</P>
<P>
   But the new process creates more wiggle room in case key
athletes are injured. It also allows the committee to shore up
weaknesses on certain apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe most importantly, it was intended to give the selection
committee a broader set of performances upon which to base its
decision. Karolyi envisioned his training camps, which began in
January, as the perfect time for the selection committee to judge
the athletes and track their improvement.
</P>
<P>
   But Talavera and Cross haven't been to any of the camps, because
they weren't named to the committee until this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tracee, I highly respect her, but I haven't seen her in last
nine to 10 years,'' Karolyi said. ''Marilyn, I highly respect her,
too. But I haven't seen her. She hasn't been at the camps. She
hasn't been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Talavera and Cross were selected by coaches of potential Olympic
athletes. They didn't attend the camps because the coaches didn't
make their choices until USA Gymnastics finalized its selection
process. That happened in April.
</P>
<P>
   Senior team director Kathy Kelly, who hired Karolyi last
November, understands his complaints, but thinks the system will
still work.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a little departure from the way he saw it and that makes
him uneasy,'' Kelly said. ''But we're quite confident that we have
really knowing and caring people. We feel the coaches feel that
way, too. In the end, his plan won't be hampered, it will be
enhanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is the prickly question as to what happens if
Karolyi is outnumbered on the committee over the selection of a
certain athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is a difference of opinion, the loser will be the one
I appreciate the most,'' he said. ''I just hope everyone realizes
what the best interest of the team is, and what the strengths and
weaknesses of the athletes are.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Gymnastics president Bob Colarossi said the process will
still work.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are tremendous, competent people with a strong breadth
of experience,'' he said. ''There's a mutual level of respect
between a group of qualified individuals. I think it will be all
right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
