<DOCNO> APW20000628.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court ruling should get Boy Scouts on state charity list, lawyer says </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The U.S. Supreme Court's ruling that the
Boy Scouts can ban homosexual leaders means Connecticut state
employees should be allowed to contribute to scouting through
payroll deductions, a lawyer for the organization said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Connecticut State Employee Campaign
Committee removed the Boy Scouts from a list of charities that
state employees could contribute to through a payroll deduction
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was based on a ruling by the state's Commission on
Human Rights and Opportunities that including the Boy Scouts on the
list violated the state's anti-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   But the Irving, Texas-based Boy Scouts and one Connecticut
scouting council filed a federal discrimination lawsuit against the
state, arguing that exclusion from the list was a First Amendment
violation.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts also appealed the campaign committee's decision
to take them off the list. The board is reviewing the appeal.
Committee chairwoman Carol Carney was on vacation and unavailable
for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Supreme Court decision bolsters and further strengthens
our arguments,'' said Daniel L. Schwartz, the Scouts' lawyer who
filed the suit against the state employee campaign board and state
Comptroller Nancy Wyman. ''The Boy Scouts have the constitutional
right to their membership policies.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the case, a civil liberties lawyer said, but the
state should not be using its resources on behalf of an
organization with a discriminatory policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state employee contribution program uses state resources
and money,'' said Joe Grabarz, executive director of the
Connecticut Civil Liberties Union. ''Should the state be forced to
do that for an organization that violates state law and state
policy? The (American Civil Liberties Union) clearly says 'no.'''
</P>
<P>
   When the CHRO unanimously decided last month that the Boy Scouts
could not be included in the employee contribution campaign, the
board declined to rule directly on whether the organization's
policy violates state anti-discrimination laws. But it did find
that including a group with such a policy on the employee
contribution list violated state anti-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign committee had asked the CHRO for a ruling in
November after the New Jersey Supreme Court found the Boy Scouts'
policy of banning gay leaders was unconstitutional. The Boy Scouts
appealed, and the U.S. Supreme Court ruled 5-4 in their favor
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say it's too early to tell how the high court
ruling will affect the payroll deduction program.
</P>
<P>
   A CHRO spokeswoman declined to comment on the ruling until the
board had a chance to review it. Attorney General Richard
Blumenthal, who is representing the campaign committee and Wyman,
said he is also reviewing the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign committee hires the United Way to collect the
employee payroll deductions. But the state has the right to prevent
the fund-raiser from giving the Boy Scouts any contributions not
designated for a particular agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 campaign, $9,950 was contributed directly to the Boy
Scouts by state employees. The Scouts also received a portion of
$200,000 in non-designated contributions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1736 </TRAILER>
