<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court upholds charter school law  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state's highest court Wednesday upheld
New Jersey's landmark charter school law.
</P>
<P>
   In its unanimous ruling, the state Supreme Court turned back
attempts by school districts in Englewood, Clifton, Franklin
Township and Highland Park to revoke charters of new schools in
their towns.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature in 1995 allowed for the creation of
charter schools, which are outside the control of local boards of
education and are free of many state mandates and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state law, charters receive 90 percent of their
funding from local districts.
</P>
<P>
   Public school officials who filed the lawsuit complained about
the loss of funds. They also questioned whether charters could
exacerbate racial divisions by siphoning off white students.
</P>
<P>
   While upholding the charter law, the justices ordered the state
education commissioner to assess the racial and financial impact of
a charter school's approval on the local school district.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the 1995 law stands, according to the 33-page opinion
penned by Associate Justice Jaynee LaVecchia.
</P>
<P>
   ''The choice to include charter schools among the array of
public entities providing educational services for our pupils is a
choice appropriately made by the Legislature so long as the
constitutional mandate to provide a thorough and efficient system
of education is satisfied,'' the opinion said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
