<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Authorities say they can't stop tribe's closing of Appalachian Trail </HEADLINE>
By DAVE COLLINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Federal and state officials say they
don't have the power to stop the Schaghticoke American Indians from
closing a portion of the Appalachian Trail that runs through the
tribe's reservation in Kent.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe's chief, Richard Velky, announced Wednesday that the
Schaghticokes would close a two-mile section of trail from Saturday
to Tuesday to protest the federal government's handling of the
tribe's recognition petition.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers with the Appalachian Mountain Club, a private group
that maintains the trail in Connecticut and Massachusetts, will
detour hikers around the tribe's land, said Brian King, a spokesman
for the club's parent organization. Detour signs will be posted, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Richard Blumenthal deplored Velky's plan
Wednesday, urging the chief to keep the trail open. But Blumenthal
conceded that the state has little power to stop the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ''While our legal options may be limited, the moral high ground
in this landscape is clear: Innocent hikers and campers should not
be made pawns in the Schaghticokes' dispute with the federal
government,'' Blumenthal wrote in a letter to Velky.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said his office was looking into the extent of the
state's legal rights in the matter. But under a long-standing
legislative act, the tribe has most ownership rights over the
property, located in the northwest part of the state, the attorney
general said.
</P>
<P>
   But Blumenthal emphasized in the letter that state police have
authority to enforce laws on reservation land.
</P>
<P>
   State police spokesman Sgt. Paul Vance said there were no plans
to send troopers to the reservation over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''We under no circumstances expect any confrontation
whatsoever,'' Vance said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service, which oversees the 2,167-mile trail
that stretches from Georgia to Maine, said it too is powerless to
stop the tribe from closing the trail because that portion of trail
is on private property.
</P>
<P>
   Velky said tribe members and private security guards would close
the trail from 8 a.m. Saturday through 8 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Velky said the Bureau of Indian Affairs has been to slow to act
on the recognition petition the tribe first filed in 1994. The
chief said he has been told that it could take another 10 to 12
years for the tribe's application to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Velky also claimed the federal Department of the Interior
promoted trespassing on the 312-member tribe's land by routing the
Appalachian Trail through the reservation, which was recognized by
state government in 1736.
</P>
<P>
   ''We shouldn't have to wait an ungodly amount of time,'' Velky
said. ''We just want to show them that they are trespassing. It is
our land.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal recognition makes tribes eligible for several federal
assistance programs and classifies them as sovereign nations.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mashantucket Pequot and Mohegan tribes opened
successful casinos after being federally recognized, Velky has said
that his tribe has no plans for a casino.
</P>
<P>
   Velky apologized to hikers, but he said the government's
inaction left him no choice but to close the trail.
</P>
<P>
   King, spokesman for the Appalachian Trail Conference, said the
trail's closing will be a minor inconvenience for hikers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just one more change in the schedule,'' King said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
