<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Dial Corp., down $2.125 at $10.938
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to incur restructuring charges totaling $17
million, or 19 cents a share, in a bid to boost future profits. As
a result, earnings per share for the first half of its current
fiscal year will fall about 40 percent below year-ago levels.
</P>
<P>
ShopKo Stores Inc., up 12.5 cents at $14.563
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to report second-quarter operating earnings
of 25 cents a share. Analysts had expected earnings of 36 cents a
share. ShopKo attributed the expected earnings shortfall to
lower-than-expected sales and the recent sale of its ProVantage
Health Services unit to Merck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
Conseco Inc., up $1.438 at $7.625
</P>
<P>
   Reports have said that Gary C. Wendt, who was credited with
turning GE Capital Services into a financial-services powerhouse,
will become chief executive at Conseco. The company was reportedly
voting on the move Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
AAR Corp., down $1.50 at $11.75
</P>
<P>
   The company earned 9 cents per share in the fiscal fourth
quarter, down from 42 cents per share a year earlier. AAR, a
provider of products and services to the aerospace industry, cited
an unexpected shortfall in aircraft and engine sales and leasing
activity.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Webhire Inc., up $1.438 at $3.75
</P>
<P>
   Executive search firm Korn/Ferry International and Internet
investment group Softbank Corp. will invest a total of $12 million
in Webhire. The company's stock price has dropped steadily since
the beginning of April on concerns it was running out of cash.
</P>
<P>
Bolder Technologies Corp., up $1.75 at $6.188
</P>
<P>
   The company sold about 2.46 million unregistered common shares
in a private placement in exchange for a $10 million investment
from the State of Wisconsin Investment Board. Bolder said it plans
to use the money to improve its balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
IXYS Corp., down $18.375 at $46.258
</P>
<P>
   International Rectifier Corp. filed a patent infringement suit
against IXYS, a maker of semiconductors that convert and control
electric power. International Rectifier makes integrated circuits,
power systems and components. IXYS said it is reviewing the
allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
