<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House votes down Andrews' amendment to stall Delaware deepening  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - Despite defeat of his amendment that would
have withheld nearly $30 million to deepen the Delaware River, U.S.
Rep. Rob Andrews is pledging to work to halt the project, which he
calls ''environmentally risky.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first round in a long fight,'' Andrews said
Wednesday, hours after the House, in a 249-176 vote late Tuesday
night, defeated an amendment he had sponsored to withhold $29.8
million for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, with the backing of the
Delaware River Port Authority, plans to deepen 108 miles of the
river to 45 feet, from its current depth of 40 feet. That would
allow ships to carry more cargo to the Port of Camden and
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority and shippers say this is crucial to keep the
port open and to continue to attract ships. But environmentalists
oppose it, saying dredging could stir up toxins at the river
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   They're also concerned about what will be done with 22 million
cubic yards of sediment that would be dredged. Plans call for it to
be put along the river and Delaware Bay in Delaware and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority also is exploring putting some of the fill in
abandoned mines in Pennsylvania and selling it to companies for use
as highway and construction fill.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the federal government would fund about
two-thirds of the $311 million cost and the Port Authority would
pay about one-third, with contributions from New Jersey,
Pennsylvania and Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews' amendment would have held back $29.8 million until next
June so the project's economic and environmental effects could be
studied.
</P>
<P>
   ''The burden of proof is on those who want to do this project to
prove that it makes sense economically,'' Andrews said Wednesday.
''Then environmental questions need to be answered about toxic hot
spots in the river and effects on wetlands.''
</P>
<P>
   On the House floor Tuesday night Andrews said, ''We're being
asked to invest nearly $30 million in a project that is
economically unproven, environmentally risky and fundamentally
unfair to the people of southern New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Rodney Frelinghuysen is among the supporters of the
deepening project.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not and have not supported any project in New Jersey that
would harm my state's environment,'' he said during the House
debate. ''The Delaware deepening project meets all environmental
standards and has been approved by the Environmental Protection
Agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Frelinghuysen, the state's only member of the House
Appropriations Committee, also said, ''If this amendment passes, I
can assure this body that some other worthy project somewhere other
than New Jersey will benefit. Some other state will benefit and
again, New Jersey's priorities fall further down the list at the
bottom of the federal barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   The amendment was to the House's Energy and Water Appropriations
bill, which passed early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate must vote on its own Energy and Water Appropriations
bill, then the two will be merged. That bill would then be sent to
President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1755 </TRAILER>
