<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exiled Laotian Royals Visit U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Members of the exiled Lao royal family are in
Washington as part of a monthlong U.S. trip aimed at generating
support for peacefully removing the communists who have ruled their
country for a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will request that the U.S. government press for
negotiations to restore democracy in Laos,'' said Prince Sauryavong
Savang, 63, the patriarch of the family, which lives in France. He
is the brother of Laos' last king, who died in a ''re-education''
camp after the communists took control in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the prince is the king's son, Prince Soulivong
Savang, 37, the heir to the throne, and Tiao Bouavong Kattygnarath,
a special adviser to the family.
</P>
<P>
   The two princes spoke through a translator during an interview
Wednesday at Washington's Army-Navy Club. They plan to meet this
week with a half dozen members of Congress. But the family was
rebuffed in its attempt to meet with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The crown prince has offered to return to Laos, a tiny, poor,
landlocked nation in Southeast Asia, and preside over a
constitutional monarchy while elections are held. Laotian
government officials have dismissed the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the family met with an official from the
United Nations Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights,
pressing him to investigate human rights violations in Laos.
</P>
<P>
   Laos does not tolerate political dissent, and last October
police arrested at least five people at an anti-government rally.
Their fate remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The government also has been fighting a low-level insurgency
from Hmong rebels, the highland people who aided the CIA during the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, two Hmong-Americans, Houa Ly, 56, of Appleton, Wis.,
and Michael Vang, 36, of Fresno, Calif., disappeared while on
vacation. They were last seen boarding a boat from Thailand to
Laos.
</P>
<P>
   Mai Sayavongs of the Laotian embassy in Washington dismissed the
allegations of human rights violations in his country.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Lao government is improving human rights in Laos,'' he
said, adding that people have ''individual rights and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The royal family will travel to Denver on Friday for a 10-day
visit, then heads to St. Paul, Minn., for six days. Both cities
have relatively large Lao populations.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
