<HEADLINE> Cubans in NJ angered by Supreme Court decision  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) - Cuban-Americans in New Jersey said
Wednesday that Elian Gonzalez is returning home to a life much
worse than the one he could have had in America.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know he has no future over there,'' said Joseph Larin, who
came to Union City from Cuba in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of one of the nation's largest Cuban-American
communities were disappointed by the U.S. Supreme Court's refusal
to consider granting 6-year-old Elian an asylum hearing before his
father could take him back to Cuba. But nearly all said they had
expected this end to the story long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not surprised by the outcome,'' said Mayor Rudy Garcia,
a Cuban-American. ''We're just surprised by the process. Everyone
has had their day in court but Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said American courts have emphasized that Elian's father
has a right to make decisions for his son while ignoring Cuba's
communist politics and living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ''He always wanted to stay. I remember him saying that to me,''
said Garcia, who visited the boy when he was staying in Miami with
his great-uncle and cousin.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Menendez, D-N.J., said that unlike other Cuban
children over 6, Elian will likely receive milk because of his
American saga, but will still have to spend his childhood laboring
four months a year in fields. He said the Supreme Court decision
will have consequences for other immigrants seeking asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a very sad day when the highest court in the land
decides that a young boy does not have the same rights as an adult
refugee fleeing from oppression,'' Menendez said. ''Today, the
Supreme Court consciously set a precedent that will reject future
political asylum applications based on age, nor merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Emilio Perez, a 76-year-old Cuban-American who spent 18 years as
a political prisoner in Cuba, had stronger words for the court. He
said the justices had to be ''a bunch of orphans'' for being able
to deny Elian a hearing to keep him in America.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Cuban-American community, numbering about 150,000
in Hudson County, marched in the streets and blocked traffic near
the Lincoln Tunnel after federal agents seized Elian from the home
of his Miami relatives. Remberto Perez, regional director for the
Cuban American National Foundation, says the issue galvanized the
community, especially its younger members.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never in my years with the foundation got as many calls
as I've gotten from students, young executives,'' Perez said,
''people who are usually leaving the fight up to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But one Union City resident, who wouldn't give his last name
because he feared retribution, said the issue had created too much
debate among Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am happy that he's going. At least we got rid of an issue,''
said Leon A. ''We have to talk about other things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1811 </TRAILER>
