<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Insurance Commissioner Quits  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HOWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Insurance Commissioner Chuck
Quackenbush, embroiled in one of the state's largest political
controversies in years, resigned Wednesday after being accused of
using millions of dollars from insurance settlements to further his
own political career.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican's decision averted the possibility of impeachment
by the Legislature, which has been investigating the deepening
scandal. However, Attorney General Bill Lockyer said his own
investigation of Quackenbush's actions will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's attorney, Don Heller, said his client resigned
because he could no longer serve effectively as commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a decent man with very human and decent feelings about
people ... and in his effort to fulfill campaign promises he made
as to reaching out, mistakes were made,'' Heller said. ''I am
satisfied he has done nothing illegal or criminal or improper in
any way. He made mistakes which he readily admitted.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal centers on money paid by several insurance companies
that had been accused by the state Insurance Department of
mishandling claims filed by policyholders after the 1994 earthquake
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony, the insurance companies were threatened
with billions of dollars in fines by the department but were let
off the hook if they paid far less into a nonprofit fund
established by Quackenbush's office.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the fund was supposed to go toward victim assistance
and earthquake research. But it was spent instead on TV ads
featuring Quackenbush and also went to causes such as a sports
program attended by the commissioner's children.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush had been set to testify before the Assembly
Insurance Committee on Thursday, after which the panel was to
determine whether he should face censure, criminal charges,
impeachment proceedings or whether no punishment was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   With the commissioner's resignation, the committee will cancel
the hearing and publish a report on its findings, said the
chairman, Assemblyman Jack Scott, a Democrat. ''I take no joy in
the ruin of a man,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's resignation followed what sources said were days
of negotiations with lawmakers in an attempt to limit any civil and
criminal liability. The Insurance Committee made no deal with
Quackenbush, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's wife, Chris, said earlier Wednesday that she was
hoping he wouldn't resign. She said he was being targeted by
powerful enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you are elected by 5.5 million people, you don't get
unelected by the newspapers. He's been convicted in the court of
public opinion and that's a mistake in a democracy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Rosenfield, president of the Foundation for Taxpayer and
Consumer Rights, said: ''There's a sort of 'ding-dong the witch is
dead' feeling around here. He took an office that was born out of
voter frustration with the insurance companies and betrayed the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush was re-elected to a second four-year term in 1998.
He is one of only two Republicans holding statewide office in
California. The other is Secretary of State Bill Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
