<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Prepares New TV Ad Blitz  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With just over a month before the Republican
National Convention, George W. Bush is raising money for a final
pre-convention TV ad blitz touting his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ''Please click on my Web site and contribute to my campaign,''
the Texas governor wrote in an e-mail to supporters. ''Every cent
will go to TV ads to let Americans know what I would do as
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush cannot spend privately raised money after he becomes the
official Republican presidential nominee at the July 31-Aug. 3
convention in Philadelphia. At that point, he will get $67.6
million in taxpayer money to run his fall campaign. Vice President
Al Gore, the likely Democratic presidential nominee, will get the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised more than $90 million, had $7.1 million left at
the end of May and continues to raise more. ''The money is still
coming in,'' said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Republican National Committee pulled its Bush ads
this week, concluding that spots paid for by the Democratic
National Committee on Gore's behalf have not been effective. And
the DNC prepared to air a new spot on education.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to people who registered on his Internet site, Bush
pleaded for donations to counter the DNC ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now the Democrats are running a multimillion-dollar TV ad
campaign,'' Bush wrote. ''Will you help me overcome this new
assault, this latest attempt by Al Gore to try to 'reinvent
himself' for the American people?''
</P>
<P>
   He noted the RNC also has run ads, but said: ''I would like my
campaign to be able to run Bush for President ads in key
battleground states. To do that, I need your help.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said plans have not been finalized, but a TV ad
campaign is the most likely course. The ads could appear any time
between now and Aug. 3. An ad blitz in the days immediately before
the convention or during its opening days is one possibility.
</P>
<P>
   After an exhaustive and expensive primary season, the Bush and
Gore campaigns haven't run ads since March. This month, the DNC
launched its ad campaign featuring Gore, which was immediately
matched by the RNC ads focusing on Bush's Social Security plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign estimates the DNC will have spent $9.2 million
on its ads by Sunday. But since the ads began running, Bush has
gained on Gore in national polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the DNC's ads are already doing Al Gore sufficient
damage,'' said RNC spokesman Cliff May.
</P>
<P>
   DNC spokeswoman Jenny Backus scoffed at the assertion. ''If
their ads had been working the way they claim they have been
working, they would leave them up,'' she said. ''This is a sign of
panic over at the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The DNC ads, all of which feature Gore, have focused on
prescription drugs, the patients' bill of rights and fatherhood. A
new ad on education will begin running Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
