<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman signs bill aimed at shore 'animal houses'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Local towns can now bar underage drinking
on private property.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman signed a bill Wednesday that allows each
municipality in the state to pass an ordinance saying people under
the age of 21 are not allowed to drink or even possess alcoholic
beverages in private settings. Exemptions are made for religious
ceremonies or if a parent or guardian is present.
</P>
<P>
   ''This legislation will enable municipalities to take steps to
prevent underage persons from illegally consuming alcoholic
beverages in areas where they once could drink and not be affected
by the law,'' Whitman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Violators would be subject to a $200 fine for a first offense
and a $350 fine for any subsequent conviction. In addition to the
fine, up to 180 days of community service would be required.
Driving privileges could be either suspended or postponed for six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is levied if offenders have a driver's license.
If they do not, they cannot apply for one until six months after
they turn 17 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Bill sponsors said the law was designed to help police at towns
along the Jersey shore.
</P>
<P>
   ''So-called 'animal houses' with rampant underage drinking are
notorious problems at the shore. In many cases our local police
have their hands tied because they lack the tools to enforce laws
against underage drinking when it occurs on private property,''
state Sen. Leonard Connors, R-Ocean, said after the bill passed the
Legislature in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
