<DOCNO> APW20000628.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio campaign questions first lady's appearance aboard USS Kennedy </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAY SHORE, N.Y. (AP) - Rep. Rick Lazio's campaign staff fired a
shot across Senate rival Hillary Rodham Clinton's bow on Wednesday,
questioning her expected appearance aboard an aircraft carrier
during a July Fourth celebration next week in New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first lady's campaign should reimburse the taxpayers for
the massive costs of this event,'' said Lazio campaign manager Bill
Dal Col.
</P>
<P>
   The combined OpSail 2000 and the sixth International Naval
Review are expected to draw 50,000 or more visiting ships and small
craft to New York Harbor, believed to be the largest convergence of
vessels ever in one place.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is to review the 17-mile long line of warships
from aboard the missile cruiser USS Hue City, then board the
carrier USS John F. Kennedy to watch the stately tall ships sail up
the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clearly no accident that the first lady and her husband
have chosen New York - a state whose only connection to them is
Mrs. Clinton's Senate campaign - as the site of their Independence
Day activities,'' Dal Col said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has come under scrutiny for her use of taxpayer funds to
travel, but her campaign has maintained that she follows election
law. She flies on government aircraft on the advice of the Secret
Service and reimburses the government the same way presidential
candidates do: at the rate of a first-class commercial ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Lissa Muscatine, the first lady's White House press secretary,
said the president and his wife were invited by the Defense
Department last October and the president accepted in his role as
commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   ''She is going with him as first lady,'' Muscatine said. ''There
are these sort of official events every now and then, but in this
particular case she's going with the president and obviously, he's
the one who will be doing the speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col said that defining the celebration that way is
''laughable and shows a lack of respect for the intelligence of New
Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is expected to be in Albany on July Fourth on the second
leg of a five-day statewide bus tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1832 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercury Coach Fined $500  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Phoenix Mercury coach Cheryl Miller was fined
$500 by the WNBA on Wednesday for making derogatory remarks about
the officiating after her team's loss at Cleveland on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rules were being broken,'' an angry Miller said about the
officiating after the Rockers' 64-61 victory. ''They are paid to
know the rules, but messed up this call.''
</P>
<P>
   With 23.6 seconds to play, referees allowed Cleveland substitute
Mery Andrade to enter the game when Phoenix called a 20-second
timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Under WNBA rules, a team can substitute on a 20-second timeout
only if the team that called the timeout also makes a change.
Phoenix (8-4) did not make any changes.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade blocked a 3-point attempt by Tonya Edwards with 10.9
seconds to play as Phoenix had three chances to tie.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we acknowledge an error was made by the referees
regarding a substitution near the end of the game, we simply cannot
condone public criticism of the officiating by our teams,'' said
Connie Hurlbut, WNBA Director of Basketball Operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1833 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon: Navy Fleet Budget Short  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon said in a report to Congress that
under President Clinton's current budget it cannot afford to
sustain the fleet of about 306 Navy ships that it deems a bare
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The report released Wednesday also said the Pentagon is
considering an accelerated shipbuilding plan that would cost $4
billion to $5 billion more per year than is budgeted in the current
Pentagon spending plan through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   After a review of the nation's military needs in 1997, the
Pentagon concluded that the Navy should reduce its fleet to about
306 ships, including 12 aircraft carriers. In the years since, that
has proven problematic because it does not allow for continual
carrier presence in the Persian Gulf, the Mediterranean and the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Sustaining a 306-ship fleet requires the construction of 8.7 new
vessels each year to replace decommissioned ships. The report
acknowledged that Clinton's budget for fiscal years 2001-2005
allows for a shipbuilding rate of only 7.8 per year.
</P>
<P>
   In its report to Congress on Monday, the Pentagon said the next
major review of U.S. defense needs, scheduled to start in 2001,
would consider as ''one possible option'' building up the fleet to
360 ships, including 15 aircraft carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Building such a force would take a major commitment of
resources and require pacing over 15 to 20 years,'' the report
said. It would require building ships at an average rate of 11 per
year, which would cost an additional $4 billion to $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement responding to the Pentagon report, Sen. Olympia
Snowe, R-Maine, said it revealed ''a disturbing gap'' between what
the Pentagon says is needed for the long term and what Clinton's
budget provides.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe is chairwoman of the Senate Armed Services subcommittee on
seapower. Bath Ironworks in Maine is a major shipbuilder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1833 </TRAILER>
