<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Links Pollution With Deaths  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN POPE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Tiny pollution particles produced by everything
from cars to power plants are responsible for higher death rates
and more hospital stays among the elderly, according to a study.
</P>
<P>
   The study of 90 large American cities, released Wednesday by the
Health Effects Institute, confirms a link suggested by previous
smaller-scale studies. But it goes farther in isolating
''particulate matter'' as the cause of higher rates of death and
disease, separating it from pollutants such as ozone, sulfur
dioxide and carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at tiny atmospheric particles of 10 microns or
less in diameter. A micron is equal to one thousandth of a
millimeter.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of particulate matter comes from combustion
sources, such as cars and power plants. The other 40 percent comes
from construction, agriculture and road-related pollution, such as
minute pieces of brakes and tires.
</P>
<P>
   The report claimed to ''provide new and strong evidence linking
particulate air pollution to adverse health effects.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that on average, deaths increased 0.5 percent
for every 10 microgram increase in the number of particles per
cubic meter of air. Among the elderly, hospital admissions for
cardiovascular problems increased 1 percent for each 10 microgram
increase and cardiopulmonary admissions rose 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important to remember that a 0.5 percent increase
reflects a broad population base. A small percentage can affect a
large number of people,'' said Robert O'Keefe, the institute's vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not attempt to calculate how many lives increased
pollution might cost, or to fully address whether pollution merely
sped the deaths of people who already were gravely ill.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in death and disease was actually less than that
reported in several previous studies. But the authors of the latest
study said it uses more sophisticated statistical methods and
surveys a broader area -- meaning the results are less dramatic but
more credible.
</P>
<P>
   The highest correlation was found in cities in the Northeast,
especially New York, where the increase in mortality was more than
twice the average of other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said that might be due to more accurate data for
that area, or to a more unhealthy combination of pollutants there.
</P>
<P>
   The institute is funded in equal parts by the federal
Environmental Protection Agency and the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''We respect their findings,'' said Phil Colley, a spokesman for
Ford Motor Co., which also issued a statement calling for more
research on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1841 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-CT--Murder in Greenwich, 5th Ld-Writethru,1,000  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - There is ample evidence to justify
putting Kennedy cousin Michael Skakel on trial as an adult in the
1975 beating death of a Greenwich teen-ager, a prosecutor declared
Wednesday at the close of three dramatic days of hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict said Skakel's
purported confessions in the late 1970s to two former classmates at
a substance-abuse rehabilitation center were reason enough to make
him stand trial. Skakel's lawyer, Michael Sherman, accused those
witnesses of lying outright on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile Judge Maureen Dennis told the lawyers she would issue a
written ruling, though she did not indicate when.
</P>
<P>
   The proceedings, which began last week and ended Wednesday
afternoon, were held to determine if there was enough evidence to
proceed to trial with the case against Skakel, and if so, whether
he should be tried as a juvenile or as an adult in the Oct. 30,
1975 murder of 15-year-old Martha Moxley. Because he was 15 at the
time of the killing, Skakel's case has so far been handled in
juvenile court.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, now 39, is the son of Rushton Skakel Sr., a brother of
slain U.S. Sen. Robert F. Kennedy's widow, Ethel. The Skakels lived
across the street from the Moxleys in Belle Haven, an exclusive
gated community in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   For years, authorities suspected Skakel's older brother, Thomas,
then 17, in Moxley's killing. But no arrests were ever made, and
the case stalled until a grand jury consisting of a single judge
was appointed in 1998. In January, Michael Skakel was arrested
based on the grand juror's findings.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing arguments, Benedict cited the testimony of a
childhood friend of Skakel's who testified that more than 15 years
after the murder, Skakel admitted being at the spot where
15-year-old Moxley was killed at the time of her murder, although
he denied having anything to do with her death.
</P>
<P>
   Moxley's bludgeoned body was found on her family's estate on
Oct. 31, 1975. She had been with the Skakel brothers and other
teen-age friends the night before, when authorities believe she was
murdered as she left the Skakel house to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict said Skakel should be tried as an adult because ''no
Connecticut juvenile institution has the ability to deal in any way
with a 39- or 40-year-old man.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said the state's case was built on testimony that
amounted to lies. He said Skakel's clean criminal record since 1975
served as ''a crystal ball'' that showed he is an upstanding
citizen incapable of murder and does not require any kind of
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the benefit of 25 years of hindsight. For 25 years, he
has led an exemplary life,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Moxley's brother, John, later pointed out that Skakel has
not had a completely clean record since the killing, citing his
arrest in 1978 in Windham, N.Y., after leading police on a
high-speed chase. He was sent to Elan shortly after that incident.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, members of the Kennedy clan turned out to
support Skakel, including two of his cousins - Robert F. Kennedy
Jr. and Douglas Kennedy, both sons of Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a horrible, unspeakable tragedy, but it only compounds
it to blame Michael Skakel, who is innocent,'' Robert F. Kennedy
Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman called to the witness stand a former student at the Elan
School, a residential drug and alcohol treatment center in Maine
which Skakel attended in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, two former students at the school testified that
Skakel had confessed to them that he killed Moxley, who was
bludgeoned with a golf club. The 6-iron used in the murder was
traced to a set owned by the Skakels.
</P>
<P>
   One student, John Higgins, said Skakel confessed to him one
night 20 years ago during an erratic, tearful conversation. But
Higgins admitted he lied to investigators when they initially
questioned him about the alleged confession. He also admitted
asking about a $50,000 reward.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Coleman, another former Elan student, said Skakel told
him he drove Moxley's skull in with a golf club and declared: ''I'm
gonna get away with murder. I'm a Kennedy.'' Coleman went on to
describe his own life - filled with alcoholism, drug addiction, a
criminal record, homelessness, and living under a bridge at times.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, former student Alice Dunn said she never heard
Skakel admit to killing Moxley, even while he was undergoing
therapy that involved being pummeled in a boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   ''He denied vehemently, over and over again, 'No, no, no, no!'''
Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel was subjected to the treatment after he ran away from
Elan, Dunn testified. The ring was used to break down students'
resistance and force them to confront the root cause of their
emotional problems, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But later, during cross-examination, Benedict read portions of
Dunn's earlier testimony before a grand jury that appeared to
contradict what she said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In her grand jury testimony, Dunn quoted Skakel as saying, ''I
don't know if I did it; it was myself or my brother. It was one of
us, but I was in a blackout and I don't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other Elan students testified for the defense that they
never heard Skakel confess.
</P>
<P>
   But Benedict said in his closing arguments that prosecutors do
not claim Skakel made confessions to all of the more than 200
students at Elan. He said Higgins and Coleman had no reason to
fabricate the alleged confessions or to agree to testify against
Skakel after so many years other than wanting to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman also called a child advocate and state magistrate who
was a Skakel family friend.
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette Coomaraswamy said that in the early 1980s, when
Skakel was in his early 20s, she frequently asked him to speak to a
child advocacy group she helped found because he had overcome his
substance abuse problems and wanted to help others.
</P>
<P>
   She said she later introduced him to Mother Teresa because, ''He
seemed to want to give so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman then asked Coomaraswamy if she would go as far to say
that Skakel, even if he did kill Moxley - which she does not
believe - does not need rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, that's correct,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1842 </TRAILER>
