<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School construction bill, state budget up for final votes Thursday  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - There's a lot on state lawmakers' plates
Thursday, the last scheduled voting day before their summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   Promising the most drama is the multibillion dollar school
construction bill, details of which were still up in the air less
than 24 hours before the scheduled vote.
</P>
<P>
   A $21.5 billion state budget will also take center stage
Thursday as the state Assembly and Senate meet for the last
scheduled voting session before the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   A host of other bills, including those outlawing the drug
Ecstasy, mandating sprinklers in college dorm rooms, and putting
sex offenders names on the Internet, are also scheduled for action.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Senate President Donald DiFrancesco and Assembly
Speaker Jack Collins said late Wednesday there was still no
agreement on the school construction bill.
</P>
<P>
   The measure provides $6 billion for the state's 30 so-called
special needs school districts to replace or repair crumbling
buildings, and $2.6 million for all other districts.
</P>
<P>
   But differences between Senate and Assembly leaders over how to
parcel out the money and between the Legislature and Gov. Christie
Whitman over its escalating pricetag have led to the current
logjam.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman and the legislative leaders want to agree ahead of time
on what changes the governor will make to the bill, in the form of
a conditional veto, after the Senate votes on the version
previously approved by the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would then be for lawmakers in both houses to vote
again to agree with her changes.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a possibility the Assembly may postpone action on
the bill if members are not given enough time to digest any
agreed-upon changes, said Chuck Leitgeb, a spokesman for the lower
house.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a chance we may not do it if a conditional veto just
lands on us late,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the possibility that Assembly leaders may not be
happy with an agreement largely crafted between the Senate and the
governor's office, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there are changes that move some Republican members off the
bill, there could be a problem,'' the spokesman said. ''The real
test will be what the conditional veto language is.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman released a statement Wednesday night acknowledging the
school construction bill's uncertain fate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're close to a compromise with the Senate and we expect them
to take action. But at this point, we have no commitments from the
Assembly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the state budget, meanwhile, is virtually assured.
</P>
<P>
   The $21.5 billion spending plan passed legislative committees in
bipartisan fashion earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Overall school aid will hit $6.65 billion, with $2.75 billion of
it earmarked for the special needs districts.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also spends $701 million for the Transportation Trust
Fund, lowering the amount that will need to be financed with
long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bills can be viewed at the Office of Legislative Services Web
site located at http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1855 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Legislature Expels Senator  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- The Brazilian Senate expelled one of its
members Wednesday for allegedly misappropriating public funds, the
first time in its history the body has ejected a lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 52 in favor, 18 against and 10 abstentions, the
upper house impeached developer and Senator Luiz Estevao and
stripped him of his congressional immunity. The move paved the way
for his arrest on charges of embezzling nearly $93 million in the
building of the yet-unfinished Sao Paulo State Labor Courthouse by
his construction firm.
</P>
<P>
   Estevao has also been charged with overbilling the Sao Paulo
state government for the construction of the courthouse which
already cost public coffers $145 million. It was unclear by how
much he overbilled the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate expelled Estevao for ''lack of parliamentary
decorum'' because he allegedly lied about the involvement of his
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ''The expulsion is another blow against politicians who use and
abuse their mandates to break the law with impunity and then hide
behind their mandates,'' said attorney Reginaldo de Castro,
president of the Brazilian Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the lower house Chamber of Deputies expelled
Congressman Hildebrando Pascoal, who is now behind bars on charges
including drug trafficking, torture and murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
