<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, June 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Leaves U.S. for Cuba
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A plane carrying Elian Gonzalez and his father left for
Cuba today after the Supreme Court cleared the way for the 6-year-old refugee's
return home. Seven months after he was lifted from the sea -- his mother lost in
that desperate journey to America -- Elian took off in one of two chartered
planes to return to a nation that calls him its ''boy hero.'' The Supreme Court
had rejected a formal appeal filed by the boy's anti-communist Miami relatives.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Upholds 'Partial-Birth' Abortion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today limited states' power to ban
so-called ''partial-birth'' abortions, a 5-4 ruling that escalated the bitter,
decades-old debate over women's right to end their pregnancies. Closing out its
1999-2000 term with some of the most divisive rulings in years, the court struck
down Nebraska's partial-birth abortion law as an ''undue burden'' on women's
rights. The court also ruled that the Boy Scouts can bar homosexuals from
serving as troop leaders. The decision may also let the 6.2-million member
organization reject gay boys as members.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Archbishop Taken Hostage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- A man seeking help on a passport problem and claiming to
have a hand grenade took Archbishop Patrick Flores hostage this morning in his
office, and more than five hours later the Roman Catholic archbishop was still
being held. Hostage negotiators were at the scene along with 40 to 50 police
officers, bomb squad personnel and the FBI. The archbishop's secretary, Myrtle
Sanchez, was also taken hostage, but she was freed unharmed after nearly three
hours.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton: Scandals Won't Hurt Gore
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rushing to Al Gore's defense, President Clinton brushed
off the vice president's tumbling poll numbers, a possible campaign finance
investigation and the stigma of ''bogus'' scandals to say today, ''It's still
more likely than not that he will win'' over George W. Bush. Clinton combined
his measured assessment of Gore's prospects with lavish praise. ''Nobody has
ever done as much for America as Vice President Al Gore has,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Calif. Insurance Commissioner Quits
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush,
embroiled in one of the state's largest political controversies in years,
resigned today after being accused of using millions of dollars from insurance
settlements to further his own political career. The Republican's decision
averted the possibility of impeachment by the Legislature, which has been
investigating the deepening scandal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Energy Dept. Warns of Power Outages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson warned today some parts
of the country face an ''imminent'' threat of electric power outages. Richardson
said New England, California and the Pacific Northwest were in greatest
jeopardy. Earlier this week, Californians were urged to voluntarily reduce their
electricity use because of concerns during a heat wave.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Intel Introduces New Computer Chip
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Intel Corp. today introduced its new high-end
Pentium 4 computer chip, running at an advertised 1.5 billion bits of
information per second for faster graphics and game play. The Pentium 4, which
goes on sale this fall, far outpaces the processing power of AMD's recently
announced Athlon chip, which runs at 1 gigahertz, or 1 billion bits of
information per second.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Major Advance in Altering Sheep DNA
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Scientists have developed a way to alter genes in sheep and
insert new ones with unprecedented precision, a step toward creating healthier
livestock and using animals as organ banks. This is the first time so-called
gene targeting has been done in a mammal other than a mouse. Alan Colman,
research director at PPL Therapeutics in Edinburgh, Scotland -- the same
laboratory that helped produce Dolly the cloned sheep in 1996-- and his
colleagues presented their research in Thursday's issue of the journal Nature.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Ends Up 81; Dow Gains 23
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today after the Federal Reserve said it would
leave interest rates unchanged for now, but the central bank's warning that
inflation risks remain in the economy put pressure on financial stocks and other
inflation-sensitive sectors. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 23.33 to
10,527.79. Advancing issues outnumbered decliners 1,790-1,112 on the New York
Stock Exchange. The Nasdaq composite index rose 81.38 to 3,940.34.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sampras Survives at Wimbledon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Pete Sampras survived an ankle injury today at
Wimbledon, pulling out a 7-6 (9), 3-6, 6-3, 6-4 victory over Karol Kucera.
Sampras' bid for a record 13th Grand Slam title had seemed in jeopardy when he
took an injury timeout at 5-2 in the third set.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
