<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor: New complex makes Manhattan's West Side world's cultural center </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - New York's most spectacular new development is a
twin-tower media center designed as the headquarters of AOL and
Time Warner and the city's CNN base, ringed by retail and
residential space.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.7 billion Time Warner Center, a 55-story, glass complex
filling 2.8 million square feet above Broadway at the corner of
Central Park, ''is the city's icon for the 21st century - the way
Rockefeller Center was for the 20th,'' said Stephen Ross, head of
The Related Cos., one of three partners in the project.
</P>
<P>
   To be completed by 2003, it promises the world's first
performing arts theaters devoted to jazz, as well as shops,
restaurants, a five-star hotel, a garage and condominiums
overlooking the Hudson River and the Manhattan skyline.
</P>
<P>
   ''The complex will create a vibrant 24-hour-a-day community at
Columbus Circle,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   He credited Mayor Rudolph Giuliani with pushing forward a
project that has faced financial and bureacratic hurdles for almost
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The process began in 1985, when the city and the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority first tried to sell the land to a
developer. Mort Zuckerman's Boston Properties held the rights for
nine years, but did not finalize a deal. In 1997, Related submitted
a proposal that beat out several others.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to yield to New York City another tremendous
landmark,'' the mayor told a news conference hosted by CNN anchor
Bernard Shaw and attended by top executives of Time Warner and
other companies, as well as city officials.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani spoke under a tent in the middle of Columbus Circle,
near a statue of Christopher Columbus. Across the street lay the
rubble of the old New York Coliseum convention center, which was
built in 1953 and has since deteriorated. The Coliseum occupied
land that Related is to purchase from the MTA by the end of next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Dominating one of the city's most valuable and best-known sites
- two blocks at the southwest corner of Central Park - the Time
Warner Center will link Manhattan's Upper West Side with midtown
Manhattan and Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   According to the design by Skidmore Owings &AMP; Merrill architect
David M. Childs, the 750-foot tall glass towers, topped by metal
and glass ''lanterns,'' will rest on a base that curves around the
circle. The Time Warner studios will be housed behind a glass
facade on the eighth floor, above a retail gallery, with other
offices on lower floors.
</P>
<P>
   AOL awaits federal approval of its merger with Time Warner,
which would unify the world's largest Internet and media companies.
</P>
<P>
   The center's 203 condominium apartments will be on the 20th to
the 49th floors of the south tower, and the 36th to the 49th floors
of the north. The 249-room Mandarin Oriental hotel is to occupy
floors 15 to 35 of the north tower.
</P>
<P>
   The main public entry will be through a 150-foot high cable net
glass wall, with a circular shopping gallery stretching behind it
from West 60th Street to West 58th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is being financed with a $1.3 billion loan from
GMAC Commercial Mortgage Corp., which bills it as the largest loan
ever made for a private development project in the United States.
Apollo Real Estate Advisors and The Palladium Co. complete the
development partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The $103 million jazz center - tucked behind the main entrance -
will include a 1,100-seat theater flanked by rehearsal studios
wired for recording, broadcast and Webcast. A 600-seat performance
atrium with a dance floor and tables will feature star performers
playing in front of a 50-foot window overlooking Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   The complex, just blocks from Lincoln Center, makes Manhattan's
West Side ''the cultural center of the world,'' said Giuliani.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1905 </TRAILER>
