<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel proposes relocating Buffalo's Children's Hospital  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Relocating Children's Hospital into a
proposed new $152.5-million facility is considered the best move
for the institution's future, an independent advisory panel
concluded Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommended relocating the city hospital to High
Street where it would be linked by an overhead walkway to Buffalo
General Hospital. The proposed new location is also near Roswell
Park Cancer Institute, creating a massive hospital corridor in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations are now in the hands of Kaleida Health
System, which operates both Children's Hospital and Buffalo
General. Kaleida officials have said the recommendations would
serve as a guide in making the final decision on whether to move
the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is essential in the maintenance of keeping Children's
Hospital with a capital C and H, just that, a children's
hospital,'' advisory panel member Dr. Theodore Putman said.
</P>
<P>
   Health care providers worry the special needs of children could
be lost by mixing the facility in with other hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ''Naturally, I'm disappointed and somewhat surprised that this
conclusion was reached before a plan was drawn up,'' Dr. Steven
Lana said.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Ann Woloszyn said: ''I would hate to see children be
clumped with adults. Children have special needs and need special
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the facility, in its new location, would allow
the hospital to provide a full range of services to adult female
patients, something it cannot do now, and enhance other medical
services.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Buffalo is also interested in the hospital's
relocation. UB officials are prepared to spend $65 million to
establish a new outpatient center and medical research building in
the High Street area should Children's Hospital move.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo institution has operated out of the same Bryant
Street location for 108 years, and was the state's first children's
hospital when it opened in 1892.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommendations include coming up with a plan to
determine how to reuse the existing site, allaying the fears of
resident who don't want an abandoned building left behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1906 </TRAILER>
