<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Coming To Close in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
By NIKO PRICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOMA BLANCA, Mexico (AP) -- Mexico's presidential candidates made
last-minute appeals to voters Wednesday -- with one even coming to a
rally on horseback -- the final day of an increasingly bitter
campaign ahead of Sunday's tightly fought election.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show conservative opposition candidate Vicente Fox in a
dead heat with Francisco Labastida of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, which has governed Mexico since 1929 -- in what
appears to be one of the cleanest races in Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who has the best chance in at least a century to topple a
Mexican government at the ballot box, rode on horseback into a
rally of 10,000 people on a grassy field outside Loma Blanca, a
rural village about 35 miles west of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not one minute more!'' Fox declared in urging an end to the
PRI's 71-year hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   Loma Blanca has long been a PRI stronghold. According to
resident Luis Enriquez Alvarez: ''It was pure PRI here. ''Now ask
anyone and they will all tell you they want change -- now.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The PRI made a lot of promises that they never kept,'' said
his wife, Susana Chavez. ''Before the last elections they started
paving the road in our town. After the elections they stopped and
they haven't done anything since.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez claimed the PRI was offering voters 50 pesos for their
votes. ''If you are going to support someone it should be legal,''
she said. ''We don't have any reason to vote for someone for 50
pesos.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of its history, the PRI dominated all aspects of
Mexican political life. When popular support was lacking, it often
resorted to stuffing ballot boxes, intimidation and patronage to
assure itself of landslide victories.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mexicans believe that fraud cost opposition candidate
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas the 1988 election -- or at least widened the
margin of victory of Carlos Salinas de Gortari. With electoral
reforms in recent years, few people believe that kind of fraud
could occur again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Tractors, buses and cars carried men in cowboy boots and hats up
a narrow dirt road to the rally, where a band played ''ranchero,''
music and cheers and bottle rockets burst from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Fox noted his own youth on a farm, and promised he was ready
''to die in the line of duty as president to help you advance.''
</P>
<P>
   He also appealed to followers of Cardenas, the No. 3 candidate,
to join his campaign to ''get the PRI out of Los Pinos,'' the
presidential residence.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas and his leftist Democratic Revolution Party have no
chance for victory, Fox told the cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas has repeatedly refused to join an alliance with Fox and
has repeatedly accused Fox of breaking campaign laws and of being
subservient to U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas appeared before a small crowd of about 500 people in
the gulf coast oil city of Ciudad del Carmen on Wednesday, saying
the oil industry was symbolic of the nation: a promising resource
misused by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Maribel Castillo, 28, had the yellow sun symbol of Cardenas'
party painted on her cheeks, but said, ''If this had been for Fox,
I still would have come... I'm just tired of the PRI and I want a
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida had a quiet schedule Wednesday ahead of his late-night
closing campaign rally in Culiacan in Sinaloa.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he appealed for reconciliation after the election:
''The important thing is that there is neither rancor nor hatred
among Mexicans after the 3rd,'' Labastida said at a rally in
Cuernavaca, south of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of those words was undercut by his repeated
television commercials on Wednesday accusing Fox of being an
anti-patriotic liar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1906 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statistics debunk notion that racial profiling ingrained in troopers </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The rank-and-file troopers have never been
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Racial profiling may be a tricky and painful door to unlock. But
new statistics seem to show that the individual prejudices, skills
and training of the men and women of the New Jersey State Police
will not provide a key to unlocking it.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic-stop statistics released Tuesday might show racial
profiling is still an issue on the New Jersey Turnpike, but it is
clearly not an issue anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Attorney General John Farmer said the new numbers are
too new to say anything.
</P>
<P>
   An American Civil Liberties Union lawyer called the new numbers
- and the state's lackluster response to them - an outrage.
</P>
<P>
   An official in the troopers' union said the new numbers prove
racial profiling is a myth.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers do show more directly than ever before that if
racial discrimination does exist, there is nothing inherent in the
makeup of the typical New Jersey state trooper to account for it.
</P>
<P>
   If it were true that troopers relied on bigotry to select which
drivers to stop, it would be true off the turnpike. It is not.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, about 26 percent of the 118,000 drivers who got
pulled over by troopers from January to April were minorities,
according to the first comprehensive breakdown ever of traffic-stop
patterns across the entire state.
</P>
<P>
   The race breakdown was as follows: 16 percent black, 6 percent
Hispanic, 4 percent Asians or other racial ethnicities.
</P>
<P>
   A Census Bureau wonk could not have predicted it better. The
census shows 27 percent of New Jersey's 8.1 million residents are
minorities: 13 percent black, 10 percent Hispanic and 4 percent
Asians or other racial ethnicities.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, troopers are pulling over precisely the share of
minority drivers one would expect them to nab as a fair, normal,
random proportion of the state's population.
</P>
<P>
   The results for the turnpike were sharply different. There, 38
percent of the drivers who were pulled over were minorities. Of the
motorists stopped by those troopers who patrol the southern leg of
the nation's busiest highway, 45 percent were minorities.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that something is going on along the turnpike
that will remain a matter of debate at the Statehouse and in
courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Reginald Jackson, executive director of the Black
Ministers Council of New Jersey, was disturbed by the 38-percent
figure, as was Bill Buckman, who handled the state's most famous
racial-profiling litigation in 1996 on behalf of the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   Union vice president David Jones, who patrolled the turnpike for
eight years, said the numbers were normal and to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   ''What man can look at these numbers and suggest any other
reason than that the people who are getting stopped are the people
who are breaking the law,'' Jones said. ''There is no such animal
as racial profiling. It is jargon that has taken on a life of its
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Paul Zoubek said all of the numbers
are inconclusive, especially since no thorough studies have been
finished on the racial demographics of turnpike travelers.
</P>
<P>
   But what it means off of the turnpike seems clear. When the
turnpike units are extracted, State Police barracks elsewhere in
the state executed 90,382 traffic stops. Of those, 22 percent of
the drivers were minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a trooper supposedly inclined to hunt down black
drivers on the turnpike, treating them like criminal suspects
merely for ''driving while black,'' suddenly lose this inclination
when assigned to work elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   The most logical answer would appear to be that state troopers
who leave the turnpike for other assignments - as most do after
three or four years - do not lose a personal inclination toward
racist treatment because they never had one in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   In the reports from Whitman administration officials and
comments from Gov. Christie Whitman herself and from others, there
has been an underlying message that the New Jersey State Police,
once widely praised as elite, is now soiled by a handful of ''bad
apples.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckman, no friend of the State Police, never accepted the
bad-apple notion, focusing blame on uniformed supervisors and
civilians in charge of law-enforcement policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Turnpike troopers) were exposed to racially stereotypical
training that taught them that color was suspect, and that their
career would be advanced by stopping as many people of color as
possible,'' Buckman said. ''This is agency-driven statistics, not a
few bad apples. This comes from the top down.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the changes imposed by Farmer and the new
superintendent, Carson Dunbar, seem designed to deal with the
mythical bad trooper.
</P>
<P>
   They have begun computer monitoring troopers on patrol,
conducted retraining on the meaning of the U.S. Constitution,
installed video cameras in patrol cars and beefed up the staff of
the hated Internal Affairs office.
</P>
<P>
   Jones calls it all a crackdown. He said with all of this
monitoring, no one could suspect that the high proportion of
minority stops on the turnpike has anything to do with a racist
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is suggesting that our people are either so arrogant or so
stupid to continue in this act with so much public scrutiny on
this,'' Jones said. ''Their careers, their families are at stake.
Who in their right mind would do this?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 1913 </TRAILER>
