<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Protest GOP Drug Plan  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In pitched partisan battle, Republicans
advanced election-year Medicare prescription drug legislation
toward a House vote Wednesday, brushing aside a veto threat from
President Clinton and the vociferous objections of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is time to modernize Medicare by adding a prescription drug
benefit so that all seniors can get the chance to enjoy their
golden years,'' said Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., advocating a
plan that relies on a blend of private insurance companies and
federal subsidies to spread coverage nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri, who led
his rank and file on a brief walkout to protest GOP tactics,
sharply disagreed. ''It's a sham. It's a hoax. It's public
relations. It's electioneering. It is not writing a plan that will
help people,'' he said after returning to the Capitol for the
daylong debate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats prepared a costlier alternative with a uniform,
government-defined prescription drug benefit, offered to all 39
million senior citizens now enrolled in Medicare. But majority
Republicans, arguing that the $100 billion price tag exceeded the
$40 billion contained in their budget, refused to allow a vote on
it.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills included provisions to help low-income senior
citizens and those with particularly high annual drug expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Costs under the GOP plan would vary by policy, but Republicans
estimated a $250 annual deductible, a $35 to $40 monthly premium
and a 50-50 split on the first $2,100 in expenses. Catastrophic
coverage would begin after a senior had spent $6,000 out of pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said their plan had a premium beginning at $25 a
month, gradually doubling as benefits increased. There would no
deductible and a 50-50 split up to $2,000 in costs, rising
gradually to $5,000. Catastrophic coverage would kick in at $4,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to cede an easy political triumph to Republicans,
Democrats forced roughly a dozen votes on time-consuming procedural
motions throughout day. In addition, they took the unusual step of
requiring the text of their 78-page alternative be read aloud from
the House podium.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans betrayed little anxiety about the outcome, and one
Democrat, Rep. Jerry Klezcka of Wisconsin, conceded the GOP bill
would ultimately pass.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hastert huddled on the House floor at one point with Rep.
JoAnn Emerson, a Missouri Republican who expressed misgivings about
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   She said she feared coverage would not be available in rural
areas, noting that in parts of her district, HMOs no longer offer
coverage for basic Medicare hospital and doctor coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Also, several Democrats referred during the day to a letter from
the head of the Health Insurance Association of America expressing
doubt that companies would choose to write policies under the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most fiery rhetoric of the day came from Rep. Jim
Traficant, D-Ohio, who chastised fellow Democrats for their
walkout. ''JFK would have never walked out from a fight. ...
Warriors do not walk out,'' he said, declaring his intention to
support the GOP measure as a good first step toward prescription
drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans maneuvered in other ways to maximize their support,
inserting a provision at the last minute designed to reassure HMOs
that they are prepared to increase their Medicare payments in
future legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton weighed in with a written veto threat, then criticized
Republicans at a White House news conference: ''The bottom line is
their plan is designed to benefit the companies who make the
prescription drugs, not the older Americans who need to take
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Polling indicates the issue ranks high with Americans 65 and
older, a group that accounted for more than one-quarter of voters
in the 1998 elections and is regarded as a key swing group in the
coming fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With elections to determine control of the House little more
than four months away, the debate was thoroughly political
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, Democrats questioned the motivation of
Republicans, reading from advice a GOP pollster recently gave
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of providing prescription coverage for seniors, it
provides political coverage for Republicans,'' charged Rep. Robert
Wexler, D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert acknowledged the issue's political importance, but
rebutted the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Citing reports that Democrats have already tested campaign
advertisements on the issue, he said, ''My friends, put those
commercials away. America is sick and tired of bickering. Americans
just want us to create a product that will benefit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in both parties used pill vials as props. Several
Democrats held them aloft, complaining the Republican plan would
leave them empty. But Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., pulled a length
of rad tape from one bottle, and said that's what senior citizens
would get if the Democratic plan were adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill is H.R. 4680.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1914 </TRAILER>
