<DOCNO> APW20000628.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Australian Art on Display  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Paintings by modern Australian Aborigines that
went on show in Washington on Wednesday belong to a tradition that
goes back 40,000 years, said George MacDonald, director of the
Melbourne Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the oldest art tradition in the world,'' he told
reporters at the opening of a show called ''Spirit Country'' in the
headquarters of the National Geographic Society.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Isaacs, curator of the show, sees a continuing line from
ancient rock and cave paintings, through designs drawn on the soil
and on people's bodies, to today's paintings on canvas and bark.
</P>
<P>
   A photo show on Australian scenery that opened a week ago, and
another that also opened Wednesday called ''The Great White Shark:
In Danger Down Under,'' make up a trio on the island continent at
the society's Explorers Hall. An 18-foot model of the shark has
been included to help show the danger to the killer fish from
commercial fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   There will be an Australian film festival -- shorts, features and
documentaries -- from July 19 to 22.
</P>
<P>
   Though more than 350,000 Aborigines remain among Australia's 19
million people, about 50 separate communities produce paintings and
artifacts now in great demand among collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are painting as we have always done, to demonstrate our
continuing link with our country and the rights and
responsibilities we have to it,'' wrote Galarrwuy Yunupingu, leader
of the Gumatj people in northern Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We paint to show the rest of the world that we own the country
and the land owns us. Our painting is a political act.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 works look like abstract art, but the people who
make them see them as maps, personal histories, religious documents
and even title deeds to land. They describe intricate tales and
ceremonies, separate for men and women, easily understood by each
community and its neighbors and now highly valued by outsiders even
though they need experts to explain them.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   ''Spirit Country: Australian Aboriginal Art'' will be in
Explorers Hall through Aug. 13. ''Australia Through the National
Geographic Lens'' and ''The Great White Shark: In Danger Down
Under'' will close Oct. 1. Admission is free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 1937 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cubans Arrange Welcome for Elian  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Several hundred children from Elian Gonzalez's
school lined up on an airport tarmac to await the boy's arrival
Wednesday evening while the government urged citizens not celebrate
in the streets when the boy returned to his communist homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them carrying small red, white and blue Cuban flags, the
children, dressed in their school uniforms, were led by adults from
Elian's school in his hometown of Cardenas, a port city east of
here.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Alarcon, president of Cuba's National Assembly, was to
greet the 6-year-old, his family and his schoolmates upon their
arrival Wednesday night, the government said in a statement read on
state television. Alarcon has served as a key adviser to Elian's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, during the protracted custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation that Fidel Castro would greet the
boy, but the statement made no mention of the Cuban president, who
had made the fight for Elian's return a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be no official reception nor will there be a mass
mobilization,'' said the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The million of compatriots who have made so much effort to
achieve this objective will enjoy their celebration in the most
intimate part of their hearts, in their homes, or in conjunction
with their closest neighbors,'' said another government statement,
issued later.
</P>
<P>
   It urged citizens ''not to rush out into the streets, overcome
with enthusiasm in expressions of happiness.'' Such behavior, it
said ''would not be the most correct and convenient in this chapter
of our fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When he took off, we all had goose bumps,'' said airport
worker Gisela Diazo, who watched the live televised takeoff of the
plane carrying Elian and his family home from the United States.
''We are all crazy for Elian!''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have won this battle, but we are going to have to keep on
fighting,'' added Dorelis Gonzalez, who also works at the airport
terminal where Elian was scheduled to arrive later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Castro has said all along that no major homecoming would be
planned for Elian, who he has characterized as a ''boy hero'' and
''symbolic child.'' The idea has been to cause Elian as little
trauma as possible and speed his return to a normal life in his
native country.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's friends in his hometown of Cardenas on Wednesday
afternoon traveled to Havana to greet Elian as he returned after
seven months in the United States, residents told journalists
there. A small group representing Elian's first grade classmates
was to meet him at the airport, then the boy was to travel to an
undisclosed site for a one-hour meeting with the whole group, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, 11 buses filled with 200-300 children of varying
ages arrived at the airport Wednesday night about an hour before
the boy was scheduled to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was to stay with his family and classmates for two or
three weeks in Havana at a specially prepared boarding school
before returning to Cardenas, where he was born and raised.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans learned on state television and radio that Elian was
headed home after the U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear the appeal
of the Miami relatives, who were seeking to keep Elian in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now more than ever, our population must behave with the most
dignity, serenity and discipline,'' the statement said. ''Let us
remember that at all times, our fight has just begun and that a
long road before us still remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro has said that even after Elian returns, Cubans must not
take a moment's rest in demanding an end to the four-decade-old
U.S. embargo on the island and American policies that allow Cubans
who reach U.S. soil to remain.
</P>
<P>
   The muted reaction by Cubans appeared to be part of a determined
effort by the government to make Elian's return as low-key as
possible in contrast to what government officials have called the
''circus'' that surrounded much of his life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wait with tranquility the triumph of justice and the end of
the kidnapping,'' ran a headline Wednesday in Granma, the official
daily of Cuba's Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, Castro promised there would be no street
celebrations, no parades when the boy returns -- despite a national
campaign in Cuba that put Elian's face on billboards, placards and
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over Elian began in late November when the child was
rescued off the Florida coast. His mother and 10 other people
drowned when their boat sank en route from Cuba to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was turned over to his Miami relatives, who began fighting
to keep him with them. The boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
fought to have the child returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Cubans backed the effort to return the boy to Cuba --
a campaign that has seen over 100 government organized rallies
across the country attended by hundreds of thousands of Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Sambiente, sitting on a park bench in Havana's Parque
Central, said Elian and his family should remain in the United
States because they would have a better life than in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm one of the 50 percent who wants him to stay,'' Sambiente
said. ''The mother wanted him to stay. She died doing that. It was
the last wish of the mother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
