<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Union Leader Joins Umps Talks  </HEADLINE>
By RONALD BLUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The president of Richie Phillips' old umpires'
union joined the new union's negotiating team in what may be the
first step toward ending the divisive fight that has engulfed the
sport for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   NL ump Jerry Crawford attended Tuesday's bargaining session and
endorsed a joint statement issued Wednesday by all 68 major league
umps and 187 minor league umps, who are separately trying to form
their own union.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something that can help heal umpires and bring us
together,'' said John Hirschbeck, president of the new union, the
World Umpires Association. ''He participated at the table and was
of great help to us when we were amongst ourselves, talking at
different breaks. His insight was very, very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford did not want to elaborate on the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of things are very sensitive here,'' he said. ''The way
things are going, I would rather just remain silent. I would like
to get a deal done.''
</P>
<P>
   NL ump Bruce Froemming, a board member of the Major League
Umpires Association and a vocal Phillips supporter, said he viewed
Crawford's inclusion ''as a positive step.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about all umpires,'' Froemming said. ''We have to come
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Umpires and management called Tuesday's session productive, then
recessed talks until July 5.
</P>
<P>
   The old labor contract expired Dec. 31, and an interim extension
is due to lapse Friday. Both sides said they wouldn't renew the
extension, which means starting Saturday they can call a work
stoppage on 14 days' notice. But neither a strike nor a lockout
appeared imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The ''joint statement of principles'' attacked some of the
demands made by the commissioner's office in negotiations for a new
labor contract, saying umpires had the right to ''exercise
independent judgment ... to call each pitch or play as they see it,
without threat of recrimination or discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Umpires also said ''none should be disciplined or dismissed
without just cause and only after the right to a full hearing
before a neutral arbitrator'' and that umpires ''must have the
right to express their points of view in public, to speak their
opinions and to defend their good names and reputations in the
press.''
</P>
<P>
   Management wants umpires to agree not to speak with reporters
without prior written consent from the commissioner's office,
except for crew chiefs, who would be permitted to discuss
controversial calls.
</P>
<P>
   None of the four major sports has arbitration clauses in the
labor contracts of officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've expressed their views across the table and they're
inconsistent with the terms of the collective bargaining agreements
of every official in professional sports,'' management negotiator
Rob Manfred said. ''Stating them in a public proclamation makes
them no more likely to be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have tried to conduct a private and positive collective
bargaining process and unfortunately for the second time in two
weeks, the umpires have elected to inject publicity into the
process in way that's never helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the new union went public with the divisive areas.
Among them in the status of the 22 umpires let go last September
after Phillips' mass resignation plan backfired. Wednesday's
statement said those umpires sustained harm that ''must be
remedied.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners have offered to rehire an unspecified number of the 22 as
part of a new labor contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 22 resigned. They were not released,'' Manfred said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for minor league umps, who have asked the federal
government for permission to form their own union, attacked the
governing body of the minor leagues, accusing it of obstructing
organization efforts and of illegally firing two umps because of
their union activities.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear to us that they're engaging in stall tactics,
trying to break their solidarity, their spirit, trying to drag
these things out,'' said Beth Sandon, a lawyer for the Association
of Minor League Umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Umpires and representatives of the National Association of
Professional Baseball Leagues, the governing body of the minors,
had a hearing Monday at the Baltimore office of the National Labor
Relations Board, but could not agree on an election procedure,
leaving the decision to the NLRB regional director.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems that lawyers can't represent umpires without engaging
in misrepresentation,'' said George Yund, a lawyer for the National
Association. ''Minor league baseball has cooperated in every
possible was with the National Labor Relations Board.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the reasons for the termination of the two umps, Steve
Mattingly of the Pacific Coast League and Jeff Kowalczyk of the
International League, were unrelated to union activity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
