<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Scandals Won't Hurt Gore  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rushing to Al Gore's defense, President
Clinton brushed off his tumbling poll numbers, a possible campaign
finance investigation and the stigma of ''bogus'' scandals to say
Wednesday, ''It's still more likely than not that he will win''
over George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton combined his measured assessment of Gore's prospects
with lavish praise of his vice president. ''Nobody has ever done as
much for America as vice president as Al Gore has,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than five months before the election, presidential politics
took center stage at Clinton's hour-long news conference in the
East Room, his third this year.
</P>
<P>
   The president refused to express an opinion about whether Bush,
the likely Republican presidential nominee, is smart enough to be
president.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a dead bang loser,'' Clinton said with a laugh as he
evaded the question and said the most important qualities are
curiosity and a willingness to learn. He did not judge Bush on
either point, but said Gore has spent 20 years working on arms
control issues.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore trails Bush in public opinion polls, Clinton said
he thinks Americans ''are still trying to figure out what they
think about this race.'' He complained that ''the word 'scandal'
has been thrown around here like a clanging teapot for seven
years'' and said there is no evidence Gore has been harmed by
anything that Clinton did.
</P>
<P>
   Gore trails Bush by 12 or 13 percentage points in a couple of
recent polls, while others still show the race close.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he appreciated the comments. ''I haven't read the full
transcript, but everybody that mentioned it to me said that he had
some really good things to say and I appreciate it,'' the vice
president said aboard his campaign plane.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton misspoke by saying that Attorney General Janet Reno had
decided not to appoint a special counsel to investigate whether
Gore told the truth about a 1996 Buddhist temple fund-raiser.
Reno's decision is still pending; twice before she has declined to
appoint a special counsel in Gore's case.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see any reason that the attorney general shouldn't
make a decision in this case as she has in every other one,''
Clinton said. Presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton
meant that Reno should make her decision based on the facts and the
law rather than political pressure, and was not suggesting that
Reno should again decline to launch an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the best thing is for the American people to make
their own decision,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there was a ''lot of volatility in these polls. ... It's
still more likely than not that he (Gore) will win.''
</P>
<P>
   On other questions, Clinton said:
</P>
<P>
   --That ''inherently there's nothing wrong'' with suspending all
or part of the federal gasoline tax to ease prices, but that
Congress would then have to deal with the impact of lost revenues
on highway construction projects and ensure that the lower gas
costs were passed on to motorists.
</P>
<P>
   --The ''only real answer'' to rising gasoline prices is to
develop alternative energy sources and more efficient ways of using
existing energy supplies. ''We can do it in a hurry if we just put
our minds to it.''
</P>
<P>
   --He would be inclined to sign a bill allowing food and drug
sales to Cuba if it does not intrude on the president's foreign
policy powers. But he said he would not support immediate easing of
broader trade sanctions against Fidel Castro's regime.
</P>
<P>
   --He had some regret over the seven-month ordeal of Elian
Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban boy who became the center of a
political firestorm in a child custody case. ''Do I wish it had
unfolded in less dramatic, less traumatic ways for all concerned?''
Clinton said. ''Of course I do.''
</P>
<P>
   --DNA evidence should be used as much as possible to ensure only
the guilty are sentenced to death. ''I think that those of us who
support the death penalty have an extra heavy responsibility to
assure both that the result if accurate and that the process was
fair and constitutional,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   --The possible threat of a missile attack from North Korea has
not receded because of the recent summit between North and South
Korea. ''Would I like it (the threat) to go away? Of course I
would. Do I think it's gone away because of this meeting? I don't.
Do I think it might? It might, and I hope it will, but we don't
know that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   --He's ''generally against discrimination against gays,'' but he
refused to criticize the Supreme Court's decision that the Boy
Scouts can bar homosexuals from serving as troop leaders. ''The Boy
Scouts still are -- they're a great group, they do a lot of good.''
</P>
<P>
   --All paramilitary groups with secret arms caches in Northern
Ireland should follow the lead of the Irish Republican Army and
allow inspections. ''I think this is a great deal ... a very
hopeful development.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Clinton transcript: 
http://www.whitehouse.gov/library/PressReleases.cgi?date=0&AMP;briefing
3
</P>
</TEXT>
