<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, June 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Gonzalez Arrives in Cuba
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Seven months after he was cast adrift in the Florida straits,
Elian Gonzalez returned to his native Cuba tonight, bringing to a close an
international custody battle laced with Cold War passions. Cuba's state
television broadcast live images of the two small jets carrying Elian, his
father, stepmother and baby half brother, along with other Cubans as they landed
in Havana after the three-hour journey from Washington. Elian's return ended the
seven-month national campaign to bring the boy home from the United States,
where his Miami relatives had fought to keep him.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IBM Announces New Supercomputer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- IBM announced today it has built the most powerful
supercomputer in the world, able to perform 12.3 trillion operations per second,
three times faster than the next-fastest computer. An earlier version proved
capable of defeating the world's greatest chess player in a 1997 tournament. The
latest machine is intended to continue the advance toward matching and
eventually surpassing the computing capacity of the human brain. The computer,
called Advanced Strategic Computing Initiative White, or ASCI White, covers
9,920 square feet of floor space, equal to two NBA basketball courts, and weighs
106 tons.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Upholds 'Partial-Birth' Abortion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today limited states' power to ban
so-called ''partial-birth'' abortions, a 5-4 ruling that escalated the bitter,
decades-old debate over women's right to end their pregnancies. Closing out its
1999-2000 term with some of the most divisive rulings in years, the court struck
down Nebraska's partial-birth abortion law as an ''undue burden'' on women's
rights. The court also ruled that the Boy Scouts can bar homosexuals from
serving as troop leaders. The decision may also let the 6.2-million member
organization reject gay boys as members.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Archbishop Taken Hostage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- A man seeking help on a passport problem and claiming to
have a hand grenade took Archbishop Patrick Flores hostage this morning in his
office, and more than eight hours later the Roman Catholic archbishop was still
being held. Hostage negotiators were at the scene along with 40 to 50 police
officers, bomb squad personnel and the FBI. The archbishop's secretary, Myrtle
Sanchez, was also taken hostage, but she was freed unharmed after nearly three
hours.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton: Scandals Won't Hurt Gore
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rushing to Al Gore's defense, President Clinton brushed
off the vice president's tumbling poll numbers, a possible campaign finance
investigation and the stigma of ''bogus'' scandals to say today, ''It's still
more likely than not that he will win'' over George W. Bush. Clinton combined
his measured assessment of Gore's prospects with lavish praise. ''Nobody has
ever done as much for America as Vice President Al Gore has,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Campaign Coming To Close in Mexico
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOMA BLANCA, Mexico (AP) -- Mexico's presidential candidates made last-minute
appeals to voters Wednesday -- with one even coming to a rally on horseback --
the final day of an increasingly bitter campaign ahead of Sunday's tightly
fought election. Polls show conservative opposition candidate Vicente Fox in a
dead heat with Francisco Labastida of the Institutional Revolutionary Party,
which has governed Mexico since 1929 -- in what appears to be one of the
cleanest races in Mexican history.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Energy Dept. Warns of Power Outages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson warned today some parts
of the country face an ''imminent'' threat of electric power outages. Richardson
said New England, California and the Pacific Northwest were in greatest
jeopardy. Earlier this week, Californians were urged to voluntarily reduce their
electricity use because of concerns during a heat wave.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Ends Up 81; Dow Gains 23
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today after the Federal Reserve said it would
leave interest rates unchanged for now, but the central bank's warning that
inflation risks remain in the economy put pressure on financial stocks and other
inflation-sensitive sectors. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 23.33 to
10,527.79. Advancing issues outnumbered decliners 1,790-1,112 on the New York
Stock Exchange. The Nasdaq composite index rose 81.38 to 3,940.34.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Jersey Picks Kenyon Martin
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Kenyon Martin of Cincinnati, the consensus college player
of the year, broke down in tears tonight as he was selected first overall in the
NBA draft by the New Jersey Nets. Martin, who wasn't 100 percent certain he'd be
picked first, hugged his family before pulling on a Nets cap. The Nets had
entertained numerous trade offers for the 6-foot-9 center-forward whose
collegiate career was ended prematurely by a broken leg, but they decided to
keep it and use it on Martin.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
