<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Archbishop Taken Hostage  </HEADLINE>
By KELLEY SHANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Archbishop Patrick Flores decided to enter
the priesthood while working in a beer-soaked Texas dance hall as a
teen-ager -- mopping up beer and cigarette butts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just thinking -- not having visions or anything like that
-- but I said 'I should not go to work for smoke and stench,'''
Flores told The Associated Press in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He rose to become the nation's first Mexican-American Catholic
bishop.
</P>
<P>
   While he was held hostage Wednesday by a man said to be
distraught over a passport problem, Flores' colleagues, friends and
parishioners prayed for the man known to many as simply ''Patrick''
or ''Patricio.''
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming archbishop in August 1979, Flores, 70, has gained
a reputation as an advocate for immigrants and the poor and for
determinedly opposing violence.
</P>
<P>
   His bilingualism and humble background have made for close ties
between Flores and the 1 million Roman Catholics in his largely
Hispanic archdiocese, which covers 23 counties and stretches to the
Texas-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   His bilingual Sunday Mass at San Fernando Cathedral is televised
throughout the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Flores was born in Ganado, about 70 miles southwest of Houston,
the seventh of nine children in a migrant farm worker family.
</P>
<P>
   He became a priest in 1956. After working for years as a priest
in Houston, he was named auxiliary bishop in San Antonio in 1970,
the nation's first Mexican-American to reach that level. He was a
bishop in El Paso before becoming archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Flores welcomed Pope John Paul II as his houseguest
during the pontiff's visit to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Flores is no stranger to controversy, whether stirred by his
protests against abortion or modern art he deems sacrilegious. He
has weathered allegations of sexual misconduct against priests in
his district and opposition to archdiocese plans to renovate aging
churches.
</P>
<P>
   He unveiled ''no guns'' signs in early 1996 -- as the state's
concealed handgun law went into effect -- warning in English and
Spanish that weapons were not permitted on church property.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that the good that guns may seem to do is only
temporary,'' Flores said, ''but the harm they do is permanent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 2011 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
