<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutor: Evidence To Try Skakel  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- After three days of hearings, the
decision on whether a Kennedy relative should stand trial as an
adult in the 1975 beating death of a teen-age neighbor was in the
hands of a judge.
</P>
<P>
   State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict said in closing arguments
Wednesday that Michael Skakel's purported confessions in the late
1970s to two former classmates at a substance-abuse rehabilitation
center were reason enough to make him stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's lawyer, Michael Sherman, accused those witnesses of
lying on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding Judge Maureen Dennis said she would issue a ruling,
though she did not indicate when. She said she would take as much
time as she needed to review the law and the transcript of the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The proceedings, which began last week and ended Wednesday
afternoon, were held to see if there was enough evidence to proceed
with the case against Skakel. And if so, whether he should be tried
as a juvenile or an adult in the 1975 beating death of Martha
Moxley, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, now 39, was also 15 at the time of the killing. He is
the son of Rushton Skakel Sr., a brother of Ethel Kennedy, the
widow of Sen. Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing arguments, Benedict cited the testimony of a
childhood friend of Skakel's who testified that more than 15 years
after the murder, Skakel admitted being in the same spot where
15-year-old Moxley was killed -- and at the time she was slain. He
said that effectively placed Skakel at the scene at the time of the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict said Skakel should be tried as an adult because ''no
Connecticut juvenile institution has the ability to deal in any way
with a 39- or 40-year-old man.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman, the defense lawyer, said the state's case was built on
testimony that amounted to lies. He said Skakel's clean criminal
record served as ''a crystal ball'' that showed he is an upstanding
citizen incapable of a murder.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman called to the witness stand a former student at the Elan
School, a residential drug and alcohol treatment center in Maine
which Skakel attended as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, two former students at the school testified that
Skakel had confessed to them that he killed Moxley, who was
bludgeoned with a golf club. The 6-iron used in the murder was
traced to a set owned by the Skakels.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, former student Alice Dunn said she never heard
Skakel admit to killing Moxley, even while undergoing therapy that
involved being pummeled in a boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   ''He denied vehemently, over and over again, 'No, no, no, no!'''
Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel was subjected to the treatment after he ran away from
Elan, Dunn testified. The ring was used to break down students'
resistance and force them to confront the root cause of their
emotional problems, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, members of Skakel's extended family --
including Robert F. Kennedy Jr. -- turned out to support Skakel.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a horrible, unspeakable tragedy, but it only compounds
it to blame Michael Skakel, who is innocent,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 2012 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug, green card sting nets 159 arrests in six states  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A yearlong investigation into a heroin and
cocaine ring that traded green cards for cash and drugs, resulted
in the arrest Wednesday of 105 people in six states, federal and
state agents said.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ''Operation Wildcard,'' the sting put federal and state
agents inside a drug ring that operated in New York, New Jersey,
Connecticut, Florida, Georgia and Massachusetts. It started in
April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   One posed as a corrupt Immigration and Naturalization Services
agent offering to create documents like a resident alien card,
known as ''green cards,'' for a fee, paid in large amounts of
heroin, cocaine or cash worth anywhere from $5,000 to $13,000, a
press release from several agencies said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other agents portrayed drug traffickers with connections to
the corrupt INS worker. The drug dealers wanted the documentation
so they and their workers could travel freely between the United
States and their home countries, the agencies said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigations resulted in payments and seizures totaling
nearly $400,000 in cash, 10.25 kilograms of heroin, 11 kilograms of
cocaine and three vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Police are still searching for 54 people named in federal
indictments on a raft of charges including conspiracy to distribute
cocaine and heroin, distribution of cocaine and heroin, conspiracy
to bribe a public official, establishing a criminal enterprise for
the purpose of evading provisions of the immigration law,
transportation of illegal aliens, and re-entry after deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Upon conviction of the crimes, depending the amount of drugs
involved, the penalties cover a wide range from a minimum of five
years to a maximum of life in prison. Convictions also can carry a
fine ranging from $250,000 to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of those indicted, 107 were from New York, 28 from New Jersey,
eight from Connecticut, six from Florida and five each from Georgia
and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Operation Wildcard'' was a reprise of a 1991-93 operation
called ''Operation Cali-Cardgame,'' which led to the prosecution of
150 people and the seizure of 26 kilograms of cocaine, eight
kilograms of crack cocaine, two kilograms of heroin, 12 vehicles
and $1.2 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The multi-agency Organized Crime Drug Enforcement Task Force was
comprised of the Unites States Attorney's Office, New York State
Police, INS, U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration, Federal Bureau
of Investigation, U.S. Marshals and U.S. Customs Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-28-00 2013 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000628.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Girl's Body Found in Concrete  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Coroner's investigators broke open a concrete
slab Wednesday and found the entombed body of a little girl
believed to be the missing 3-year-old daughter of a couple arrested
for her killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''A female child was encased in concrete. There's decomposition
so identity can't immediately be confirmed,'' coroner's office
spokesman Scott Carrier said.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Foster and his girlfriend, Rakiesha Scott, both 22, were
arrested Tuesday and booked for investigation of murder, Deputy
David Cervantes said. They were held without bail.
</P>
<P>
   The county Sheriff's Department did not identify the girl.
</P>
<P>
   ''The information we have was that about four or five months ago
a body was placed in the trunk in a box and that box was
subsequently filled with cement,'' Lt. Ray Peavey said.
</P>
<P>
   The abandoned car holding the concrete-filled box had been
covered up and parked for months behind the Athens Park home of
Foster's father.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies were tipped about the concrete tomb Tuesday afternoon
by the child's grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ''My main thing is that there was a little girl out there who
deserves to be buried, not to be embedded in a piece of concrete,''
said Bill Foster, father of the man in custody.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Foster said his son told him Saturday that the
couple's daughter died several months ago after an accident in the
bathroom. There were no other details about the death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
