<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Works On Kosovo, Colombia Bill  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top lawmakers edged Wednesday toward
completing an emergency package financing Colombia's war against
drug producers, U.S. troops in Kosovo and rebuilding from fires,
storms and other disasters at home.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the House and Senate Appropriations committees met
throughout the day, and were said to be close to brokering a
compromise on a bill that President Clinton has wanted passed since
the beginning of the year. Top Republicans hope to push the measure
through Congress and send it to Clinton by Friday, when lawmakers
plan to begin their weeklong Fourth of July recess.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,
said the bill would probably total about $11 billion -- more than
double the $5.2 billion Clinton initially proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the daylong, closed-door wrangling over the measure's final
shape, lawmakers scrambled to carve out money for their own
districts. Participants said that as part of the final package, the
House and Senate would each get a $100 million kitty -- perhaps a
bit more -- for various lawmakers' projects.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'd be surprised how many emergencies you can discover,''
Stevens joked to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Final details remained obscure. But participants speaking on
condition of anonymity said the package was likely to include about
$30 million for a convention center in the Youngstown, Ohio,
district of maverick Rep. James Traficant, D-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   They said GOP lawmakers had apportioned the money to Traficant,
who during the day spoke out against fellow Democrats for walking
out of the House chamber during debate over prescription drug
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was also said to include $468 million for the Coast
Guard to purchase six C-130 transport planes.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young,
R-Fla., said the measure would include $1.3 billion to help
Colombia's embattled government fight drug traffickers who control
broad swaths of the country, along with their leftist guerrilla and
right-wing paramilitary allies. Included is money for purchasing
helicopters and other supplies and training Colombian troops.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a victory for Clinton and House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., who have pushed for the aid as a way to combat
drug use in the United States. Colombia supplies most of the
cocaine used in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Though final numbers could shift, participants said the
compromise would also include $2.05 billion to repay the Pentagon
for the costs of 5,700 American troops serving with the NATO
peacekeeping team in Kosovo, plus more than $4 billion more for
other Pentagon programs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there was at least $660 million for rebuilding from
the government-set fires that ravaged Los Alamos, N.M., and $250
million to help North Carolina and other states recover from last
September's Hurricane Floyd and other agricultural problems.
</P>
<P>
   Still unresolved was whether to include compromise language
struck Tuesday that would lift the four-decade-old U.S. food
embargo against Cuba. There is strong opposition to that deal among
some senators, and Young indicated it might be left for inclusion
in some later bill.
</P>
<P>
   Aides and lawmakers had said earlier that to keep the bill
acceptable to Clinton, they would avoid including controversial
provisions changing laws.
</P>
<P>
   They said they would therefore omit a provision pushed by
Schering-Plough Corp. to win an extension of its patent for
Claritin, the popular and profitable allergy drug. Also left off
the bill was language by Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., aimed at
extending a lucrative patent his alma mater, Columbia University,
has on a process its scientists invented for making some widely
sold biotechnology drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those measures could end up on other bills.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved $13 billion in March, mostly by adding extra
money for the Pentagon, while the Senate approved roughly $9
billion last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 2021 </TRAILER>
