<HEADLINE> Suspected Spy Pleads Innocent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A retired Army reserve colonel considered the
highest-ranking military officer ever arrested for espionage
pleaded innocent to the charge Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   George Trofimoff, 73, said nothing during a brief court
appearance. His attorney, Daniel Hernandez, spoke for him.
</P>
<P>
   Trofimoff is a former civilian chief of the United States Army
Element of the Joint Interrogation Center in Nuremberg, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Judge Elizabeth A. Jenkins set a tentative trial
date for Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Walter Furr said the government
needs additional time to obtain legal assistance from Germany and
Austria to prepare its case.
</P>
<P>
   Trofimoff was indicted June 14 by a grand jury on a single
espionage charge and arrested the same day.
</P>
<P>
   He is being held in the Hillsborough County Jail without bail.
</P>
<P>
   As civilian chief of the interrogation center from 1969 to 1994,
Trofimoff had access to top-secret information the U.S. obtained
from Soviet defectors. The indictment accuses him of photographing
documents from secured files and passing them on to KGB agents.
</P>
</TEXT>
