<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-28 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cubans Welcome Elian Gonzalez  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cubans obeyed requests not to go overboard in
welcoming home Elian Gonzalez, who received an enthusiastic but
restrained reception -- with Cuban leader Fidel Castro noticeably
absent -- when he returned to his communist homeland on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred schoolchildren from Elian's hometown of Cardenas
cheered and waved small red, white and blue Cuban flags as Elian
appeared at the door of the plane minutes after it landed in
Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Alarcon, president of Cuba's National Assembly, was the
highest ranking Cuban official on hand to greet the 6-year-old, his
family and his schoolmates upon their arrival Wednesday night, the
government said in a statement read on state television.
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon has served as a key adviser to Elian's father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, during the protracted custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation that Castro -- who had launched a
national campaign that included numerous mass demonstrations across
the island to press for the boy's return -- would greet the boy, but
the Cuban leader was nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be no official reception nor will there be a mass
mobilization,'' said the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Another government statement urged citizens ''not to rush out
into the streets.'' Such behavior, it said ''would not be the most
correct and convenient in this chapter of our fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cubans were thrilled that Elian had finally come home.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he took off, we all had goose bumps,'' said airport
worker Gisela Diazo, who watched the live televised takeoff. ''We
are all crazy for Elian!''
</P>
<P>
   Castro has said all along that no major homecoming would be
planned for Elian, who he has characterized as a ''boy hero'' and
''symbolic child.'' The idea has been to cause Elian as little
trauma as possible and speed his return to a normal life in his
native country.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's friends in his hometown of Cardenas, a port city east of
Havana, traveled to the Cuban capital to greet Elian, residents
told journalists. The government statement said a small group of
Elian's first-grade classmates was to meet him at the airport. The
boy would then spend an hour with his classmates, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven buses filled with 200-300 children of varying ages
arrived at the airport Wednesday night about an hour before the boy
was scheduled to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was to stay with his family and classmates for two or
three weeks in Havana at a specially prepared boarding school
before returning to Cardenas, where he was born and raised.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans learned on state television and radio that Elian was
headed home after the U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear the appeal
of the Miami relatives, who were seeking to keep Elian in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now more than ever, our population must behave with the most
dignity, serenity and discipline,'' the statement said. ''Let us
remember that at all times, our fight has just begun and that a
long road before us still remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro has said that even after Elian returns, Cubans must not
take a moment's rest in demanding an end to the four-decade-old
U.S. embargo on the island and American policies that allow Cubans
who reach U.S. soil to remain.
</P>
<P>
   The muted reaction by Cubans appeared to be part of a determined
effort by the government to make Elian's return as low-key as
possible in contrast to what government officials have called the
''circus'' that surrounded much of his life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wait with tranquility the triumph of justice and the end of
the kidnapping,'' ran a headline Wednesday in Granma, the official
daily of Cuba's Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, Castro promised there would be no street
celebrations, no parades when the boy returns -- despite a national
campaign in Cuba that put Elian's face on billboards, placards and
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over Elian began in late November when the child was
rescued off the Florida coast. His mother and 10 other people
drowned when their boat sank en route from Cuba to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was turned over to his Miami relatives, who began fighting
to keep him with them. The boy's father fought to have the child
returned to Cuba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 2040 </TRAILER>
