<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Disclosure Bill Considered  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Overcoming Republican opposition, legislation
requiring secretive groups to disclose their donors was moving
toward approval in the Senate, which is now poised to send
President Clinton the first piece of campaign finance legislation
since he took office.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've finally made a crack in the wall that everyone said we
couldn't crack,'' said Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis. ''We have
forced members of Congress to face what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, approved by an overwhelming vote in the House,
would require tax-exempt groups that register under the newly
popular section 527 of the tax code to say who is paying for their
political activities, including TV ads and other attempts to
influence elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate opened debate Wednesday night, with a vote planned on
the measure Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Section 527 has been in the tax code since 1975, but only
recently has it become the vehicle of choice for donors who want to
remain secret.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance experts call it a massive loophole that is
undermining one of the pillars of Watergate reforms -- disclosure of
donors. Opponents say it encourages more people to participate in
the political process.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation has already passed the Senate once, as an
amendment to the defense spending bill. The agreement reached
Wednesday would remove the language from the spending bill and
allow for a short debate, followed by an up-or-down vote on the
House bill.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is ready to sign it, eager to shine light on
what he called ''those mysterious interest groups whose financial
backers are cloaked in secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate GOP leaders have fought the measure, but they lost one
vote already, 57-42, and the momentum grew with the strong House
vote early Wednesday morning. House GOP leaders initially fought
the legislation but in the end, most of them voted for it and the
bill passed 385-39.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a great victory that will give us substantial momentum
for broader campaign finance reform,'' Feingold said.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said that Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott pushed for
an agreement that bar Feingold and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., from
pushing other campaign finance legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We rejected out of hand,'' Feingold said. ''This is about
momentum to do more if possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would require disclosure of groups that organize
under section 527 of the tax code, which allows tax-exempt groups
to engage in unlimited political activity, including campaign-style
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   It was designed for political parties and political action
committees, who already report their activities to the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But section 527 has become popular with groups across the
political spectrum who disclose their spending and donors to no
one. They avoid the FEC by steering clear of words like ''elect''
and ''vote for,'' claiming that they are engaged in issues not
electioneering.
</P>
<P>
   The bill covers any 527 group that raises at least $25,000 a
year. It requires those that do not already report to the Federal
Election Commission to report to the Internal Revenue Service,
which will make the reports public. They would have to report
contributions of $200 or more and spending of $500 or more.
</P>
<P>
   And within 24 hours of organizing, they must notify the IRS of
their existence.
</P>
<P>
   Using a 527, a pair of Texas brothers ran $2.5 million in ads
praising Texas Gov. George W. Bush and attacking McCain in the days
before a crucial GOP primary election. Another 527 with ties to
House Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, is working to raise $25 million to
help a variety of Republicans running for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the oldest 527s is the Sierra Club, which is running
an $8 million campaign boosting Democrats running for Congress and
attacking Bush's record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the disclosure measure note that every day of
delay allows groups to collect more secret cash. Even if a bill
does become law, groups will not have to disclose the names of
anyone who donates money before the legislation is signed.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 4762.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Congress: http://www.thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-28-00 2051 </TRAILER>
