<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, June 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Gonzalez Arrives in Cuba
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- About 800 children from Elian Gonzalez' elementary school
cheered as the 6-year-old boy returned to his native Cuba this evening, bringing
to a close an international custody battle laced with Cold War passions. Elian
and his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, stepped off the plane from the United
States and were immediately embraced by the boy's grandmothers and other
relatives on the tarmac at a small airport in the Cuban capital. Elian's return
ended the seven-month national campaign to bring the boy home from the United
States, where his Miami relatives had fought to keep him.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Archbishop Released
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- A man seeking help on a passport problem and claiming to
have a hand grenade took Archbishop Patrick Flores hostage in his office for
nine hours before releasing him tonight. The Roman Catholic archbishop appeared
to be unharmed as he was escorted out of his office by police and placed on a
stretcher. The suspect was led out in handcuffs. Gabriel Trevino, a police
department spokesman, said police had been negotiating with the suspect through
the day, and said negotiator could hear Flores in the background while they
talked to the suspect. The archbishop's secretary, Myrtle Sanchez, was also held
for about three hours but was freed unharmed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IBM Announces New Supercomputer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- IBM announced today it has built the most powerful
supercomputer in the world, able to perform 12.3 trillion operations per second,
three times faster than the next-fastest computer. An earlier version proved
capable of defeating the world's greatest chess player in a 1997 tournament. The
latest machine is intended to continue the advance toward matching and
eventually surpassing the computing capacity of the human brain. The computer,
called Advanced Strategic Computing Initiative White, or ASCI White, covers
9,920 square feet of floor space, equal to two NBA basketball courts, and weighs
106 tons.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Upholds 'Partial-Birth' Abortion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today limited states' power to ban
so-called ''partial-birth'' abortions, a 5-4 ruling that escalated the bitter,
decades-old debate over women's right to end their pregnancies. Closing out its
1999-2000 term with some of the most divisive rulings in years, the court struck
down Nebraska's partial-birth abortion law as an ''undue burden'' on women's
rights. The court also ruled that the Boy Scouts can bar homosexuals from
serving as troop leaders. The decision may also let the 6.2-million member
organization reject gay boys as members.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton: Scandals Won't Hurt Gore
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rushing to Al Gore's defense, President Clinton brushed
off his tumbling poll numbers, a possible campaign finance investigation and the
stigma of ''bogus'' scandals to say today, ''It's still more likely than not
that he will win'' over George W. Bush. Clinton combined his measured assessment
of Gore's prospects with lavish praise of his vice president. ''Nobody has ever
done as much for America as vice president as Al Gore has,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Campaign Coming To Close in Mexico
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOMA BLANCA, Mexico (AP) -- Mexico's presidential candidates made last-minute
appeals to voters Wednesday -- with one even coming to a rally on horseback --
the final day of an increasingly bitter campaign ahead of Sunday's tightly
fought election. Polls show conservative opposition candidate Vicente Fox in a
dead heat with Francisco Labastida of the Institutional Revolutionary Party,
which has governed Mexico since 1929.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Davidians Testify About Conditions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WACO, Texas (AP) -- Branch Davidians believed sect leader David Koresh was a
manifestation of ''God, made flesh,'' and if God asked someone do to something,
it would not be considered a sin, a survivor of the 1993 siege testified today.
''We believe that God was speaking through him,'' said Clive Doyle, a plaintiff
in the $675 million wrongful death lawsuit against the government. Some 80
members died April 19, 1993, as the 51-day standoff with the government came to
a fatal end.
</P>
