<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investigators Rule Out E. coli  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A coroner ruled Wednesday that E. coli had
nothing to do with five of 21 deaths considered possibly linked to
the intestinal bacteria that contaminated a rural town's drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Young, the Ontario chief coroner, said he expected a
similar finding for some of the other deaths being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said seven people died and an estimated 2,000
people were sickened by the bacteria that showed up in the water
supply of Walkerton, 90 miles west of Toronto, in May.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had enough information on these five cases to determine
that E. Coli was not the cause of death,'' Young said in a
statement. ''It is likely that some of the remaining 16 cases will
ultimately be eliminated as caused by E. coli. However, further
information is necessary before this can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the worst known E. coli contamination in North America,
and residents of Walkerton face at least four more weeks without
their normal water supply as authorities try to clean the system
and determine the source of the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jim Cairns, the Ontario deputy chief coroner, said people
still could get sick if they fail to take proper precautions with
the town water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Four investigations of the E. coli contamination have started or
been announced -- by Ontario Provincial Police, health and
environment officials, the coroner's office, and a public inquiry
to be conducted by a judge.
</P>
<P>
   The province has taken over the Walkerton water utility.
Officials also are studying the town's main wells to try to find
the source of the bacteria, often spread through human and animal
feces.
</P>
<P>
   Walkerton officials have said the local water utility knew of
the contamination before a boil-water order was issued May 21. Some
of the deaths under investigation for a possible link to the E.
coli contamination occurred weeks before the boil order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
